				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 19: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Who scatter clouds about the sky, away over the billowy sea:
					-
					-
						O Agni, with those Maruts come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 19: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Who with their bright beams spread them forth over the ocean in their might
					-
					-
						O Agni, with those Maruts come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 19: Verse 9
				-
					-
						For thee, to be thine early draught, I pour the Soma-mingled meath:
					-
					-
						O Agni, with the Maruts come.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 20
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 20: Verse 1
				-
					-
						FOR the Celestial Race this song of praise which gives wealth lavishly
					-
					-
						Was made by singers with their lips.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 20: Verse 2
				-
					-
						They who for Indra, with their mind, formed horses harnessed by a word,
					-
					-
						Attained by works to sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 20: Verse 3
				-
					-
						They for the two Nasatyas wrought a light car moving every way:
					-
					-
						They formed a nectar-yielding cow.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 20: Verse 4
				-
					-
						The Rbhus with effectual prayers, honest, with constant labour, made
					-
					-
						Their Sire and Mother young again.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 20: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Together came your gladdening drops with Indra by the Maruts girt,
					-
					-
						With the Adityas, with the Kings.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 20: Verse 6
				-
					-
						The sacrificial ladle, wrought newly by the God Tvastar's hand--
					-
					-
						Four ladles have ye made thereof.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 20: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Vouchsafe us wealth, to him who pours thrice seven libations, yea, to each
					-
					-
						Give wealth, pleased with our eulogies.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 20: Verse 8
				-
					-
						As ministering Priests they held, by pious acts they won themselves,
					-
					-
						A share in sacrifice with Gods.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 21
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 21: Verse 1
				-
					-
						INDRA and Agni I invoke fain are we for their song of praise:
					-
					-
						Chief Soma-drinkers are they both.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 21: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Praise ye, O men, and glorify Indra-Agni in the holy rites:
					-
					-
						Sing praise to them in sacred songs.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 21: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Indra and Agni we invite, the Soma-drinkers, for the fame
					-
					-
						Of Mitra, to the Soma-draught.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 21: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Strong Gods, we bid them come to this libation that stands ready here:
					-
					-
						Indra and Agni, come to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 21: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Indra and Agni, mighty Lords of our assembly, crush the fiends:
					-
					-
						Childless be the devouring ones.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 21: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Watch ye, through this your truthfulness, there in the place of spacious
						view
					-
					-
						Indra and Agni, send us bliss.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 22
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WAKEN the Asvin Pair who yoke their car at early morn: may they
					-
					-
						Approach to drink this Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 2
				-
					-
						We call the Asvins Twain, the Gods borne in a noble car, the best
					-
					-
						Of charioteers, who reach the heavens.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Dropping with honey is your whip, Asvins, and full of pleasantness
					-
					-
						Sprinkle therewith the sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 4
				-
					-
						As ye go thither in your car, not far, O Asvins, is the home
					-
					-
						Of him who offers Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 5
				-
					-
						For my protection I invoke the golden-handed Savitar.
					-
					-
						He knoweth, as a God, the place.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 6
				-
					-
						That he may send us succour, praise the Waters' Offspring Savitar:
					-
					-
						Fain are we for his holy ways.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 7
				-
					-
						We call on him, distributer of wondrous bounty and of wealth,
					-
					-
						On Savitar who looks on men.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Come hither, friends, and seat yourselves Savitar, to be praised by us,
					-
					-
						Giving good gifts, is beautiful.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 9
				-
					-
						O Agni, hither bring to us the willing Spouses of the Gods,
					-
					-
						And Tvastar, to the Soma draught.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Most youthful Agni, hither bring their Spouses, Hotra, Bharati,
					-
					-
						Varutri, Dhisana, for aid.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Spouses of Heroes, Goddesses, with whole wings may they come to us
					-
					-
						With great protection and with aid.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Indrani, Varunani, and Agnayi hither I invite,
					-
					-
						For weal, to drink the Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 13
				-
					-
						May Heaven and Earth, the Mighty Pair, bedew for us our sacrifice,
					-
					-
						And feed us full with nourishments.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Their water rich with fatness, there in the Gandharva's steadfast place,
					-
					-
						The singers taste through sacred songs.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Thornless be thou, O Earth, spread wide before us for a dwelling-place:
					-
					-
						Vouchsafe us shelter broad and sure.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 16
				-
					-
						The Gods be gracious unto us even from the place whence Visnu strode
					-
					-
						Through the seven regions of the earth!
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Through all this world strode Visnu; thrice his foot he planted, and the
						whole
					-
					-
						Was gathered in his footstep's dust.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Visnu, the Guardian, he whom none deceiveth, made three steps; thenceforth
					-
					-
						Establishing his high decrees.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Look ye on Visnu's works, whereby the Friend of Indra, close-allied,
					-
					-
						Hath let his holy ways be seen.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 20
				-
					-
						The princes evermore behold that loftiest place where Visnu is,
					-
					-
						Laid as it were an eye in heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 22: Verse 21
				-
					-
						This, Vishnu's station most sublime, the singers, ever vigilant,
					-
					-
						Lovers of holy song, light up.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 23
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 1
				-
					-
						STRONG are the Somas; come thou nigh; these juices have been mixt with
						milk:
					-
					-
						Drink, Vayu, the presented draughts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Both Deities who touch the heaven, Indra and Vayu we invoke
					-
					-
						To drink of this our soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 3
				-
					-
						The singers' for their aid, invoke Indra and Vayu, swift as mind,
					-
					-
						The thousand-eyed, the Lords of thought.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mitra and Varuna, renowned as Gods of consecrated might,
					-
					-
						We call to drink the Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Those who by Law uphold the Law, Lords of the shining light of Law,
					-
					-
						Mitra I call, and Varuna.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Let Varuna be our chief defence, let Mitra guard us with all aids
					-
					-
						Both make us rich exceedingly.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Indra, by Maruts girt, we call to drink the Soma juice: may he
					-
					-
						Sate him in union with his troop.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Gods, Marut hosts whom Indra leads, distributers of Pusan's gifts,
					-
					-
						Hearken ye all unto my cry.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 9
				-
					-
						With conquering Indra for ally, strike Vrtra down, ye bounteous Gods
					-
					-
						Let not the wicked master us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 10
				-
					-
						We call the Universal Gods, and Maruts to the Soma draught,
					-
					-
						For passing strong are Prsni's Sons.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Fierce comes the Maruts' thundering voice, like that of conquerors, when ye
						go
					-
					-
						Forward to victory, O Men.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Born of the laughing lightning. may the Maruts guard us everywhere
					-
					-
						May they be gracious unto Us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Like some lost animal, drive to us, bright Pusan, him who bears up heaven,
					-
					-
						Resting on many-coloured grass.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Pusan the Bright has found the King, concealed and hidden in a cave,
					-
					-
						Who rests on grass of many hues.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 15
				-
					-
						And may he. duly bring to me the six bound closely, through these drops,
					-
					-
						As one who ploughs with steers brings corn.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Along their paths the Mothers go, Sisters of priestly ministrants,
					-
					-
						Mingling their sweetness with the milk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 17
				-
					-
						May Waters gathered near the Sun, and those wherewith the Sun is joined,
					-
					-
						Speed forth this sacrifice of ours.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 18
				-
					-
						I call the Waters, Goddesses, wherein our cattle quench their thirst;
					-
					-
						Oblations to the Streams be given.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Amrit is in the Waters in the Waters there is healing balm
					-
					-
						Be swift, ye Gods, to give them praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Within the Waters--Soma thus hath told me--dwell all balms that heal,
					-
					-
						And Agni, he who blesseth all. The Waters hold all medicines.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 21
				-
					-
						O Waters, teem with medicine to keep my body safe from harm,
					-
					-
						So that I long may see the Sun.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Whatever sin is found in me, whatever evil I have wrought.
					-
					-
						If I have lied or falsely sworn, Waters, remove it far from me.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 23
				-
					-
						The Waters I this day have sought, and to their moisture have we come:
					-
					-
						O Agni, rich in milk, come thou, and with thy splendour cover me.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 23: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Fill me with splendour, Agni; give offspring and length of days; the Gods
					-
					-
						Shall know me even as I am, and Indra with the Rsis, know.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 24
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WHO now is he, what God among Immortals, of whose auspicious name we may
						bethink us?
					-
					-
						Who shall to mighty Aditi restore us, that I may see my Father and my
						Mother?
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Agni the God the first among the Immortals,--of his auspicious name let us
						bethink us.
					-
					-
						He shall to mighty Aditi restore us, that I may see my Father and my
						Mother.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 3
				-
					-
						To thee, O Savitar, the Lord of precious things, who helpest us
					-
					-
						Continually, for our share we come-
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Wealth, highly lauded ere reproach hath fallen on it, which is laid,
					-
					-
						Free from all hatred, in thy hands
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Through thy protection may we come to even the height of affluence
					-
					-
						Which Bhaga hath dealt out to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Ne'er have those birds that fly through air attained to thy high dominion
						or thy might or spirit;
					-
					-
						Nor these the waters that flow on for ever, nor hills, abaters of the
						wind's wild fury.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Varuna, King, of hallowed might, sustaineth erect the Tree's stem in the
						baseless region.
					-
					-
						Its rays, whose root is high above, stream downward. Deep may they sink
						within us, and be hidden.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 8
				-
					-
						King Varuna hath made a spacious pathway, a pathway for the Sun wherein to
						travel.
					-
					-
						Where no way was he made him set his footstep, and warned afar whate'er
						afflicts the spirit.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 9
				-
					-
						A hundred balms are thine, O King, a thousand; deep and wide-reaching also
						be thy favours.
					-
					-
						Far from us, far away drive thou Destruction. Put from us e'en the sin we
						have committed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Whither by day depart the constellations that shine at night, set high in
						heaven above us?
					-
					-
						Varuna's holy laws remain unweakened, and through the night the Moon moves
						on in splendor
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 11
				-
					-
						I ask this of thee with my prayer adoring; thy worshipper craves this with
						his oblation.
					-
					-
						Varuna, stay thou here and be not angry; steal not our life from us, O thou
						Wide-Ruler.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Nightly and daily this one thing they tell me, this too the thought of mine
						own heart repeateth.
					-
					-
						May he to whom prayed fettered Sunahsepa, may he the Sovran Varuna release
						us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Bound to three pillars captured Sunahsepa thus to the Aditya made his
						supplication.
					-
					-
						Him may the Sovran Varuna deliver, wise, ne'er deceived, loosen the bonds
						that bind him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 14
				-
					-
						With bending down, oblations, sacrifices, O Varuna, we deprecate thine
						anger:
					-
					-
						Wise Asura, thou King of wide dominion, loosen the bonds of sins by us
						committed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 24: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Loosen the bonds, O Varuna, that hold me, loosen the bonds above, between,
						and under.
					-
					-
						So in thy holy law may we made sinless belong to Aditi, O thou Aditya.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 25
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WHATEVER law of thine, O God, O Varuna, as we are men,
					-
					-
						Day after day we violate.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 2
				-
					-
						give us not as a prey to death, to be destroyed by thee in wrath,
					-
					-
						To thy fierce anger when displeased.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 3
				-
					-
						To gain thy mercy, Varuna, with hymns we bind thy heart, as binds
					-
					-
						The charioteer his tethered horse.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 4
				-
					-
						They flee from me dispirited, bent only on obtaining wealths
					-
					-
						As to their nests the birds of air.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 5
				-
					-
						When shall we bring, to be appeased, the Hero, Lord of warrior might,
					-
					-
						Him, the far-seeing Varuna?
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 6
				-
					-
						This, this with joy they both accept in common: never do they fail
					-
					-
						The ever-faithful worshipper.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 7
				-
					-
						He knows the path of birds that fly through heaven, and, Sovran of the sea,
					-
					-
						He knows the ships that are thereon.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 8
				-
					-
						True to his holy law, he knows the twelve moons with their progeny:
					-
					-
						He knows the moon of later birth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 9
				-
					-
						He knows the pathway of the wind, the spreading, high, and mighty wind:
					-
					-
						He knows the Gods who dwell above.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Varuna, true to holy law, sits down among his people; he,
					-
					-
						Most wise, sits there to govern all.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 11
				-
					-
						From thence percerving he beholds all wondrous things, both what hath been,
					-
					-
						And what hereafter will be done.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 12
				-
					-
						May that Aditya, very wise, make fair paths for us all our days:
					-
					-
						May he prolong our lives for us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Varuna, wearing golden mail, hath clad him in a shining robe.
					-
					-
						His spies are seated found about.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 14
				-
					-
						The God whom enemies threaten not, nor those who tyrannize o'er men,
					-
					-
						Nor those whose minds are bent on wrong.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 15
				-
					-
						He who gives glory to mankind, not glory that is incomplete,
					-
					-
						To our own bodies giving it.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Yearning for the wide-seeing One, my thoughts move onward unto him,
					-
					-
						As kine unto their pastures move.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Once more together let us speak, because my meath is brought: priest-like
					-
					-
						Thou eatest what is dear to thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 25: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Now saw I him whom all may see, I saw his car above the earth:
					-
					-
						He hath accepted these my songs.
