					-
					-
						And offer this our sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 26: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Sit ever to be chosen, as our Priest, most youthful, through our hymns,
					-
					-
						O Agni, through our heavenly word.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 26: Verse 3
				-
					-
						For here a Father for his son, Kinsman for kinsman worshippeth,
					-
					-
						And Friend, choice-worthy, for his friend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 26: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Here let the foe-destroyers sit, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman,
					-
					-
						Like men, upon our sacred grass.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 26: Verse 5
				-
					-
						O ancient Herald, be thou glad in this our rite and fellowship:
					-
					-
						Hearken thou well to these our songs.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 26: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Whate'er in this perpetual course we sacrifice to God and God,
					-
					-
						That gift is offered up in thee
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 26: Verse 7
				-
					-
						May he be our dear household Lord, Priest, pleasant and, choice-worthy may
					-
					-
						We, with bright fires, be dear to him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 26: Verse 8
				-
					-
						The Gods, adored with brilliant fires. have granted precious wealth to us
					-
					-
						So, with bright fires, we pray to thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 26: Verse 9
				-
					-
						And, O Immortal One, so may the eulogies of mortal men
					-
					-
						Belong to us and thee alike.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 26: Verse 10
				-
					-
						With all thy fires, O Agni, find pleasure in this our sacrifice,
					-
					-
						And this our speech, O Son of Strength.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 27
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WITH worship will I glorify thee, Agni, like a long-tailed steed,
					-
					-
						Imperial Lord of sacred rites.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 2
				-
					-
						May the far-striding Son of Strength, bringer of great felicity,
					-
					-
						Who pours his gifts like rain, be ours.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Lord of all life, from near; from far, do thou, O Agni evermore
					-
					-
						Protect us from the sinful man.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 4
				-
					-
						O Agni, graciously announce this our oblation to the Gods,
					-
					-
						And this our newest song of praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Give us a share of strength most high, a share of strength that is below,
					-
					-
						A share of strength that is between.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Thou dealest gifts, resplendent One; nigh, as with waves of Sindhu, thou
					-
					-
						Swift streamest to the worshipper.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 7
				-
					-
						That man is lord of endless strength whom thou protectest in the fight,
					-
					-
						Agni, or urgest to the fray.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Him, whosoever he may be, no man may vanquish, mighty One:
					-
					-
						Nay, very glorious power is his.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 9
				-
					-
						May he who dwells with all mankind bear us with war-steeds through the
						fight,
					-
					-
						And with the singers win the spoil.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Help, thou who knowest lauds, this work, this eulogy to Rudra, him
					-
					-
						Adorable in every house.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 11
				-
					-
						May this our God, great, limitless, smoke-bannered excellently bright,
					-
					-
						Urge us to strength and holy thought.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Like some rich Lord of men may he, Agni the banner of the Gods,
					-
					-
						Refulgent, hear us through our lauds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 27: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Glory to Gods, the mighty and the lesser glory to Gods the younger and the
						elder!
					-
					-
						Let us, if we have power, pay the God worship: no better prayer than this,
						ye Gods, acknowledge.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 28
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 28: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THERE where the broad-based stone raised on high to press the juices out,
					-
					-
						O Indra, drink with eager thirst the droppings which the mortar sheds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 28: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Where, like broad hips, to hold the juice the platters of the press are
						laid,
					-
					-
						O Indra, drink with eager thirst the droppings which the mortar sheds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 28: Verse 3
				-
					-
						There where the woman marks and leans the pestle's constant rise and fall,
					-
					-
						O Indra, drink with eager thirst the droppings which the mortar sheds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 28: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Where, as with reins to guide a horse, they bind the churning-staff with
						cords,
					-
					-
						O Indra, drink with eager thirst the droppings which the mortar sheds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 28: Verse 5
				-
					-
						If of a truth in every house, O Mortar thou art set for work,
					-
					-
						Here give thou forth thy clearest sound, loud as the drum of conquerors.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 28: Verse 6
				-
					-
						O Sovran of the Forest, as the wind blows soft in front of thee,
					-
					-
						Mortar, for Indra press thou forth the Soma juice that he may drink.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 28: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Best strength-givers, ye stretch wide jaws, O Sacrificial Implements,
					-
					-
						Like two bay horses champing herbs.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 28: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Ye Sovrans of the Forest, both swift, with swift pressers press to-day
					-
					-
						Sweet Soma juice for Indra's drink.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 28: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Take up in beakers what remains: the Soma on the filter pour,
					-
					-
						and on the ox-hide set the dregs.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 29
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 29: Verse 1
				-
					-
						O SOMA DRINKER, ever true, utterly hopeless though we be,
					-
					-
						Do thou, O Indra, give us hope of beauteous horses and of kine,
					-
					-
						In thousands, O most wealthy One.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 29: Verse 2
				-
					-
						O Lord of Strength, whose jaws are strong, great deeds are thine, the
						powerful:
					-
					-
						Do thou, O Indra, give us hope of beauteous horses and of kine,
					-
					-
						In thousands, O most wealthy One.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 29: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Lull thou asleep, to wake no more, the pair who on each other look
					-
					-
						Do thou, O Indra, give us hope of beauteous horses and of kine,
					-
					-
						In thousands, O most wealthy One.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 29: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Hero, let hostile spirits sleep, and every gentler genius wake:
					-
					-
						Do thou, O Indra, give us hope of beauteous horses and of kine,
					-
					-
						In thousands, O most wealthy One.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 29: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Destroy this ass, O Indra, who in tones discordant brays to thee:
					-
					-
						Do thou, O Indra, give us hope of beauteous horses and of kine,
					-
					-
						In thousands, O most wealthy One.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 29: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Far distant on the forest fall the tempest in a circling course!
					-
					-
						Do thou, O Indra, give us hope of beauteous horses and of kine,
					-
					-
						In thousands, O most wealthy One.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 29: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Slay each reviler, and destroy him who in secret injures us:
					-
					-
						Do thou, O Indra, give us hope of beauteous horses and of kine
					-
					-
						In thousands, O most wealthy One.
					-
			-
				Mandala 1: Hymn 30
			-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WE seeking strength with Soma-drops fill full your Indra like a well,
					-
					-
						Most liberal, Lord of Hundred Powers,
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Who lets a hundred of the pure, a thousand of the milk-blent draughts
					-
					-
						Flow, even as down a depth, to him;
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 3
				-
					-
						When for the strong, the rapturous joy he in this manner hath made room
					-
					-
						Within his belly, like the sea.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 4
				-
					-
						This is thine own. Thou drawest near, as turns a pigeon to his mate:
					-
					-
						Thou carest too for this our prayer.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 5
				-
					-
						O Hero, Lord of Bounties, praised in hymns, may power and joyfulness
					-
					-
						Be his who sings the laud to thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Lord of a Hundred Powers, stand up to lend us succour in this fight
					-
					-
						In others too let us agree.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 7
				-
					-
						In every need, in every fray we call as friends to succour us
					-
					-
						Indra the mightiest of all.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 8
				-
					-
						If he will hear us let him come with succour of a thousand kinds,
					-
					-
						And all that strengthens, to our call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 9
				-
					-
						I call him mighty to resist, the Hero of our ancient home,
					-
					-
						Thee whom my sire invoked of old.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 10
				-
					-
						We pray to thee, O much-invoked, rich in all precious gifts, O Friend,
					-
					-
						Kind God to those who sing thy praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 11
				-
					-
						O Soma-drinker, Thunder-armed, Friend of our lovely-featured dames
					-
					-
						And of our Soma-drinking friends.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Thus, Soma-drinker, may it be; thus, Friend, who wieldest thunder, act
					-
					-
						To aid each wish as we desire.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 13
				-
					-
						With Indra splendid feasts be ours, rich in all strengthening things
						wherewith,
					-
					-
						Wealthy in food, we may rejoice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Like thee, thyself, the singers' Friend, thou movest, as it were, besought,
					-
					-
						Bold One, the axle of the car.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 15
				-
					-
						That, Satakratu, thou to grace and please thy praisers, as it were,
					-
					-
						Stirrest the axle with thy strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 16
				-
					-
						With champing, neighing loudly-snorting horses Indra hath ever won himself
						great treasures
					-
					-
						A car of gold hath he whose deeds are wondrous received from us, and let us
						too receive it.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Come, Asvins, with enduring strength wealthy in horses and in kine,
					-
					-
						And gold, O ye of wondrous deeds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Your chariot yoked for both alike, immortal, ye of mighty acts,
					-
					-
						Travels, O Asvins, in the sea.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 19
				-
					-
						High on the forehead of the Bull one chariot wheel ye ever keep,
					-
					-
						The other round the sky revolves.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 20
				-
					-
						What mortal, O immortal Dawn, enjoyeth thee? Where lovest thou?
					-
					-
						To whom, O radiant, dost thou go?
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 21
				-
					-
						For we have had thee in our thoughts whether anear or far away,
					-
					-
						Red-hued and like a dappled mare.
					-
				-
					Mandala 1: Hymn 30: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Hither, O Daughter of the Sky, come thou with these thy strengthenings,
					-
					-
						And send thou riches down to us.
