				-
					-
						Now, too, the princes shall obtain excellent riches by our lips.
					-
					-
						Protect us for our welfare: lend thy succour, O thou Son of Strength. Be
						near in fight to prosper us.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 18
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 18: Verse 1
				-
					-
						AT dawn let: Agni, much-beloved guest of the house, be glorified;
					-
					-
						Immortal who delights in all oblations brought by mortal men.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 18: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For Dvita who receives through wealth of native strength maimed offerings,
					-
					-
						Thy praiser even gains at once the Soma-drops, Immortal Gods!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 18: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Nobles, with song I call that car of yours that shines with lengthened
						life,
					-
					-
						For, God who givest steeds! that car hither and thither goes unharmed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 18: Verse 4
				-
					-
						They who have varied ways of thought, who guard, the lauds within their
						lips,
					-
					-
						And strew the grass before the light, have decked themselves with high
						renown.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 18: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Immortal Agni, give the chiefs, heroes who institute the rite,
					-
					-
						Heroes' illustrious, lofty fame, who at the synod met for praise presented
						me with fifty steeds.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 19
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 19: Verse 1
				-
					-
						ONE state begets another state: husk is made visible from husk:
					-
					-
						Within his Mother's side he speaks.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 19: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Discerning, have they offered gifts: they guard the strength that never
						wastes.
					-
					-
						To a strong fort have they pressed in.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 19: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Svaitreya's people, all his men, have gloriously increased in might.
					-
					-
						A gold chain Brhaduktha wears, as, through this Soma, seeking spoil.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 19: Verse 4
				-
					-
						I bring, as 'twere, the longed-for milk, the dear milk of the Sister-Pair.
					-
					-
						Like to a caldron filled with food is he, unconquered, conquering all.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 19: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Beam of light, come to us in sportive fashion, finding thyself close to the
						wind that fans thee.
					-
					-
						These flames of his are wasting flames, like arrows keen-pointed,
						sharpened, on his breast.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 20
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 20: Verse 1
				-
					-
						AGNI, best winner of the spoil, cause us to praise before the Gods
					-
					-
						As our associate meet for lauds, wealth which thou verily deemest wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 20: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Agni, the great who ward not off the anger of thy power and might
					-
					-
						Stir up the wrath and hatred due to one who holds an alien creed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 20: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Thee, Agni, would we choose as Priest, the perfecter of strength and skill;
					-
					-
						We who bring sacred food invoke with song thee Chief at holy rites.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 20: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Here as is needful for thine aid we toil, O Conqueror, day by day,
					-
					-
						For wealth, for Law. May we rejoice, Most Wise One! at the feast, with
						kine, rejoice, with heroes, at the feast.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 21
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 21: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WE stablish thee as Manus used, as Manus used we kindle thee.
					-
					-
						Like Manus, for the pious man , Angiras, Agni, worship Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 21: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For well, O Agni, art thou pleased when thou art kindled mid mankind.
					-
					-
						Straight go the ladles unto thee, thou highborn God whose food is oil.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 21: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Thee have all Gods of one accord established as their messenger.
					-
					-
						Serving at sacrifices men adore thee as a God, O Sage.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 21: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Let mortal man adore your God, Agni, with worship due to Gods.
					-
					-
						Shine forth enkindled, Radiant One. Sit in the chamber of the Law, sit in
						the chamber of the food.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 22
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 22: Verse 1
				-
					-
						LIKE Atri, Visvasaman! sing to him of purifying light,
					-
					-
						Who must be praised in holy rites, the Priest most welcome in the house.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 22: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Set Jatavedas in his place, Agni the God and Minister.
					-
					-
						Let sacrifice proceed to-day duly, comprising all the Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 22: Verse 3
				-
					-
						All mortals come to thee for aid, the God of most observant mind.
					-
					-
						Of thine excelling favour we bethink us as we long for it.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 22: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mark with attention this our speech, O Agni, thou victorious One.
					-
					-
						Thee, Strong-jawed! as the homestead's Lord, the Atris with their lauds
						exalt, the Atris beautify with songs.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 23
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 23: Verse 1
				-
					-
						By thy fair splendour's mighty power, O Agni, bring victorious wealth,
					-
					-
						Wealth that o'ercometh all mankind, and, near us, conquereth in fight.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 23: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Victorious Agni, bring to us the wealth that vanquisheth in war;
					-
					-
						For thou art wonderful and true, giver of strength in herds of kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 23: Verse 3
				-
					-
						For all the folk with one accord, whose sacred grass is trimmed and strewn,
					-
					-
						Invite thee to their worship-halls, as a dear Priest, for choicest wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 23: Verse 4
				-
					-
						For he, the God of all men, hath gotten him might that quelleth foes.
					-
					-
						O Agni, in these homes shine forth, bright God! for our prosperity, shine,
						Purifier! splendidly.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 24
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 24: Verse 1
				-
					-
						O AGNI, be our nearest Friend, be thou a kind deliverer and a gracious
						Friend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 24: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Excellent Agni, come thou nigh to us, and give us wealth most splendidly
						renowned.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 24: Verse 3
				-
					-
						So hear us, listen to this call of ours, and keep us far from every sinful
						man.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 24: Verse 4
				-
					-
						To thee then, O Most Bright, O Radiant God, we come with prayer for
						happiness for our friends.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 25
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 25: Verse 1
				-
					-
						I WILL sing near, for grace, your God Agni, for he is good to us.
					-
					-
						Son of the Brands, may he give gifts, and, righteous, save us from the foe.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 25: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For be is true, whpm men of old enkindled, and the Gods themselves,
					-
					-
						The Priest with the delicious tongue, rich with the light of glorious
						beams.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 25: Verse 3
				-
					-
						With wisdom that surpasseth all, with gracious will most excellent,
					-
					-
						O Agni, worthy of our choice, shine wealth on us through hymns of praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 25: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Agni is King, for he extends to mortals and to Gods alike.
					-
					-
						Agni is bearer of our gifts. Worship ye Agni with your thoughts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 25: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Agni gives to the worshipper a son, the best, of mightiest fame,
					-
					-
						Of deep devotion, ne'er subdued, bringer of glory to his sire.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 25: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Agni bestows the hero-lord who conquers with the men in fight.
					-
					-
						Agni bestows the fleet-foot steed, the victor never overcome.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 25: Verse 7
				-
					-
						The mightiest song is Agni's: shine on high, thou who art rich in light.
					-
					-
						Like the Chief Consort of a King, riches and strength proceed -from thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 25: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Resplendent are thy rays of light: loud is thy voice like pressing-stones.
					-
					-
						Yea, of itself thy thunder goes forth like the roaring of the heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 25: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Thus, seeking riches, have we paid homage to Agni Conqueror.
					-
					-
						May he, most wise, as with a ship, carry us over all our foes.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 26
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 26: Verse 1
				-
					-
						O AGNI, Holy and Divine, with splendour and thy pleasant tongue
					-
					-
						Bring hither and adore the Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 26: Verse 2
				-
					-
						We pray thee, thou who droppest oil, bright-rayed! who lookest on the Sun,
					-
					-
						Bring the Gods hither to the feast.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 26: Verse 3
				-
					-
						We have enkindled thee, O Sage, bright caller of the Gods to feast.
					-
					-
						O Agni, great in Sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 26: Verse 4
				-
					-
						O Agni, come with all the Gods, come to our sacrificial gift:
					-
					-
						We choose thee as Invoking Priest.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 26: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Bring, Agni, to the worshipper who pours the juice, heroic strength:
					-
					-
						Sit with the Gods upon the grass.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 26: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Victor of thousands, Agni, thou, enkindled, cherishest the laws,
					-
					-
						Laud-worthy, envoy of the Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 26: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Set Agni Jatavedas down, the bearer of our sacred gifts,
					-
					-
						MostYouthful, God and Minister.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 26: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Duly proceed our sacrifice, comprising all the Gods, to-day:
					-
					-
						Strew holy grass to be their seat.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 26: Verse 9
				-
					-
						So may the Maruts sit thereon, the Asvins, Mitra, Varuna:
					-
					-
						The Gods with all their company.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 27
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 27: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THE Godlike hero, famousest of nobles, hath granted me two oxen with a
						wagon.
					-
					-
						Trvrsan's son Tryaruna hath distinguished himself, Vaisvanara Agni! with
						ten thousands.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 27: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Protect Tryaruna, as thou art waxing strong and art highly praised,
						Vaisvanara Agni!
					-
					-
						Who granteth me a hundred kine and twenty, and two bay horses, good at
						draught, and harnessed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 27: Verse 3
				-
					-
						So Trasadasyu served thee, God Most Youthful, craving thy favour for the
						ninth time, Agni;
					-
					-
						Tryaruya who with attentive spirit accepteth many a song from me the
						mighty.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 27: Verse 4
				-
					-
						He who declares his wish to me, to Asvamedha, to the Prince,
					-
					-
						Pays him who with his verse seeks gain, gives power to him who keeps the
						Law.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 27: Verse 5
				-
					-
						From whom a hundred oxen, all of speckled hue, delight my heart,
					-
					-
						The gifts of Asvamedha, like thrice-mingled draughts of Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 27: Verse 6
				-
					-
						To Asvamedha who bestows a hundred gifts grant hero power,
					-
					-
						O Indra-Agni! lofty rule like the unwasting Sun in heaven.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 28
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 1
				-
					-
						AGNI inflamed hath sent to heaven his lustre: he shines forth widely
						turning unto Morning.
					-
					-
						Eastward the ladle goes that brings all blessing, praising the Godswith
						homage and oblation.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Enkindled, thou art King of the immortal world: him who brings offerings
						thou attendest for his weal.
					-
					-
						He whom thou urgest on makes all possessions his: he sets before thee,
						Agni, gifts that guests may claim.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Show thyself strong for mighty bliss, O Agni, most excellent be thine
						effulgent splendours.
					-
					-
						Make easy to maintain our household lordship, and overcome the might of
						those who hate us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Thy glory, Agni, I adore, kindled, exalted in thy strength.
					-
					-
						A Steer of brilliant splendour, thou art lighted well at sacred rites.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Agni, invoked and kindled, serve the Gods, thou skilled in sacrifice:
					-
					-
						For thou art bearer of our gifts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 28: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Invoke and worship Agni while the sacrificial rite proceeds:
					-
					-
						For offering-bearer choose ye him.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 29
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 1
				-
					-
						MAN'S worship of the Gods hath three great lustres, and three celestial
						lights have they established
					-
					-
						The Maruts gifted with pure strength adore thee, for thou, O Indra, art
						their sapient Rsi.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 2
				-
					-
						What time the Maruts sang their song to Indra, joyous when he had drunk of
						Soma juices,
					-
					-
						He grasped his thunderbolt to slay the Dragon, and loosed, that they might
						flow, the youthful Waters.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 3
				-
					-
						And, O ye Brahmans, Maruts, so may Indra drink draughts of this my
						carefully pressed Sorna;
					-
					-
						For this oblation found for man the cattle, and Indra, having quaffed it,
						slew the Dragon.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Then heaven and earth he sundered and supported: wrapped even in these he
						struck the Beast with terror.
					-
					-
						So Indra forced the Engulfer to disgorgement, and slew the Danava. panting
						against him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Thus all the Gods, O Maghavan, delivered to thee of their free will the
						draught of Soma;
					-
					-
						When thou for Etasa didst cause to tarry the flying mares of Surya racing
						forward.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 6
				-
					-
						When Maghavan with the thunderbolt demolished his nine-and-ninety castles
						all together,
					-
					-
						The Maruts, where they met, glorified Indra: ye with the Trstup hymn
						obstructed heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 7
				-
					-
						As friend to aid a friend, Agni dressed quickly three hundred buffaloes,
						even as he willed it.
					-
					-
						And Indra, from man's gift, for Vrtra's slaughter, drank ofr at once three
						lakes of pressed-out Soma.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 8
				-
					-
						When thou three hundred buffaloes' flesh hadst eaten, and drunk, as
						Maghavan, three lakes of Soma,
					-
					-
						All the Gods raised as 'twere a shout of triumph to Indra praise because he
						slew the Dragon.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 9
				-
					-
						What time ye came with strong steeds swiftly speeding, O Usana and Indra,
						to the dwelling,
					-
					-
						Thou camest thither -conquering together with Kutsa and the Gods: thou
						slewest Susna.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 10
				-
					-
						One car-wheel of the Sun thou rolledst forward, and one thou settest free
						to move for Kutsa.
					-
					-
						Thou slewest noseless Dasyus with thy weapon, and in their home
						o'erthrewest hostile speakers.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 11
				-
					-
						The lauds of Gauriviti made thee mighty to Vidathin's son, as prey, thou
						gavest Pipru.
					-
					-
						Rjisivan drew thee into friendship dressing the sacred food, and thou hast
						drunk his Soma.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Navagvas and Dasgvas with libations of Soma juice sing hymns of praise to
						Indra.
					-
					-
						Labouring at their task the men laid open the stall of Kine though firmly
						closed and fastened.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 13
				-
					-
						How shall I serve thee, Maghavan, though knowing full well what hero deeds
						thou hast accomplished?
					-
					-
						And the fresh deeds which thou wilt do, Most Mighty! these, too, will we
						tell forth in sacred synods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Resistless from of old through hero courage, thou hast done all these many
						acts, O Indra.
					-
					-
						What thou wilt do in bravery, Thunder-wielder! none is there who may hinder
						this thy prowess.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 29: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Indra, accept the prayers which now are offered, accept the new prayers,
						Mightiest! which we utter.
					-
					-
						Like fair and well-made robes, I, seeking riches, as a deft craftsman makes
						a car, have wrought them.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 30
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WHERE is that Hero? Who hath looked on Indra borne on light-rolling car by
						Tawny Coursers,
					-
					-
						Who, Thunderer, seeks with wealth the Soma-presser, and to his house goes,
						much-invoked, to aid him?
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 2
				-
					-
						I have beheld his strong and secret dwelling, longing have sought the
						Founder's habitation.
					-
					-
						I asked of others, and they said in answer, May we, awakened men, attain to
						Indra.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 3
				-
					-
						We will tell, Indra, when we pour libation, what mighty deeds thou hast
						performed to please us.
					-
					-
						Let him who knows not learn, who knows them listen: hither rides Maghavan
						with all his army.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Indra, when born, thou madest firm thy spirit: alone thou seekest war to
						fight with many.
					-
					-
						With might thou clavest e'en the rock asunder, and foundest out the stable
						of the Milch-kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 5
				-
					-
						When thou wast born supremest at a distance, bearing a name renowned in
						far-off regions,
					-
					-
						Since then e'en Gods have been afraid of Indra: he conquered all the floods
						which served the Dasa.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 6
				-
					-
						These blissful Maruts sing their psalm to praise thee, and pour to thee
						libation of the Soma.
					-
					-
						Indra with wondrous powers subdued the Dragon, the guileful lurker who
						beset the waters.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Thou, Maghavan, from the first didst scatter foemen, speeding, while joying
						in the milk, the Giver.
					-
					-
						There, seeking man's prosperity, thou torest away the head of Namuci the
						Dasa.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Pounding the head of Namuci the Dasa, me, too thou madest thine associate,
						Indra!
					-
					-
						Yea, and the rolling stone that is in heaven both worlds, as on a car,
						brought to the Maruts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Women for weapons hath the Dasa taken, What injury can his feeble armies To
						me?
					-
					-
						Well he distinguished his two different voices, and Indra then advanced to
						fight the Dasyu.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Divided from their calves the Cows went lowing around, on every side,
						hither and thither.
					-
					-
						These Indra re-united with his helpers, what time the well-pressed Soma
						made him joyful.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 11
				-
					-
						What time the Somas mixed by Babhru cheered him, loud the Steer bellowed in
						his habitations.
					-
					-
						So Indra drank thereof, the Fort-destroyer, and gave him guerdon, in
						return, of milch-kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 12
				-
					-
						This good deed have the Rusamas done, Agni! that they have granted me four
						thousand cattle.
					-
					-
						We have received Rnancaya's wealth, of heroes the most heroic, which was
						freely offered.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 13
				-
					-
						The Rusamas, O Agni, sent me homeward with fair adornment and with kine in
						thousands.
					-
					-
						The strong libations have made Indra joyful, when night, whose course was
						ending, changed to morning.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Night, well-nigh ended, at Rnancaya's coming, King of the Rusamas, was
						changed to morning.
					-
					-
						Like a strong courser, fleet of foot, urged onward, Babhru hath gained four
						thousand as his guerdon.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 30: Verse 15
				-
					-
						We have received four thousand head of cattle presented by the Rusamas, O
						Agni.
					-
					-
						And we, the singers, have received the caldron of metal which was heated
						for Pravargya.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 31
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 1
				-
					-
						MAGHAVAN Indra turns his chariot downward, the strength-displaying car
						which he hath mounted.
					-
					-
						Even as a herdsman driveth forth his cattle, he goeth, first, uninjured,
						fain for treasure.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Haste to us, Lord of Bays; be not ungracious: visit us, lover of gold-hued
						oblation.
					-
					-
						There is naught else better than thou art, Indra: e'en to the wifeless hast
						thou given spouses.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 3
				-
					-
						When out of strength arose the strength that conquers, Indra displayed all
						powers that he possesses.
					-
					-
						Forth from the cave he drove the milky mothers, and with the light laid
						bare investing darkness.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Anus have wrought a chariot for thy Courser, and Tvastar, Much-invoked! thy
						bolt that glitters.
					-
					-
						The Brahmans with their songs exalting Indra increased his strength that he
						might slaughter Ahi.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 5
				-
					-
						When heroes sang their laud to thee the Hero, Indra! and stones and Aditi
						accordant,
					-
					-
						Without or steed or chariot were the fellies which, sped by Indra, rolled
						upon the Dasytis.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 6
				-
					-
						I will declare thine exploits wrought aforetime, and, Maghavan, thy deeds
						of late achievement,
					-
					-
						When, Lord of Might, thou sunderedst earth and heaven, winning for man the
						moistly-gleaming waters.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 7
				-
					-
						This is thy deed, e'en this, Wonderful! Singer! that, slaying Ahi, here thy
						strength thou showedst,
					-
					-
						Didst check and stay e'en gusna's wiles and magic, and, drawing nigh, didst
						chase away the Dasytis.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Thou, Indra, on the farther bank forYadu and Turvaga didst stay the gushing
						waters.
					-
					-
						Ye both assailed the fierce: thou barest Kutsa: when Gods and Usana came to
						you together.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Let the steeds bring you both, Indra and Kutsa, borne on the chariot within
						hearing-distance.
					-
					-
						Ye blew him from the waters, from his dwelling, and chased the darkness
						from the noble's spirit.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Even this sage hath come looking for succour even to Vata's docile
						harnessed horses.
					-
					-
						Here are the Maruts, all, thy dear companions: prayers have increased thy
						power and might, O Indra.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 11
				-
					-
						When night was near its close he carried forward e'en the Sun's chariot
						backward in its running.
					-
					-
						Etaga brought his wheel and firmly stays it: setting it eastward he shall
						give us courage.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 12
				-
					-
						This Indra, O ye men, hath come to see you, seeking a friend who hath
						expressed the Soma.
					-
					-
						The creaking stone is laid upon the altar, and the Adhvaryus come to turn
						it quickly.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 31: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Let mortals who were happy still be happy; let them not come to sorrow, O
						Immortal.
					-
					-
						Love thou the pious, and to these thy people-with whom may we be
						numbered-give thou vigour.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 32
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 1
				-
					-
						well thou clavest, settest free the fountains, and gavest rest to floods
						that were obstructed.
					-
					-
						Thou, Indra, laying the great mountain open, slaying the Danava, didst
						loose the torrents.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 2
				-
					-
						The fountain-depths obstructed in their seasons, thou, Thunderer! madest
						flow, the mountain's udder.
					-
					-
						Strong Indra, thou by slaying e'en the Dragon that lay extended there hast
						shown thy vigour.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Indra with violence smote down the weapon,
					-
					-
						yea, even of that wild and mighty creature.
					-
					-
						Although he deemed himself alone unequalled, another had been born e'en yet
						more potent.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Him, whom the heavenly food of these delighted, child of the mist, strong
						waxing, couched in darkness,
					-
					-
						Him the bolt-hurling Thunderer with his lightning smote down and slew, the
						Danava's wrath-fire, Susna.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Though he might ne'er be wounded still his vitals felt that, the God's
						bolt, which his powers supported,
					-
					-
						When, after offered draughts, Strong Lord, thou laidest him, fain to
						battle, in the pit in darkness.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Him as he lay there huge in length extended, still waxing in the gloom
						which no sun lightened,
					-
					-
						Him, after loud-voiced threats, the Hero Indra, rejoicing in the poured
						libation, slaughtered.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 7
				-
					-
						When 'gainst the mighty Danava his weapon Indra uplifted, power which none
						could combat,
					-
					-
						When at the hurling of his bolt he smote him, he made him lower than all
						living creatures.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 8
				-
					-
						The fierce God seized that huge and restless coiler, insatiate, drinker of
						the sweets, recumbent,
					-
					-
						And with his mighty weapon in his dwelling smote down the footless
						evil-speaking ogre.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Who may arrest his strength or cheek his vigour? Alone, resistless, he
						bears off all riches.
					-
					-
						Even these Twain, these Goddesses, through terror of Indra's might, retire
						from his dominion.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 10
				-
					-
						E'en the Celestial Axe bows down before him, and the Earth, lover-like,
						gives way to Indra.
					-
					-
						As he imparts all vigour to these people, straightway the folk bend them to
						him the Godlike.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 11
				-
					-
						I hear that thou wast born sole Lord of heroes of the Five Races, famed
						among the people.
					-
					-
						As such my wishes have most lately grasped him, invoking Indra both at eve
						and morning.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 32: Verse 12
				-
					-
						So, too, I hear of thee as in due season urging to action and enriching
						singers.
					-
					-
						What have thy friends received from thee, the Brahmans who, faithful, rest
						their hopes on thee, O Indra?
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 33
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 33: Verse 1
				-
					-
						GREAT praise to Indra, great and strong mid heroes, I ponder thus, the
						feeble to the Mighty,
					-
					-
						Who with his band shows favour to this people, when lauded, in the fight
						where spoil is gathered.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 33: Verse 2
				-
					-
						So made attentive by our hymns, Steer! Indra! thou fastenedst the girth of
						thy Bay Coursers,
					-
					-
						Which, Maghavan, at thy will thou drivest hither. With these subdue for us
						the men who hate us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 33: Verse 3
				-
					-
						They were not turned to us-wtrd, lofty Indra! while yet through lack of
						prayer they stood unharnessed.
					-
					-
						Ascend this chariot, thou whose hand wields thunder, and draw the rein, O
						Lord of noble horses.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 33: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Thou, because many lauds are thine, O Indra, wast active warring in the
						fields
					-
					-
						for cattle.
					-
					-
						For Surya in his own abode thou, Hero, formedst in fights even a Dasa's
						nature.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 33: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Thine are we, Indra; thine are all these people, conscious of might, whose
						cars are set in motion.
					-
					-
						Some hero come to us, O Strong as Ahi beauteous in war, to be invoked like
						Bhaga.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 33: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Strength much to be desired is in thee, Indra: the Immortal dances forth
						his hero exploits.
					-
					-
						Such, Lord of Treasure, give us splendid riches. I praise the Friend's
						gift, his whose wealth is mighty.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 33: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Thus favour us, O Indra, with ihy succour; Hero, protect the bards who sing
						thy praises.
					-
					-
						Be friendly in the fray to those who offer the skin of beautiful and
						well-pressed Soma.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 33: Verse 8
				-
					-
						And these ten steeds which Trasadasyu gives me, the goldrich chief, the son
						of Purukutsa,
					-
					-
						Resplendent in their brightness shall convey me. Gairiksita willed it and
						so came I hither.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 33: Verse 9
				-
					-
						And these, bestowed as sacrificial guerdon, the powerful tawny steeds of
						Marutasva;
					-
					-
						And thousands which kind Cyavatana gave me, abundantly bestowed for my
						adornment.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 33: Verse 10
				-
					-
						And these commended horses, bright and active, by Dhvanya son of Laksmana
						presented,
					-
					-
						Came unto me, as cows into the Rsi Samvarana's stall, with magnitude of
						riches.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 34
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 34: Verse 1
				-
					-
						BOUNDLESS and wasting not, the heavenly food of Gods goes to the foeless
						One, doer of wondrous deeds.
					-
					-
						Press out, make ready, offer gifts with special zeal to him whom many laud,
						accepter of the prayer.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 34: Verse 2
				-
					-
						He who filled full his belly with the Soma's juice, Maghavan, was delighted
						with the meath's sweet draught,
					-
					-
						When Usana, that he might slay the monstrous beast, gave him the mighty
						weapon with a thousand points.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 34: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Illustrious is the man whoever presseth out Soma for him in sunshine or in
						cloud and rain.
					-
					-
						The mighty Maghavan who is the sage's Friend advanceth more and more his
						beauteous progeny.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 34: Verse 4
				-
					-
						The Strong God doth not flee away from him whose sire, whose mother or
						whose brother he hath done to death.
					-
					-
						He, the Avenger, seeketh this man's offered gifts: this God, the source of
						riches, doth not flee from sin.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 34: Verse 5
				-
					-
						He seeks no enterprise with five or ten to aid, nor stays with him who
						pours no juice though prospering well.
					-
					-
						The Shaker conquers or slays in this way or that, and to the pious gives a
						stable full of kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 34: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Exceeding strong in war he stays the chariot wheel, and, hating him who
						pours not, prospers him who pours.
					-
					-
						Indra the terrible, tamer of every man, as Arya leads away the Dasa at his
						will.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 34: Verse 7
				-
					-
						He gathers up for plunder all the niggard's gear: excellent wealth he gives
						to him who offers gifts.
					-
					-
						Not even in wide stronghold may all the folk stand firm who have provoked
						to anger his surpassing might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 34: Verse 8
				-
					-
						When Indra Maghavan hath marked two wealthy men fighting for beauteous cows
						with all their followers,
					-
					-
						He who stirs all things takes one as his close ally, and, Shaker, with his
						Heroes, sends the kine to him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 34: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Agni! I laud the liberal Agnivesi, Satri the type and standard of the
						pious.
					-
					-
						May the collected waters yield him plenty, and his be powerful and bright
						dominion.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 35
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 35: Verse 1
				-
					-
						INDRA, for our assistance bring that most effectual power of thine,
					-
					-
						Which conquers men for us, and wins the spoil, invincible in fight.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 35: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Indra, whatever aids be thine, four be they, or, O Hero, three,
					-
					-
						Or those of the Five Tribes of men, bring quickly all that help to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 35: Verse 3
				-
					-
						The aid most excellent of thee the Mightiest hitherward we call,
					-
					-
						For thou wast born with hero might, conquering, Indra, with the Strong.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 35: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Mighty to prosper us wast thou born, and mighty is the strength thou hast.
					-
					-
						In native power thy soul is firm: thy valour, Indra, slays a host.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 35: Verse 5
				-
					-
						O Satakratu, Lord of Strength, O Indra, Caster of the Stone.
					-
					-
						With all thy chariot's force assail the man who shows himself thy foe.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 35: Verse 6
				-
					-
						For, Mightiest Vrtra-slayer, thee, fierce, foremost among many, folk
					-
					-
						Whose sacred grass is trimmed invite to battle where the spoil is won.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 35: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Indra, do thou protect our car that mingles foremost in the fights,
					-
					-
						That bears its part in every fray, invincible and seeking spoil.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 35: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Come to us, Indra, and protect our car with thine intelligence.
					-
					-
						May we, O Mightiest One, obtain excellent fame at break of day, and
						meditate our hymn at dawn.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 36
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 36: Verse 1
				-
					-
						MAY Indra come to us, he who knows rightly to give forth treasures from his
						store of riches.
					-
					-
						Even as a thirsty steer who roams the deserts may he drink eagerly the
						milked-out Soma.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 36: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Lord of Bay Horses, Hero, may the Soma rise to thy cheeks and jaws like
						mountain-ridges.
					-
					-
						May we, O King, as he who driveth coursers, all joy in thee with hymns,
						invoked of many!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 36: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Invoked of many, Caster of the Stone my heart quakes like a rolling wheel
						for fear of penury.
					-
					-
						Shall not Puruvasu the singer give thee praise, O ever-prospering Maghavan,
						mounted on thy car?
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 36: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Like the press-stone is this thy praiser, Indra. Loudly he lifts his voice
						with strong endeavour.
					-
					-
						With thy left hand, O Maghavan, give us riches: with thy right, Lord of
						Bays, be not reluctant.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 36: Verse 5
				-
					-
						May the strong Heaven make thee the Strong wax stronger: Strong, thou art
						borne by thy two strong Bay Horses.
					-
					-
						So, fair of cheek, with mighty chariot, mighty, uphold us, strong-willed,
						thunderarmed, in battle.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 36: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Maruts, let all the people in obeisance bow down before this youthful
						Srutaratha,
					-
					-
						Who, rich in steeds, gave me two dark red horses together with three
						hundred head of cattle.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 37
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 37: Verse 1
				-
					-
						BEDEWED with holy oil and meetly worshipped, the Swift One vies with
						Surya's beam in splendour.
					-
					-
						For him may mornings dawn without cessation who saith, Let us press Soma
						out for Indra.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 37: Verse 2
				-
					-
						With kindled fire and strewn grass let him worship, and, Soma-presser, sing
						with stones adjusted:
					-
					-
						And let the priest whose press-stones ring forth loudly, go down with his
						oblation to the river.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 37: Verse 3
				-
					-
						This wife is coming near who loves her husband who carries to his home a
						vigorous consort.
					-
					-
						Here may his car seek fame, here loudly thunder, and his wheel make a
						thousand revolutions.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 37: Verse 4
				-
					-
						No troubles vex that King in whose home Indra drinks the sharp Soma juice
						with milk commingled.
					-
					-
						With heroes he drives near, he slays the foeman: Blest, cherishing that
						name, he guards his people.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 37: Verse 5
				-
					-
						May he support in peace and win in battle: he masters both the hosts that
						meet together.
					-
					-
						Dear shall he be to Surya, dear to Agni, who with pressed Soma offers gifts
						to India.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 38
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WIDE, Indra Satakratu, spreads the bounty of thine ample grace:
					-
					-
						So, Lord of fair dominion, Friend of all men, give us splendid wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 2
				-
					-
						The food which, Mightiest Indra, thou possessest worthy of renown
					-
					-
						Is bruited as most widely famed, invincible, O Golden-hued!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 3
				-
					-
						O Darter of the Stone, the powers which readily obey thy will,-
					-
					-
						Divinities, both thou and they, ye rule, to guard them, earth and heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 4
				-
					-
						And from whatever power of thine, O Vrtra-slayer, it may be,
					-
					-
						Bring thou to us heroic strength: thou hast a man's regard for us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 38: Verse 5
				-
					-
						In thy protection, with these aids of thine, O Lord of Hundred Powers,
					-
					-
						Indra, may we be guarded well, Hero, may we be guarded well.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 39
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 1
				-
					-
						STONE-DARTING Indra. Wondrous One, what wealth is richly given from thee,
					-
					-
						That bounty, Treasure-Finder! bring filling both thy hands, to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Bring what thou deemest worth the wish, O Indra, that which is in heaven.
					-
					-
						So may we know thee as thou art, boundless in thy munificence.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Thy lofty spirit, far-renowned as fain to give and prompt to win,-
					-
					-
						With this thou rendest e'en the firm, Stone-Darter! so to gain thee
						strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Singers with many songs have made Indra propitious to their fame,
					-
					-
						Him who is King of human kind, most liberal of your wealthy ones.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 39: Verse 5
				-
					-
						To him, to Indra must be sung the poet's word, the hymn of praise.
					-
					-
						To him, accepter of the prayer, the Atris raise their songs on high, the
						Atris beautify their songs.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 40
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 1
				-
					-
						COME thou to what the stones have pressed, drink Soma, O thou Soma's Lord,
					-
					-
						Indra best Vrtra-slayer Strong One, with the Strong.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Strong is the stone, the draught is strong, strong is this Soma that is
						pressed,
					-
					-
						Indra, best Vrtra-slayer, Strong One with the Strong.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 3
				-
					-
						As strong I call on thee the Strong, O Thunder-armed, with various aids,
					-
					-
						Indra, best Vrtra-slayer, Strong One with the Strong.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Impetuous, Thunderer, Strong, quelling the mighty, King, potent,
						Vrtra-slayer, Soma-drinker,
					-
					-
						May he come hither with his yoked Bay Horses; may Indra gladden him at the
						noon libation.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 5
				-
					-
						O Surya, when the Asura's descendant Svarbhanu, pierced thee through and
						through with darkness,
					-
					-
						All creatures looked like one who is bewildered, who knoweth not the place
						where he is standing.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 6
				-
					-
						What time thou smotest down Svarbhanu's magic that spread itself beneath
						the sky, O Indra,
					-
					-
						By his fourth sacred prayer Atri disoovered Surya concealed in gloom that
						stayed his function.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Let not the oppressor with this dread, through anger swallow me up, for I
						am thine, O Atri.
					-
					-
						Mitra art thou, the sender of true blessings: thou and King Varuna be both
						my helpers.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 8
				-
					-
						The Brahman Atri, as he set the press-stones, serving the Gods with praise
						and adoration,
					-
					-
						Established in the heaven the eye of Surya, and caused Svarbhanu's magic
						arts to vanish.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 40: Verse 9
				-
					-
						The Atris found the Sun again, him whom Svarbhanu of the brood
					-
					-
						Of Asuras had pierced with gloom. This none besides had power to do.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 41
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WHO, Mitra-Varuna, is your pious servant to give you gifts from earth or
						mighty heaven?
					-
					-
						Preserve us in the seat of holy Order, and give the offerer power that
						winneth cattle.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 2
				-
					-
						May Mitra, Varuna, Aryaman, and Ayu, Indra Rbhuksan, and the Maruts, love
						us,
					-
					-
						And they who of one mind with bounteous Rudra accept the hymn and laud with
						adorations.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 3
				-
					-
						You will I call to feed the car-horse, Asvins, with the wind's flight
						swiftest of those who travel:
					-
					-
						Or also to the Asura of heaven, Worshipful, bring a hymn as 'twere
						libation.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 4
				-
					-
						The heavenly Victor, he whose priest is Kanva, Trta with Dyaus accordant,
						Vata, Agni,
					-
					-
						All-feeding Pusan, Bhaga sought the oblation, as they whose steeds are
						fleetest seek the contest.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Bring ye your riches forward borne on horses: let thought be framed for
						help and gain of treasure.
					-
					-
						Blest he the priest of Ausija through courses, the courses which are yours
						the fleet, O Maruts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Bring hither him who yokes the car, your Vayu, who praises with his songs,
						the God and Singer;
					-
					-
						And, praying and devout, noble and prudent, may the Gods' Spouses in their
						thoughts retain us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 7
				-
					-
						I speed to you with powers that should be honoured, with songs
						distinguishing Heaven's mighty Daughters,
					-
					-
						Morning and Night, the Two, as 'twere all-knowing: these bring the
						sacrifice unto the mortal.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 8
				-
					-
						You I extol, the nourishers of heroes bringing you gifts, Vastospati and
						Tvastar-
					-
					-
						Rich Dhisana accords through our obeisance - andTrees and Plants, for the
						swift gain of riches.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Ours be the Parvatas, even they, for offspring, free-moving, who are Heroes
						like the Vasus.
					-
					-
						May holy Aptya, Friend of man, exalted, strengthen our word for ever and be
						near us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Trta praised him, germ of the earthly hero, with pure songs him the
						Offspring of the Waters.
					-
					-
						Agn; with might neighs loudly like a charger: he of the flaming hair
						destroys the forests.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 11
				-
					-
						How shall we speak to the great might of Rudra? How speak to Bhaga who
						takes thought for riches?
					-
					-
						May Plants, the Waters, and the Sky preserve us, and Woods and Mountains
						with their trees for tresses.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 12
				-
					-
						May the swift Wanderer, Lord of refreshments listen to our songs, who
						speeds throuih cloudy heaven:
					-
					-
						And may the Waters, bright like castles, hear us, as they flow onward from
						the cloven mountain.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 13
				-
					-
						We know your ways, ye Mighty Ones receiving choice meed, ye Wonderful, we
						will proclaim it.
					-
					-
						Even strong birds descend not to the mortal who strives to reach them with
						swift blow and weapons.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Celestial and terrestrial generations, and Waters will I summon to the
						feasting.
					-
					-
						May days with bright dawns cause my songs to prosper, and may the conquered
						streams increase their waters.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Duly to each one hath my laud been offered. Strong be Varutri with her
						powers to succour.
					-
					-
						May the great Mother Rasa here befriend us, straight-handed, with the
						princes, striving forward.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 16
				-
					-
						How may we serve the Liberal Ones with worship, the Maruts swift of course
						in invocation, the Maruts far-renowned in invocation?
					-
					-
						Let not the Dragon of the Deep annoy us, and gladly may he welcome our
						addresses.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Thus thinking, O ye Gods, the mortal wins you to give him increase of his
						herds of cattle: the mortal wins him, O ye Gods, your favour.
					-
					-
						Here he wins wholesome food to feed this body: as for mine old age, Nirrti
						consume it
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 18
				-
					-
						O Gods, may we obtain from you this favour, strengthening food through the
						Cow's praise, ye Vasus.
					-
					-
						May she who gives good gifts, the gracious Goddes. s, come speeding nigh to
						us for our well-being.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 19
				-
					-
						May Ila, Mother of the herds of cattle, and Urvasi with all the streams
						accept us;
					-
					-
						May Urvasi in lofty heaven accepting, as she partakes the oblation of the
						living,
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 41: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Visit us while she shares Urjavya's food.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 42
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Now may our sweetest song with deep devotion reach Varuna, Mitra, Aditi,
						and Bhaga.
					-
					-
						May the Five Priests' Lord, dwelling in oblations, bliss-giving Asura,
						hear, whose paths are open.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 2
				-
					-
						May Aditi welcome, even as a mother her dear heart-gladdening son, my song
						that lauds her.
					-
					-
						The prayer they love, bliss-giving, God-appointed, I offer unto Varuna and
						Mitra.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 3
				-
					-
						In spirit him, the Sagest of the Sages; with sacrificial oil and meath
						bedew him
					-
					-
						So then let him, God Savitar, provide us excellent, ready, and resplendent
						treasures.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 4
				-
					-
						With willing mind, Indra, vouchsafe us cattle, prosperity, Lord of Bays!
						and pious patrons;
					-
					-
						And, with the sacred prayer by Gods appointed, give us the holy Deities'
						lovingkindness.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 5
				-
					-
						God Bhaga, Savitar who deals forth riches, Indra, and they who conquer
						Vrtra's treasures,
					-
					-
						And Vaja and Rbhuksan and Purandhi, the Mighty and Immortal Ones, protect
						us!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Let us declare his deeds, the undecaying unrivalled Victor whom the Maruts
						follow.
					-
					-
						None of old times, O Maghavan, nor later, none of these days hath reached
						thy hero prowess.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Praise him the Chief who gives the boon of riches, Brhaspati distributor of
						treasures,
					-
					-
						Who, blessing most the man who sings and praises, comes with abundant
						wealth to his invoker.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Tended, Brhaspati, with thy protections, the princes are unharmed and girt
						by heroes.
					-
					-
						Wealth that brings bliss is found among the givers of horses and of cattle
						and of raiment.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Make their wealth flee who, through our hymns enjoying their riches, yield
						us not an ample guerdon.
					-
					-
						Far from the sun keep those who hate devotion, the godless, prospering in
						their vocation.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 10
				-
					-
						With wheelless chariots drive down him, O Maruts, who at the feasts of Gods
						regards the demons.
					-
					-
						May he, though bathed in sweat, form empty wishes, who blames his sacred
						rite who toils to serve you.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Praise him whose bow is strong and sure his arrow, him who is Lord of every
						balm that bealeth.
					-
					-
						Worship thou Rudra for his great good favour: adore the Asura, God, with
						salutations.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 12
				-
					-
						May the House-friends, the cunning-handed Artists, may the Steer's Wives,
						the streams carved out by Vibhvan,
					-
					-
						And may the fair Ones honour and befriend us, Sarasvati, Brhaddiva, and
						Raka.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 13
				-
					-
						My newest song, thought that now springs within me, I offer to the Great,
						the Sure Protector,
					-
					-
						Who made for us this All, in fond love laying each varied form within his
						Daughter's bosom.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Now, even now, may thy fair praise, O Singer, attain Idaspati who roars and
						thunders,
					-
					-
						Who, rich in clouds and waters with his lightning speeds forth bedewing
						both the earth and heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 15
				-
					-
						May this my laud attain the troop of Maruts, those who are youths in act,
						the Sons of Rudra.
					-
					-
						The wish calls me to riches and well-being: praise the unwearied Ones whose
						steeds are dappled.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 16
				-
					-
						May this my laud reach earth and air's mid-region, and forest trees and
						plants to win me riches.
					-
					-
						May every Deity be swift to listen, and Mother Earth with no ill thought
						regard me.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Gods, may we dwell in free untroubled bliss.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 42: Verse 18
				-
					-
						May we obtain the Asvins' newest favour, and gain their health-bestowing
						happy guidance.
					-
					-
						Bring riches hither unto us, and heroes, and all felicity and joy,
						Immortals!
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 43
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 1
				-
					-
						MAY the Milch-cows who hasten to their object come harmless unto us with
						liquid sweetness.
					-
					-
						The Singer, lauding, calls, for ample riches, the Seven Mighty Ones who
						bring enjoyment.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 2
				-
					-
						With reverence and fair praise will I bring hither, for sake of strength,
						exhaustless Earth and Heaven.
					-
					-
						Father and Mother, sweetof speech, fairhanded, may they, far-famed, in
						every fight protect us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Adhvaryus, make the sweet libations ready, and bring the beautiful bright
						juice to Vayu.
					-
					-
						God, as our Priest, be thou the first to drink it: we give thee of the mead
						to make thee joyful.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Two arms-the Soma's dexterous immo. lators-and the ten fingers set and fix
						the press-stone.
					-
					-
						The stalk hath poured, fair with its spreading branches, the mead's bright
						glittering juice that dwells on mountains.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 5
				-
					-
						The Soma hath been pressed for thee, its lover, to give thee power and
						might and high enjoyment.
					-
					-
						Invoked, turn hither in thy car, O Indra, at need, thy two well-trained and
						dear Bay Horses.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Bring by God-traversed paths, accordant, Agni, the great Aramati, Celestial
						Lady,
					-
					-
						Exalted, worshipped with our gifts and homage, who knoweth holy Law, to
						drink sweet Soma.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 7
				-
					-
						As on his father's lap the son, the darling, so on the fire is set the
						sacred caldron,
					-
					-
						Which holy singers deck, as if extending and heating that which holds the
						fatty membrane.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Hither, as herald to invite the Asvins, come the great lofty song, most
						sweet and pleasant!
					-
					-
						Come in one car, joy-givers! to the banquet, like the bolt binding pole and
						nave, come hither.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 9
				-
					-
						I have declared this speech of adoration to mightiest Pusan and victorious
						Vayu,
					-
					-
						Who by their bounty are the hymns' inspirers, and of themselves give power
						as a possession.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Invoked by us bring hither, jatavedas the Maruts all under their names and
						figures.
					-
					-
						Come to the sacrifice with aid all Maruts, all to the songs and praises of
						the singer!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 11
				-
					-
						From high heaven may Sarasvati the Holy visit our sacrifice, and from the
						mountain.
					-
					-
						Eager, propitious, may the balmy Goddess hear our effectual speech, our
						invocation.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Set in his seat the God whose back is dusky, Brhaspati the lofty, the
						Disposer.
					-
					-
						Him let us worship, set within the dwelling, the red, the golden-hued, the
						allresplendent.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 13
				-
					-
						May the Sustainer, high in heaven, come hither, the Bounteous One, invoked,
						with all his favours,
					-
					-
						Dweller with Dames divine, with plants, unwearied, the Steer with triple
						horn, the life-bestower.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 14
				-
					-
						The tuneful eloquent priests of him who liveth have sought the Mother's
						bright and loftiest station.
					-
					-
						As living men, with offered gifts and homage they deck the most auspicious
						Child to clothe him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Agni, great vital power is thine, the mighty: pairs waxing old in their
						devotion seek thee.
					-
					-
						May every Deity be swift to listen, and Mother Earth with no ill thought
						regard me.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Gods, may we dwell in free untroubled bliss.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 43: Verse 17
				-
					-
						May we obtain the Asvins' newest favour, and gain their health-bestowing
						happy guidance.
					-
					-
						Bring riches hither unto us, and heroes, and all felicity and joy,
						Immortals!
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 44
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 1
				-
					-
						As in the first old times, as all were wont, as now, he draweth forth the
						power turned hitherward with song,
					-
					-
						The Princedom throned on holy grass, who findeth light, swift, conquering
						in the' plants wherein he waxeth strong.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Shining to him who leaves heaven's regions undisturbed, which to his sheen
						who is beneath show fair in light,
					-
					-
						Good guardian art thou, not to be deceived, Most Wise! Far from deceits thy
						name dwelleth in holy Law.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Truth waits upon oblation present and to come: naught checks him in his
						way, this vic tory- bringing Priest:
					-
					-
						The Mighty Child who glides along the sacred grass, the undecaying Youth
						set in the midst of plants.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 4
				-
					-
						These come, well-yoked, to you for furtherance in the rite: down come the
						twinborn strengtheners of Law for him,
					-
					-
						With reins easily guided and commanding all. In the deep fall the hide
						stealeth away their names.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Thou, moving beauteously in visibly pregnant ones, snatching with trees the
						branching plant that grasps the juice,
					-
					-
						Shinest, true Singer! mid the upholders of the voice. Increase thy Consorts
						thou, lively at sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Like as he is beheld such is he said to be.
					-
					-
						They with effectual splendour in the floods have made
					-
					-
						Earth yield us room enough and amply wide extent, great might invincible,
						with store of hero sons.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Surya the Sage, as if unwedded, with a Spouse, in battle-loving spirit
						moveth o'er the foes.
					-
					-
						May he, self-excellent, grant us a sheltering home, a house that wards the
						fierce heat off on every side.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Thy name, sung forth by Rsis in these hymns of ours, goes to the loftier
						One with this swift mover's light.
					-
					-
						By skill he wins the boon whereon his heart is set: he who bestirs himself
						shall bring the thing to pass.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 9
				-
					-
						The chief and best of these abideth in the sea, nor doth libation fail
						wherein it is prolonged.
					-
					-
						The heart of him who praiseth trembleth not in fear there where the hymn is
						found connected with the pure.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 10
				-
					-
						For it is he: with though to of Ksatra, Manasa, of Yajata, and Sadhri, and
						Evavada,
					-
					-
						With Avatsara's sweet songs will we strive to win the mightiest strength
						which even he who knows should gain.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 11
				-
					-
						The Hawk is their full source, girth-stretching rapturous drink of
						Visvavara, of Mayin, and Yajata.
					-
					-
						They ever seek a fresh draught so that they may come, know when thy time to
						halt and drink thy fill is near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Sadaprna the holy, Tarya, Srutavit, and Bahuvrkta, joined with you, have
						slain the foes.
					-
					-
						He gains his wish in both the worlds and brightly shines-when he adores the
						host with well-advancing steeds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 13
				-
					-
						The worshipper's defender is Sutambhara, producer and uplifter of all holy
						thoughts.
					-
					-
						The milch-cow brought, sweet-flavoured milk was dealt around. Who speaks
						the bidding text knows this, not he who sleeps.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 14
				-
					-
						The sacred hymns love him who wakes and watches: to him who watches come
						the Sama verses.
					-
					-
						This Soma saith unto the man who watches, I rest and have my dwelling in
						thy friendship.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 44: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Agni is watchful, and the gcas love him; Agni is watchful, Sama verses seek
						him.
					-
					-
						Agni is watchful, to him saith this Soma, I rest and have my dwelling in
						thy friendship.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 45
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 1
				-
					-
						BARDS of approaching Dawn who know the heavens are come with hymns to throw
						the mountain open.
					-
					-
						The Sun hath risen and oped the stable portals: the doors of men, too, hath
						the God thrown open.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Surya hath spread his light as splendour: hither came the Cows' Mother,
						conscious, from the stable,
					-
					-
						To streams that flow with biting waves to deserts; and heaven is stablished
						like a firm-set pillar.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 3
				-
					-
						This laud hath won the burden of the mountain. To aid the ancient birth of
						mighty waters
					-
					-
						The mountain parted, Heaven performed his office. The worshippers were worn
						with constant serving.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 4
				-
					-
						With hymns and God-loved words will I invoke you, Indra and Agni, to obtain
						your favour,
					-
					-
						For verily sages, skilled in sacrificing, worship the Maruts and with lauds
						invite them.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 5
				-
					-
						This day approach us: may our thoughts be holy, far from us let us cast
						away misfortune.
					-
					-
						Let us keep those who hate us at a distance, and haste to meet the man who
						sacrifices.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Come, let us carry out, O friends, the purpose wherewith the Mother threw
						the Cow's stall open,
					-
					-
						That wherewith Manu conquered Visisipra, wherewith the wandering merchant
						gained heaven's water.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Here, urged by hands, loudly hath rung the press-stone wherewith Navagvas
						through ten months sang praises.
					-
					-
						Sarama went aright and found the cattle. Angiras gave effect to all their
						labours.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 8
				-
					-
						When at the dawning of this mighty Goddess, Angirases all sang forth with
						the cattle,-
					-
					-
						Their spring is in the loftiest place of meeting,-Sarama found the kine by
						Order's pathway.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Borne by his Coursers Seven may Surya visit the field that spreadeth wide
						for his long journey.
					-
					-
						Down on the Soma swooped the rapid Falcon. Bright was the young Sage moving
						mid his cattle.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Surya hath mounted to the shining ocean when he hath yoked his fair-backed
						Tawny Horses.
					-
					-
						The wise have drawn him like a ship through water: the floods obedient have
						descended hither.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 45: Verse 11
				-
					-
						I lay upon the Floods your hymn, lightwinning, wherewith Navagvas their ten
						months completed.
					-
					-
						Through this our hymn may we have Gods to guard us: through this our hymn
						pass safe beyond affliction.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 46
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WELL knowing I have bound me, horselike, to the pole: I carry that which
						bears as on and gives us help.
					-
					-
						I seek for no release, no turning back therefrom. May he who knows the way,
						the Leader, guide me straight.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 2
				-
					-
						O Agni, Indra, Varuna, and Mitra, give, O ye Gods, and Marut host, and
						Visnu.
					-
					-
						May both Nasatyas, Rudra, heavenly Matrons, Pusan, Sarasvati, Bhaga, accept
						us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Indra and Agni, Mitra, Varuna, Aditi, the Waters, Mountains, Maruts, Sky,
						and Earth and Heaven,
					-
					-
						Visnu I call, Pusan, and Brahmanaspati, and Bhaga, Samsa, Savitar that they
						may help.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 4
				-
					-
						May Visnu also and Vata who injures none, and Soma granter of possessions
						give us joy;
					-
					-
						And may the Rbhus and the Asvins, Tvastar and Vibhvan remember us so that
						we may have wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 5
				-
					-
						So may the band of Maruts dwelling in the sky, the holy, come to us to sit
						on sacred grass;
					-
					-
						Brhaspati and Pusan grant us sure defence, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman guard and
						shelter us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 6
				-
					-
						And may the Mountains famed in noble eulogies, and the fair-gleaming Rivers
						keep us safe from harm.
					-
					-
						May Bhaga the Dispenser come with power and grace, and far-pervading Aditi
						listen to my call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 7
				-
					-
						May the Gods' Spouses aid us of their own freewill, aid us to offspring and
						the winning of the spoil.
					-
					-
						Grant us protection, O ye gracious Goddesses, ye who are on the earth or in
						the waters' realm.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 46: Verse 8
				-
					-
						May the Dames, wives of Gods, enjoy our presents, Rat, Asvini, Agnayi, and
						Indrani.
					-
					-
						May Rodasi and Varunani hear us, and Goddesses come at the Matrons' season.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 47
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 1
				-
					-
						URGING to toil and making proclamation, seeking Heaven's Daughter comes the
						Mighty Mother:
					-
					-
						She comes, the youthful Hymn, unto the Fathers, inviting to her home and
						loudly calling.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Swift in their motion, hasting to their duty, reaching the central point of
						life immortal,
					-
					-
						On every side about the earth and heaven go forth the spacious paths
						without a limit.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Steer, Sea, Red Bird with strong wings, he hath entered the dwelling-place
						of the Primeval Father.
					-
					-
						A gay-hued Stone set in the midst of heaven, he hath gone forth and guards
						mid-air's two limits.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Four bear him up and give him rest and quiet, and ten invigorate the Babe
						for travel.
					-
					-
						His kine most excellent, of threefold nature, pass swiftly round the
						boundaries of heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Wondrous, O people, is the mystic knowledge that while the waters stand the
						streams are flowing:
					-
					-
						That, separate from his Mother, Two support him, closely-united, twins,
						here made apparent.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 6
				-
					-
						For him they lenghten prayers and acts of worship: the Mothers weave
						garments for him their offspring.
					-
					-
						Rejoicing, for the Steer's impregning contact, his Spouses move on paths or
						heaven to meet him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 47: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Be this our praise, O Varuna and Mitra may this be health and force to us,
						O Agni.
					-
					-
						May we obtain firm ground and room for resting: Glory to Heaven, the lofty
						habitation!
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 48
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WHAT may we meditate for the beloved Power, mighty in native strength and
						glorious in itself,
					-
					-
						Which as a magic energy seeking waters spreads even to theimmeasurable
						middle region's cloud?
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 2
				-
					-
						O'er all the region with their uniform advance these have spread out the
						lore that giveth heroes strength.
					-
					-
						Back, with their course reversed, the others pass away: the pious lengthens
						life with those that are before.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 3
				-
					-
						With pressing-stones and with the bright beams of the day he hurls his
						broadest bolt against the Guileful One.
					-
					-
						Even he whose hundred wander in his own abode, driving the days afar and
						bringing them again.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 4
				-
					-
						I, to enjoy the beauty of his form, behold that rapid rush of his as 'twere
						an axe's edge,
					-
					-
						What time he gives the man who calls on him in fight wealth like a
						dwelling-house filled full with store of food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 48: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Four-faced and nobly clad, Varuna, urging on the pious to his task, stirs
						himself with the tongue.
					-
					-
						Naught by our human nature do we know of him, him from whom Bhaga Savitar
						bestows the boon.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 49
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THIS day I bring God Savitar to meet you, and Bhaga who allots the wealth
						of mortals.
					-
					-
						You, Asvins, Heroes rich in treasures, daily seeking your friendship fain
						would I turn hither.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Knowing full well the Asura's time of coming, worship God Savitar with
						hymns and praises.
					-
					-
						Let him who rightly knoweth speak with homage to him who dealeth out man's
						noblest treasure.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Not for reward doth Pusan send his blessings, Bhaga, or Aditi: his garb is
						splendour.
					-
					-
						May Indra, Visniu, Varuna, Mitra, Agni produce auspicious days, the
						Wonder-Workers.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Sending the shelter which we ask, the foeless Savitar and the Rivers shall
						approach us.
					-
					-
						When I, the sacrifice's priest, invite them, may we he lords of wealth and
						rich possessions.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 49: Verse 5
				-
					-
						They who devote such worship to the Vasus, singing their hymns to Varuna
						and Mitra,
					-
					-
						Vouchsafe them ample room, far off be danger. Through grace of Heaven and
						Earth may we be happy.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 50
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 1
				-
					-
						LET every mortal man elect the friendship of the guiding God.
					-
					-
						Each one solicits him for wealth and seeks renown to prosper him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 2
				-
					-
						These, leading God, are thine, and these here ready to speak after us.
					-
					-
						As such may we attain to wealth and wait with services on thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 3
				-
					-
						So further honour as our guests the Hero Gods and then the Dames.
					-
					-
						May he remove and keep afar our foes and all who block our path.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Where fire is set, and swiftly runs the victim dwelling in the trough,
					-
					-
						He wins, with heroes in his home, friendly to man, like constant streams.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 50: Verse 5
				-
					-
						May these thy riches, Leader God! that rule the car, be blest to us,
					-
					-
						Yea, blest to us for wealth and weal. This will we ponder praising
						strength, this ponder as we praise the God.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 51
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WITH all assistants, Agni, come hither to drink the Soma-juice;
					-
					-
						With Gods unto our sacred gifts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Come to the sacrifice, O ye whose ways are right, whose laws are true,
					-
					-
						And drink the draught with Agni's tongue.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 3
				-
					-
						O Singer, with the singers, O Gracious, with those who move at dawn,
					-
					-
						Come to the Soma-draught with Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 4
				-
					-
						To Indra and to Vayu dear, this Soma, by the mortar pressed,
					-
					-
						Is now poured forth to fill the jar.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Vayu, come hither to the feast, wellpleased unto our sacred gifts:
					-
					-
						Drink of the Soma juice effused come to the food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Ye, Indra, Vayu, well deserve to drink the juices pressed by us.
					-
					-
						Gladly accept them, spotless Pair come to the food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 7
				-
					-
						For Indra and for Vayu pressed are Soma juices blent with curd,
					-
					-
						As rivers to the lowland flow: come to the food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Associate with all the Gods, come, with the Asvins and with Dawn,
					-
					-
						Agni, as erst with Atri, so enjoy the juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Associate with Varuna, with Mitra, Soma, Visnu, come,
					-
					-
						Agni, as erstwith Atri, so enjoy the juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Associate with Vasus, with Adityas, Indra, Viyu, come, Agni as erst with
						Atri, so enjoy the juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 11
				-
					-
						May Bhaga and the Asvins grant us health and wealth, and Goddess Adid and
						he whom none resist.
					-
					-
						The Asura Pusan grant us all prosperity, and Heaven and Earth most wise
						vouchsafe us happiness.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Let us solicit Vayu for prosperity, and Soma who is Lord of all the world
						for weal;
					-
					-
						For weal Brhaspati with all his company. May the Adityas bring us health
						and happiness.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 13
				-
					-
						May all the Gods, may Agni the beneficent, God of all men, this day be with
						us for our weal.
					-
					-
						Help us the Rbhus, the Divine Ones, for our good. May Rudra bless and keep
						us from calamity.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Prosper us, Mitra, Varuna. O wealthy Pathya, prosper us.
					-
					-
						Indra and Agni, prosper us; prosper us thou, O Aditi.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 51: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Like Sun and Moon may we pursue in full prosperity our path,
					-
					-
						And meet with one who gives again, -who knows us well and slays us not.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 52
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 1
				-
					-
						SING boldly forth, Syavasva, with the Maruts who are loud in song,
					-
					-
						Who, holy, as their wont is, joy in glory that is free from guile.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For in their boldness they are friends of firm and sure heroic strength.
					-
					-
						They in their course, bold-spirited, guard all men of their own accord.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Like steers in rapid motion they advance and overtake the nights;
					-
					-
						And thus the Maruts' power in heaven and on the earth we celebrate.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 4
				-
					-
						With boldness to your Maruts let us offer laud and sacrifice:
					-
					-
						Who all, through ages of mankind, guard mortal man from injury.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Praiseworthy, givers of good gifts, Heroes with full and perfect strength -
					-
					-
						To Maruts, Holy Ones of heaven, will I extol the sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 6
				-
					-
						The lofty Heroes cast their spears and weapons bright with gleaming gold.
					-
					-
						After these Maruts followed close, like laughing lightning from the sky, a
						splendour of its own accord.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 7
				-
					-
						They who waxed mighty, of the earth, they who are in the wide mid-air,
					-
					-
						Or in the rivers' compass, or in the abode of ample heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Praise thou the Maruts' company, the valorous and truly strong,
					-
					-
						The Heroes, hasting, by themselves have yoked their deer for victory.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 52: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Fair-gleaming, on Parusni they have clothed themselves in robes of wool,
					-
					-
						And with their chariot tires they cleave the rock asunder in their might.
					-
