					-
					-
						To this our goodly sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 71: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For, Varuna and Mitra, ye Sages are Rulers over all. Fill full our songs,
						for this ye can.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 71: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Come to the juice that we have pressed. Varuna, Mitra, come to drink
					-
					-
						This Soma of the worshipper.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 72
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 72: Verse 1
				-
					-
						To Varuna and Mitra we offerwith songs, as Atri did. Sit on the sacred
						grass to drink the Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 72: Verse 2
				-
					-
						By Ordinance and Law ye dwell in peace secure, bestirring men.
					-
					-
						Sit on the sacred grass to drink the Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 72: Verse 3
				-
					-
						May Varuna and Mitra, for our help, accept the sacrifice.
					-
					-
						Sit on the sacred grass to drink the Soma juice.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 73
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 73: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WHETHER, O Asvins, ye this day be far remote or near at hand,
					-
					-
						In many spots or in mid-air, come hither, Lords of ample wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 73: Verse 2
				-
					-
						These here, who show o'er widest space, bringing full many a wondrous act,
					-
					-
						Resistless, lovingly I seek, I call the Mightiest to enjoy.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 73: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Another beauteous wheel have ye fixed there to decorate your car.
					-
					-
						With others through the realms ye roam in might unto the neighbouring
						tribes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 73: Verse 4
				-
					-
						That deed of yours that is extolled, Visvas! hath all been done with this.
					-
					-
						Born otherwise, and spotless, ye have entered kinship's bonds with us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 73: Verse 5
				-
					-
						When Surya mounted on your car that rolls for ever rapidly,
					-
					-
						Birds of red hue were round about and burning splendours compassed you.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 73: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Atri bethinks himself of you, O Heroes, with a friendly mind,
					-
					-
						What time, Nasatyas, with his mouth he stirs the spotless flame for you.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 73: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Strong is your swiftly moving steed, famed his exertion in the course
					-
					-
						When by your great deeds, Atyins, Chiefs, Atri is brought to us again.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 73: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Lovers of sweetness, Rudras, she who streams with sweetness waits on you.
					-
					-
						When ye have travelled through the seas men bring you gifts of well-dressed
						food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 73: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Asvins, with truth they call you Twain bestowers of felicity;
					-
					-
						At sacrifice most prompt to hear, most gracious ye at sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 73: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Most pleasing to the Asvins be these prayers which magnify their might,
					-
					-
						Which we have fashioned, even as cars high reverence have we spoken forth.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 74
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 74: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WHERE in the heavens are ye to-day, Gods, Asvins, rich in constancy?
					-
					-
						Hear this, ye excellent as Steers: Atri inviteth you to come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 74: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Where are they now? Where are the Twain, the famed Nasatyas, Gods in
						heaven?
					-
					-
						Who is the man ye strive to reach? Who of your suppliants is with you?
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 74: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Whom do ye visit, whom approach? to whom direct your harnessed car?
					-
					-
						With whose devotions are ye pleased? We long for you to further us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 74: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Ye, Strengtheners, for Paura stir the filler swimming in the flood,
					-
					-
						Advancing to be captured like a lion to the ambuscade.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 74: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Ye from cyavana worn with age removed his skin as 'twere a robe.
					-
					-
						So, when ye made him young again, he stirred the longing of a dame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 74: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Here is the man who lauds you both: to see your glory are we here.
					-
					-
						Now bear me, come with saving help, ye who are rich in store of wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 74: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Who among many mortal men this day hath won you to himself?
					-
					-
						What bard, accepters of the bard? Who, rich in wealth! with sacrifice?
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 74: Verse 8
				-
					-
						O Asvins, may your car approach, most excellent of cars for speed.
					-
					-
						Through many regions may our praise pass onward among mortal men.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 74: Verse 9
				-
					-
						May our laudation of you Twain, lovers of meath! be sweet to you.
					-
					-
						Fly hitherward, ye wise of heart, like falcons with your winged steeds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 74: Verse 10
				-
					-
						O Asvins, when at any time ye listen to this call of mine,
					-
					-
						For you is dainty food prepared: they mix refreshing food for you.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 75
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 75: Verse 1
				-
					-
						To meet your treasure-bringing car, the mighty car most dear to us,
					-
					-
						Asvins, the Rsi is prepared, your raiser, with his song of praise. Lovers
						of sweetness, hear my call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 75: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Pass, O ye Asvins, pass away beyond all tribes of selfish men,
					-
					-
						Wonderful, with your golden paths, most gracious, bringers of the flood.
						Lovers of sweetness, hear my call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 75: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Come to us, O ye Asvin Pair, bringing your precious treasures, come
					-
					-
						Ye Rudras, on your paths of gold, rejoicing, rich in store of wealth.
						Lovers of sweetness, hear my call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 75: Verse 4
				-
					-
						O strong and Good, the voice of him who lauds you well cleaves to your car.
					-
					-
						And that great beast, your chariot-steed, fair, wonderful, makes dainty
						food. Lovers of sweetness, hear my call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 75: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Watchful in spirit, born on cars, impetuous, listing to his cry,
					-
					-
						Asvins, with winged steeds ye speed down to cyavana void of guile. Lovers
						of sweetness, hear my call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 75: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Hither, O Heroes, let your steeds, of dappled hue, yoked at the thought,
					-
					-
						Your flying steeds, O Asvins, bring you hitherward, with bliss, to drink.
						Lovers of sweetness, hear my call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 75: Verse 7
				-
					-
						O Asvins, hither come to us; Nasatyas, be not disinclined.
					-
					-
						Through longing for the pious turn out of the way to reach our home. Lovers
						of sweetness, bear my call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 75: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Ye Lords of Splendour, free from guile, come, stand at this our sacrifice.
					-
					-
						Beside the singer, Asvins, who longs for your grace and lauds you both.
						Lovers of sweetness, hear my call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 75: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Dawn with her white herd hath appeared, and in due time hath fire been
						placed.
					-
					-
						Harnessed is your immortal car, O WonderWorkers, strong and kind. Lovers of
						sweetness, bear my call.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 76
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 76: Verse 1
				-
					-
						AGNI, the bright face of the Dawns, is shining; the singers' pious voices
						have ascended.
					-
					-
						Borne on your chariot, Asvins, turn you hither and come unto our full and
						rich libation.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 76: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Most frequent guests, they scorn not what is ready: even now the lauded
						Asvins are beside us.
					-
					-
						With promptest aid they come at morn and evening, the worshipper's most
						blessed guards from trouble.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 76: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Yea, come at milking-time, at early morning, at noon of day and when the
						Sun is setting,
					-
					-
						By day, by night, with favour most auspicious. Not only now the draught
						hath drawn the Asvins.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 76: Verse 4
				-
					-
						For this place, Asvins, was of old your dwelling, these were your houses,
						this your habitation.
					-
					-
						Come to us from high heaven and from the mountain. Come from the waters
						bringing food and vigour.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 76: Verse 5
				-
					-
						May we obtain the Asvins' newest favour, and gain their health-bestowing
						happy guidance.
					-
					-
						Bring riches hither unto us, and heroes, and all felicity and joy,
						Immortals!
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 77
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 1
				-
					-
						FIRST worship those who come at early morning: let the Twain drink before
						the giftless niggard.
					-
					-
						The Asvins claim the sacrifice at daybreak: the sages yielding the first
						share extol them.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Worship at dawn and instigate the Asvins:nor is the worshipper at eve
						rejected.
					-
					-
						Besides ourselves another craves and worships: each first in worship is
						most highly favoured.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Covered with gold, meath-tinted, dropping fatness, your chariot with its
						freight of food comes hither,
					-
					-
						Swift as thought, Asvins, rapid as the tempest, wherewith ye travel over
						all obstructions.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 4
				-
					-
						He who hath served most often the Nasatyas, and gives the sweetest food at
						distribution,
					-
					-
						Furthers with his own holy works his offspring, and ever passes those whose
						flames ascend not.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 77: Verse 5
				-
					-
						May we obtain the Asvins' newest favour, and gain their health-bestowing
						happy ildance.
					-
					-
						Bring riches hither unto us, and heroes, and all felicity and joy,
						Immortals!
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 78
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 1
				-
					-
						YE Asvins, hither come to us: Nasatyas, be not disinclined.
					-
					-
						Fly hither like two swans unto the juice we shed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 2
				-
					-
						O Asvins, like a pair of deer, like two wild cattle to the mead:
					-
					-
						Fly hither like two swans unto the juice we shed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 3
				-
					-
						O Asvins rich in gifts, accept our sacrifice to prosper it:
					-
					-
						Fly hither like two swans unto the juice we shed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 4
				-
					-
						As Atri when descending to the cavem called on you loudly like a wailing
						woman.
					-
					-
						Ye came to him, O Asvins, with the freshest and most auspicious fleetness
						of a falcon.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Tree, part asunder like the side of her who bringeth forth a child.
					-
					-
						Ye Asvins, listen to my call: loose Saptavadhri from his bonds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 6
				-
					-
						For Saptavadhri, for the seer affrighted when he wept and wafled,
					-
					-
						Ye, Asvins, with your magic powers rent up the tree and shattered it.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Like as the wind on every side ruffles a pool of lotuses,
					-
					-
						So stir in thee the babe unborn, so may the ten-month babe descend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Like as the wind, like as the wood, like as the sea is set astir,
					-
					-
						So also, ten-month babe, descend together with the after-birth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 78: Verse 9
				-
					-
						The child who hath for ten months' time been lying in his mother's side,-
					-
					-
						May he come forth alive, unharmed, yea, livingfrorn the living dame.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 79
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 1
				-
					-
						O HEAVENLY Dawn, awaken us to ample opulence to-day
					-
					-
						Even as thou hast wakened us with Satyasravas, Vayya's son, high-born!
						delightful with thy steeds!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Daughter of Heaven, thou dawnedst on Sunitha Sucadratha's son,
					-
					-
						So dawn thou on one mightier still, on Satyasravas, Vayya's son, high-born!
						delightful with thy steeds!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 3
				-
					-
						So, bringing treasure, dawn to-day on us thou Daughter of the Sky,
					-
					-
						As thou, O mightier yet. didst shine for Satyatravas, Vayya's son,
						high-born! delightful with thy steeds!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Here round about thee are the priests who laud thee, Bright One, with their
						hymns,
					-
					-
						And men with gifts, O Bounteous Dame, splendid with wealth and offering
						much, high-born! delightful with thy steeds!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Whatever these thy bands perform to please thee or to win them wealth,
					-
					-
						E'en fain they gird us round and give rich gifts which ne'er are reft away,
						high-born! delightful with thy steeds!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Give to these wealthy patrons fame, O affluent Dawn, with hero sons,
					-
					-
						To these our princes who have brought rich gifts ne'er to be reft away,
						highborn! delightful with thy steeds!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Bring lofty and resplendent fame, O thou munificent Dawn, to these
					-
					-
						Our wealthy patrons who bestow rich gifts on us of steeds and kine,
						high-born! delightful with thy steeds!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Bring us, O Daughter of the Sky, subsistence in our herds of kine,
					-
					-
						Together with the sunbeams, with the shine of pure refulgent flames,
						highborn! delightful with thy steeds!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 9
				-
					-
						O Daughter of the Sky, shine forth; delay not to perform thy task.
					-
					-
						Let not the Sun with fervent heat consume thee like a robber foe,
						high-born! delightful with the steeds!
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 79: Verse 10
				-
					-
						So much, and more exceedingly, O Dawn, it suits thee to bestow,
					-
					-
						Thou Radiant One who ceasest not to shine for those who sing thy praise,
						highborn! delightful with thy steeds!
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 80
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THE singers welcome with their hymns and praises the Goddess Dawn who
						bringeth in the sunlight,
					-
					-
						Sublime, by Law true to eternal Order, bright on her path, red-tinted,
						far-refulgent.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 2
				-
					-
						She comes in front, fair, rousing up the people, making the pathways easy
						to be travelled.
					-
					-
						High, on her lofty chariot, all-impelling, Dawn gives her splendour at the
						days' beginning.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 3
				-
					-
						She, harnessing her car with purple oxen. injuring none, hath brought
						perpetual riches.
					-
					-
						Opening paths to happiness, the Goddess shines, praised by all, giver of
						every blessing.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 4
				-
					-
						With changing tints she gleams in double splendour while from the eastward
						she displays her body.
					-
					-
						She travels perfectly the path of Order, nor fails to reach, as one who
						knows, the quarters.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 5
				-
					-
						As conscious that her limbs are bright with bathing, she stands, as 'twere,
						erect that we may see her.
					-
					-
						Driving away malignity and darkness, Dawn, Child of Heaven, hath come to us
						with lustre.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 80: Verse 6
				-
					-
						The Daughter of the Sky, like some chaste woman, bends, opposite to men,
						her forehead downward.
					-
					-
						The Maid, disclosing boons to him who worships, hath brought again the
						daylight as aforetime.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 81
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THE priests of him the lofty Priest well-skilled in hymns harness their
						spirit, yea, harness their holy thoughts.
					-
					-
						He only knowing works assigns their priestly tasks. Yea, lofty is the
						praise of Savitar the God.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 2
				-
					-
						The Sapient One arrays himself in every form: for quadruped and biped he
						hath brought forth good.
					-
					-
						Excellent Savitar hath looked on heaven's high vault, and shineth after the
						outgoing of the Dawn.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Even he, the God whose going-forth and majesty the other Deities have
						followed with their might,
					-
					-
						He who hath measured the terrestrial regions out by his great power, he is
						the Courser Savitar.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 4
				-
					-
						To the three spheres of light thou goest, Savitar, and with the rays of
						Sidrya thou combinest thee.
					-
					-
						Around, on both sides thou encompassest the night: yea, thou, O God, art
						Mitra through thy righteous laws.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 81: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Over all generation thou art Lord alone: Pusan art thou, O God, in all thy
						goings-forth.
					-
					-
						Yea, thou hast domination over all this world. Syavasva hath brought praise
						to thee, O Savitar,
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 82
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WE crave of Savitar the God this treasure much to be enjoyed.
					-
					-
						The best, all-yielding, conquering gift of Bhaga we would gladly win.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Savitar's own supremacy, most glorious and beloved of all,
					-
					-
						No one diminisheth in aught.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 3
				-
					-
						For Savitar who is Bhaga shall send riches to his worshipper.
					-
					-
						That wondrous portion we implore.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Send us this day, God Savitar, prosperity with progeny.
					-
					-
						Drive thou the evil dream away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Savitar, God, send far away all sorrows and calamities,
					-
					-
						And send us only what is good.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Sinless in sight of Aditi through the God Savitar's influence,
					-
					-
						May we obtain all lovely things.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 7
				-
					-
						We with our hymns this day elect the general God, Lord of the good,
					-
					-
						Savitar whose decrees are true.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 8
				-
					-
						He who for ever vigilant precedes these Twain, the Day and Night,
					-
					-
						Is Savitar the thoughtful God.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 82: Verse 9
				-
					-
						He who gives glory unto all these living creatures with the song,
					-
					-
						And brings them forth, is Savitar.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 83
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 1
				-
					-
						SING with these songs thy welcome to the Mighty, with adoration praise and
						call Parjanya.
					-
					-
						The Bull, loud roaring, swift to send his bounty, lays in the plants the
						seed. for germination.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 2
				-
					-
						He smites the trees apart, he slays the demons: all life fears him who
						wields the mighty weapon.
					-
					-
						From him exceeding strong fices e'en the guiltless, when thundering
						Parjanya smites the wicked.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Like a car-driver whipping on his horses, he makes the messengers of rain
						spring forward.
					-
					-
						Far off resounds the roaring of the lion, what time Parjanya fills the sky
						with rain-cloud.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Forth burst the winds, down come the lightning-flashes: the plants shoot
						up, the realm of light is streaming.
					-
					-
						Food springs abundant for all living creatures, what time Parjanya quickens
						earth with moisture.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Thou at whose bidding earth bows low before thee, at whose command hoofed
						cattle fly in terror,
					-
					-
						At whose behest the plants assume all colours, even thou Parjanya, yield us
						great protection.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Send down for us the rain of heaven, ye Maruts, and let the Stallion's
						flood descend in torrents.
					-
					-
						Come hither with this thunder while thou pourest the waters down, our
						heavenly Lord and Father.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Thunder and roar: the germ of life deposit. Fly round us on thy chariot
						waterladen.
					-
					-
						Thine opened water-skin draw with thee downward, and let the hollows and
						the heights be level.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Lift up the mighty vessel, pour down water, and let the liberated streams
						rush forward.
					-
					-
						Saturate both the earth and heaven with fatness, and for the cows let there
						be drink abundant.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 9
				-
					-
						When thou, with thunder and with roar, Parjanya, smitest sinners down,
					-
					-
						This universe exults thereat, yea, all that is upon the earth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 83: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Thou hast poured down the rain-flood now withhold it. Thou hast made desert
						places fit for travel.
					-
					-
						Thou hast made herbs to grow for our enjoyment: yea, thou hast won thee
						praise from living creatures.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 84
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THOU, of a truth,O Prthivi, bearest the tool that rends the hills:
					-
					-
						Thou rich in torrents, who with might quickenest earth, O Mighty One.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 2
				-
					-
						To thee, O wanderer at will, ring out the lauds with beams of day,
					-
					-
						Who drivest, like a neighing steed, the swelling cloud, O bright of hue.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 84: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Who graspest with thy might on earth. e'en the strong sovrans of the wood,
					-
					-
						When from the lightning of thy cloud the rain-floods of the heaven descend.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 85
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 1
				-
					-
						SING forth a hymn sublime and solemn, grateful to glorious. Varuna,
						imperial Ruler,
					-
					-
						Who hath struck out, like one who slays the victim, earth as a skin to
						spread in front of Surya.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 2
				-
					-
						In the tree-tops the air he hath extended, put milk in kine and vigorous
						speed in horses,
					-
					-
						Set intellect in hearts, fire in the waters, Siurya in heaven and Soma on
						the mountain.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Varuna lets the big cask, opening downward, flow through the heaven and
						earth and air's mid-region.
					-
					-
						Therewith the universe's Sovran waters earth as the shower of rain bedews
						the barley.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 4
				-
					-
						When Varuna is fain for milk he moistens the sky, the land, and earth to
						her foundation.
					-
					-
						Then straight the mountains clothe them in the rain-cloud: the Heroes,
						putting forth their vigour, loose them.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 5
				-
					-
						I will declare this mighty deed of magic, of glorious Varuna the Lord
						Immortal,
					-
					-
						Who standing in the firmament hath meted the earth out with the Sun as with
						a measure.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 6
				-
					-
						None, verily, hath ever let or hindered this the most wise God's mighty
						deed of magic,
					-
					-
						Whereby with all their flood, the lucid rivers fill not one sea wherein
						they pour their waters.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 7
				-
					-
						If we have sinned against the man who loves us, have ever wronged a
						brother, friend, or comrade,
					-
					-
						The neighbour ever with us, or a stranger, O Varuna, remove from us the
						trespass.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 85: Verse 8
				-
					-
						If we, as gamesters cheat at play, have cheated, done wrong unwittingly or
						sinned of purpose,
					-
					-
						Cast all these sins away like loosened fetters, and, Varuna let us be thine
						own beloved.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 86
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THE mortal man whom ye, the Twain, Indra and Agni, help in fight,
					-
					-
						Breaks through e'en strongly-guarded wealth as Trta burst his way through
						reeds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 2
				-
					-
						The Twain invincible in war, worthy to be renowned in frays,
					-
					-
						Lords of the Fivefold. People, these, Indra and Agni, we invoke.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Impetuous is their strength, and keen the lightning of the mighty Pair,
					-
					-
						Which from their arms speeds with the car to Vrtra's slayer for the kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Indra and Agni, we invoke you both, as such, to send your cars:
					-
					-
						Lords of quick-coming bounty, ye who know, chief lovers of the song.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 5
				-
					-
						These who give increase day by day, Gods without guile for mortal man,
					-
					-
						Worthy themselves, I honour most, Two Gods as partners, for my horse.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 86: Verse 6
				-
					-
						The strength-bestowing offering thus to Indra-Agni hath been paid, as
						butter, purified by stones.
					-
					-
						Deal to our princes high renown, deal wealth to those who sing your praise,
						deal food to those who sing your praise.
					-
			-
				Mandala 5: Hymn 87
			-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 1
				-
					-
						To Visnu, to the Mighty whom the Maruts follow let your hymns born in song
						go forth, Evayamarut;
					-
					-
						To the impetuous, strong band, adorned with bracelets, that rushes on in
						joy and ever roars for vigour.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 2
				-
					-
						They who with might were manifest, and who willingly by their own knowledge
						told it forth, Evayamarut.
					-
					-
						Maruts, this strength of yours no wisdom comprehendeth: through their
						gifts' greatness they are moveless as the mountains.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Who by the psalm they sing are heard, from lofty heaven, the strong, the
						brightly shining Ones, Evayamarut;
					-
					-
						In whose abode there is no mightier one to move them, whose lightnings are
						as fires, who urge the roaring rivers.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 4
				-
					-
						He of the Mighty Stride forth strode, Evayamarut, out of the spacious
						dwelling-place, their home in common.
					-
					-
						When he, himself, hath yoked his emulous strong horses on heights, he
						cometh forth, joy-giving, with the Heroes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Like your tremendous roar, the rainer with light flashing, strong,
						speeding, hath made all tremble, Evayamarut,
					-
					-
						Wherewith victorious ye, self-luminous, press onward, with strong reins,
						decked with gold, impetuous and well-weaponed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Unbounded is your greatness, ye of mighty power: may your bright vigour be
						our aid, Evayamarut;
					-
					-
						For ye are visible helpers in the time of trouble: like fires, aglow with
						light, save us from shame and insult.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 7
				-
					-
						So may the Rudras, mighty warriors, Evayamarut, with splendid brilliancy,
						like fires, be our protectors;
					-
					-
						They whose terrestrial dwelling-place is wide-extended, whom none suspect
						of sin, whose bands have lofty courage.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Come in a friendly spirit, come to us, O Maruts, and hear his call who
						praises you, Evayamarut.
					-
					-
						Like car-borne men, one-minded with the mighty Visnu, keep enmity far from
						us with your deeds of wonder.
					-
				-
					Mandala 5: Hymn 87: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Come to our sacrifice, ye Hnly Ones, to bless it, and, free from demons,
						hear our call, Evayamarut.
					-
		-
			Mandala 6
		-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 1
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THOU, first inventor of this prayer, O Agni, Worker of Marvels, hast become
						our Herald.
					-
					-
						Thou, Bull, hast made us strength which none may conquer, strength that
						shall overcome all other prowess.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 2
				-
					-
						As Priest thou sattest at the seat of worship, furthering us, best Offerer,
						meet for honour.
					-
					-
						So first to thee have pious men resorted, turning thy mind to thoughts of
						ample riches.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 3
				-
					-
						In thee, still watching, they have followed riches, who goest with much
						wealth as with an army,
					-
					-
						The radiant Agni, lofty, fair to look on, worshipped with marrow, evermore
						resplendent.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 4
				-
					-
						They who approached the God's abode with homage, eager for glory, won them
						perfect glory:
					-
					-
						Yea, they gained even sacrificial titles, and found delight in thine
						auspicious aspect.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 5
				-
					-
						On earth the people magnify thee greatly, thee their celestial and
						terrestrial riches.
					-
					-
						Thou, Helper, must be known as our Preserver, Father and Mother of mankind
						for ever.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Dear priest among mankind, adorable Agni hath seated him, joy-giver,
						skilled in worship.
					-
					-
						Let us approach thee shining in thy dwelling, kneeling upon our knees, with
						adoration.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Longing for bliss, pure-minded, God-devoted, Agni, we seek thee, such, meet
						to be lauded.
					-
					-
						Thou, Agni, leddest forth our men to battle, refulgent with the heaven's
						exalted splendour.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Sage of mankind, all peoples' Lord and Master, the Bull of men, the sender
						down of blessings,
					-
					-
						Still pressing on, promoting, purifying, Agni the Holy One, the Lord of
						riches.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Agni, the mortal who hath toiled and worshipped, brought thee oblations
						with his kindled fuel,
					-
					-
						And well knows sacrifice with adoration, gains every joy with thee to guard
						and help him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Mightily let us worship thee the Mighty, with reverence, Agni! fuel and
						oblations,
					-
					-
						With songs, O Son of Strength, with hymns, with altar: so may we strive for
						thine auspicious favour.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Thou who hast covered heaven and earth with splendour and with thy glories,
						glorious and triumphant.
					-
					-
						Continue thou to shine on us, O Agni, with strength abundant, rich, and
						long enduring.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Vouchsafe us ever, as man needs, O Vasu, abundant wealth of kine for son
						and offspring.
					-
					-
						Food noble, plenteous, far from sin and evil, he with us, and fair fame to
						make us happy.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 1: Verse 13
				-
					-
						May I obtain much wealth in many places by love of thee and through thy
						grace, King Agni;
					-
					-
						For in thee Bounteous One, in thee the Sovran, Agni, are many boons for him
						who serves thee.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 2
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THOU, Agni, even as Mitra, hast a princely glory of thine own.
					-
					-
						Thou, active Vasu, makest fame increase like full prosperity.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For, verily, men pray to thee with sacrifices and with songs.
					-
					-
						To thee the Friendly Courser, seen of all, comes speeding through the air.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Of one accord men kindle thee Heaven's signal of the sacrifice,
					-
					-
						When, craving bliss, this race of man invites thee to the solemn rite.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Let the man thrive who travails sore, in prayer, far thee the Bountiful.
					-
					-
						He with the help of lofty Dyaus comes safe through straits of enmity.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 5
				-
					-
						The mortal who with fuel lights thy flame and offers unto thee,
					-
					-
						Supports a house with many a branch, Agni, to live a hundred years.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Thy bright smoke lifts itself aloft, and far-extended shines in heaven.
					-
					-
						For, Purifier! like the Sun thou beamest with thy radiant glow.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 7
				-
					-
						For in men's houses thou must be glorified as a well-loved guest,
					-
					-
						Gay like an elder in a fort, claiming protection like a son.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Thou, Agni, like an able steed, art urged by wisdom in the wood.
					-
					-
						Thou art like wind; food, home art thou, like a young horse that runs
						astray.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 9
				-
					-
						E'en things imperishable, thou, O Agni, like a gazing ox,
					-
					-
						Eatest, when hosts, Eternal One! of thee the Mighty rend the woods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Agni, thou enterest as Priest the home of men who sacrifice.
					-
					-
						Lord of the people, prosper them. Accept the ofrering, Angiras!
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 2: Verse 11
				-
					-
						O Agni, God with Mitra's might, call hither the favour of the Gods from
						earth and heaven.
					-
					-
						Bring weal from heaven, that men may dwell securely. May we o'ercome the
						foe's malign oppressions, may we o'ercome them, through thy help o'ercome
						them.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 3
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 1
				-
					-
						TRUE, guardian of the Law, thy faithful servant wins ample light and dwells
						in peace, O Agni,
					-
					-
						Whom thou, as Varuna in accord with Mitra, guardest, O God, by banishing
						his trouble.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 2
				-
					-
						He hath paid sacrifices, toiled in worship, and offered gifts to
						wealth-increasing Agni.
					-
					-
						Him the displeasure of the famous moves not, outrage and scorn affect not
						such a mortal.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Bright God, whose look is free from stain like Surya's, thou, swift, what
						time thou earnestly desirest,
					-
					-
						Hast gear to give us. Come with joy at evening, where, Child of Wood, thou
						mayest also tarry.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Fierce is his gait and vast his wondrous body: he champeth like a horse
						with bit and bridle,
					-
					-
						And, darting forth his tongue, as 'twere a hatchet, burning the woods,
						smelteth them like a smelter.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Archer-like, fain toshoot, he sets his arrow, and whets his splendour like
						the edge of iron:
					-
					-
						The messenger of night with brilliant pathway, like a tree-roosting bird of
						rapid pinion.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 6
				-
					-
						In beams of morn he clothes him like the singer, and bright as Mitra with
						his splendour crackles.
					-
					-
						Red in the night, by day the men's possession: red, he belongs to men by
						day, Immortal.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Like Heaven's when scattering beams his voice was uttered: among the plants
						the radiant Hero shouted,
					-
					-
						Who with his glow in rapid course came hither to fill both worlds,
						well-wedded Dames, with treasure.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 3: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Who, with supporting streams and rays that suit him, hath flashed like
						lightning with his native vigour.
					-
					-
						Like the deft Maker of the band of Maruts, the bright impetuous One hath
						shone refulgent.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 4
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 1
				-
					-
						As at man's service of the Gods, Invoker, thou, Son of Strength, dost
						sacrifice and worship,
					-
					-
						So bring for us to-day all Gods together, bring willingly the willing Gods,
						O Agni.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 2
				-
					-
						May Agni, radiant Herald of the morning, meet to be known, accept our
						praise with favour.
					-
					-
						Dear to all life, mid mortal men Immortal, our guest, awake at dawn, is
						Jatavedas.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Whose might the very heavens regard with wonder: bright as the Sun he
						clothes himself with lustre.
					-
					-
						He who sends forth,, Eternal Purifier, hath shattered e'en the ancient
						works of Asna.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Thou art a Singer, Son! our feast-companion: Agni at birth prepared his
						food and pathway.
					-
					-
						Therefore vouchsafe us strength, O Strength-bestower. Win like a King: foes
						trouble not thy dwelling.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Even he who cats his firm hard food with swiftness,and overtakes the nights
						as Vayu kingdoms.
					-
					-
						May we o'ercome those who resist thine orders, like a steed casting down
						the flying foemen.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Like Surya with his fulgent rays, O Agni, thou overspreadest both the
						worlds with splendour.
					-
					-
						Decked with bright colour he dispels the darkness, like Ausija, with clear
						flame swifily flying.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 7
				-
					-
						We have elected thee as most delightful for thy beams' glow: hear our great
						laud, O Agni.
					-
					-
						The best men praise thee as the peer of Indra in strength, mid Gods, like
						Viyu in thy bounty.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 4: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Now, Agni, on the tranquil paths of riches come to us for our weal: save us
						from sorrow.
					-
					-
						Grant chiefs and bard this boon. May we live happy, with hero children,
						through a hundred winters.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 5
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 1
				-
					-
						I INVOCATE your Son of Strength, the Youthful, with hymns, the Youngest
						God, whose speech is guileless;
					-
					-
						Sage who sends wealth comprising every treasure, bringer of many boons,
						devoid of malice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 2
				-
					-
						At eve and morn thy pious servants bring thee their precious gifts, O
						Priest of many aspects,
					-
					-
						On whom, the Purifier, all things living as on firm. ground their happiness
						have stablished.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Thou from of old hast dwelt among these people, by mental power the
						charioteer of blessings.
					-
					-
						Hence sendest thou, O sapient Jatavedas, to him who serves thee treasures
						in succession.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Agni, whoever secretly attacks us, the neighbour, thou with Mitra's might!
						who harms us,
					-
					-
						Burn him with thine own Steers for ever youthful, burning with burning
						heat, thou fiercest burner.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 5
				-
					-
						He who serves thee with sacrifice and fuel, with hymn, O Son of Strength,
						and chanted praises,
					-
					-
						Shines out, Immortal! in the midst of mortals, a sage, with wealth, with
						splendour and with glory.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Do this, O Agni, when we urge thee, quickly, triumphant in thy might subdue
						our foemen.
					-
					-
						When thou art praised with words and decked with brightness, accept this
						chanted hymn, the singer's worship.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 5: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Help us, that we may gain this wish, O Agni, gain riches, Wealthy One! with
						store of heroes.
					-
					-
						Desiring strength from thee may we be strengthened, and win, Eternal! thine
						eternal glory.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 6
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 1
				-
					-
						HE who seeks furtherance and grace to help him goes to the Son of Strength
						with newest worship,
					-
					-
						Calling the heavenly Priest to share the banquet, who rends the wood,
						bright, with his blackened pathway.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 2
				-
					-
						White-hued and thundering he dwells in splendour, Most Youthful, with the
						loudvoiced and eternal-
					-
					-
						Agni, most variform, the Purifier, who follows crunching many ample
						forests.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Incited by the wind thy flames, O Agni, move onward, Pure One! pure, in all
						directions.
					-
					-
						Thy most destructive heavenly Navagvas break the woods down and devastate
						them boldly.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Thy pure white horses from their bonds are loosened: O Radiant One, they
						shear the ground beneath them,
					-
					-
						And far and wide shines out thy flame, and flickers rapidly moving over
						earth's high ridges.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Forth darts the Bull's tongue like the sharp stone weapon discharged by him
						who fights to win the cattle.
					-
					-
						Agni's fierce flame is like a hero's onset: dread and resistless he
						destroys the forests.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Thou with the sunlight of the great Impeller hast boldly over-spread the
						earth's expanses.
					-
					-
						So drive away with conquering might all perils. fighting out foemen burn up
						those who harm us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 6: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Wondrous! of wondrous power! give to the singer wealth wondrous, marked,
						most wonderful, life-giving.
					-
					-
						Wealth bright, O Bright One, vast, with many heroes, give with thy bright
						flames to the man who lauds thee.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 7
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Him, messenger of earth and head of heaven, Agni Vaisvanara, born in holy
						Order,
					-
					-
						The Sage, the King, the guest of men, a vessel fit for their mouths, the
						Gods have generated.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Him have they praised, mid-point of sacrifices, great cistern of libations,
						seat of riches.
					-
					-
						Vaisvanara, conveyer of oblations, ensign of worship, have the Gods
						engendered.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 3
				-
					-
						From thee, O Agni, springs the mighty singer, from thee come heroes who
						subdue the foeman.
					-
					-
						O King, Vaisvanara, bestow thou on us excellent treasures worthy to
						belonged fo r.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 4
				-
					-
						To thee, Immortal! when to life thou springest, all the Gods sing for joy
						as to their infant.
					-
					-
						They by thy mental powers were made immortal, Vaisvanara, when thou shonest
						from thy Parents.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Agni Vaisvanara, no one hath ever resisted these thy mighty ordinances,
					-
					-
						When thou, arising from thy Parents' bosom, foundest the light for days'
						appointed courses.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 6
				-
					-
						The summits of the heaven are traversed through and through by the
						Immortal's light, Vaisvanara's brilliancy.
					-
					-
						All creatures in existence rest upon his head. The Seven swift-flowing
						Streams have grown like branches forth,
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 7: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Vaisvanara, who measured out the realms of air, Sage very wise who made the
						lucid spheres of heaven,
					-
					-
						The Undeceivable who spread out all the worlds, keeper is he and guard of
						immortality.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 8
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 1
				-
					-
						AT Jatavedas' holy gathering I will tell aloud the conquering might of the
						swift red-hued Steer.
					-
					-
						A pure and fresher hymn flows to Vaisvanara, even as for Agni lovely Soma
						is made pure.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 2
				-
					-
						That Agni, when in loftiest heaven he sprang to life, Guardian of Holy
						Laws, kept and observed them well.
					-
					-
						Exceeding wise, he measured out the firmament. Vaisvanara attained to
						heaven by mightiness.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Wonderful Mitra propped the heaven and earth apart, and covered and
						concealed
					-
					-
						the darkness with his light.
					-
					-
						He made the two bowls part asunder like two skins. Vaisvanara put forth all
						his creative power.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 4
				-
					-
						The Migbty seized him in the bosom of the floods: the people waited on the
						King who should be praised.
					-
					-
						As envoy of Vivasvan MatariSvan brought Agni Vaisvanara hither from far
						away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 5
				-
					-
						In every age bestow upon the singers wealth, worthy of holy synods,
						glorious, ever new.
					-
					-
						King, undecaying, as it were with sharpened bolt, smite down the sinner
						like a tree with lightning-flash.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Do thou bestow, O Agni, on our wealthy chiefs, rule, with good heroes,
						undecaying, bending not.
					-
					-
						So may we win for us strength. O Vaisvanara, hundredfold, thousandfold, O
						Agni, by thy help.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 8: Verse 7
				-
					-
						O thou who dwellest in three places, Helper, keep with effective guards our
						princely patrons.
					-
					-
						Keep our band, Agni, who have brought thee presents. Lengthen their lives,
						Vaisvanara, when lauded.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 9
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 1
				-
					-
						ONE half of day is dark, and bright the other: both atmospheres move on by
						sage devices.
					-
					-
						Agni Vaisvanara, when born as Sovran, hath with his lustre overcome the
						darkness.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 2
				-
					-
						I know not either warp or woof, I know not the web they weave when moving
						to the contest.
					-
					-
						Whose son shall here speak words that must be spoken without assistance
						from the Father near him?
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 3
				-
					-
						For both the warp and woof he understandeth, and in due time shall speak
						what should be spoken,
					-
					-
						Who knoweth as the immortal world's Protector, descending, seeing with no
						aid from other.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 4
				-
					-
						He is the Priest, the first of all: behold him. Mid mortal men he is the
						light immortal.
					-
					-
						Here was he born, firm-seated in his station Immortal, ever waxing in his
						body.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 5
				-
					-
						A firm light hath been set for men to look on: among all things that fly
						the mind is swiftest.
					-
					-
						All Gods of one accord, with one intention, move unobstructed to a single
						purpose.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Mine ears unclose to hear, mine eye to see him; the light that harbours in
						my spirit broadens.
					-
					-
						Far roams my mind whose thoughts are in the distance. What shall I speak,
						what shall I now imagine?
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 9: Verse 7
				-
					-
						All the Gods bowed them down in fear before thee, Agni, when thou wast
						dwelling in the darkness.
					-
					-
						Vaisvanara be gracious to assist us, may the Immortal favour us and help
						us.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 10
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 1
				-
					-
						INSTALL at sacrifice, while the rite advances, your pleasant, heavenly
						Agni, meet for praises.
					-
					-
						With hymns-for he illumines us-install him. He, Jatavedas, makes our rites
						successful.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Hear this laud, Radiant Priest of many aspects, O Agni with the fires of
						man enkindled,
					-
					-
						Laud which bards send forth pure as sacred butter, strength to this man, as
						'twere for self-advantage.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Mid mortal men that singer thrives in glory who offers gifts with hymns of
						praise to Agni,
					-
					-
						And the God, wondrous bright, with wondrous succours helps him to win a
						stable filled with cattle.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 4
				-
					-
						He, at his birth, whose path is black behind him, filled heaven and earth
						with far-apparent splendour:
					-
					-
						And he himself hath been. through night's thick darkness, made manifest by
						light, the Purifier.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 5
				-
					-
						With thy most mighty aid, confer, O Agni, wonderful wealth on us and on our
						princes,
					-
					-
						Who stand preeminent, surpassing others in liberal gifts, in fame, and hero
						virtues.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Agni, accept this sacrifice with gladness, which, seated here, the
						worshipper presenteth.
					-
					-
						Fair hymns hadst thou among the Bharadvajas, and holpest them to gain
						abundant vigour.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 10: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Scatter our foes, increase our store. May we he glad a hundred winters with
						brave sons.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 11
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 1
				-
					-
						EAGERLY Sacrifice thou, most skilful, Agni! Priest, pressing on as if the
						Maruts sent thee.
					-
					-
						To our oblation bring the two Nasatyas, Mitra and Varuna and Earth and
						Heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Thou art our guileless, most delightful Herald, the God, among mankind, of
						holy synods.
					-
					-
						A Priest with purifying tongue, O Agni, sacrifice with thy mouth to thine
						own body.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 3
				-
					-
						For even the blessed longing that is in thee would bring the Gods down to
						the singer's worship,
					-
					-
						When the Angirases' sagest Sage, the Poet, sings the sweet measure at the
						solemn service.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Bright hath he beamed, the wise, the far-refulgent. Worship the two
						widespreading Worlds, O Agni,
					-
					-
						Whom as the Living One rich in oblations the Five Tribes, bringing gifts,
						adorn with homage.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 5
				-
					-
						When I with reverence clip the grass for Agni, when the trimmed ladle,
						fullof oil, is lifted,
					-
					-
						Firm on the seat of earth is based the altar: eye-like, the sacrifice is
						directed Sun-ward.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 11: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Enrich us, O thou Priest of many aspects, with the Gods, Agni, with thy
						fires, enkindled.
					-
					-
						O Son of Strength, clad in the robe of riches, may we escape from woe as
						from
					-
					-
						a prison.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 12
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 1
				-
					-
						KING of trimmed grass, Herald within the dwelling, may Agni worship the
						Impeller's World-halves.
					-
					-
						He, Son of Strength, the Holy, from a distance hath spread himself abroad
						with light like Surya.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 2
				-
					-
						In thee, most wise, shall Dyaus, for full perfection, King! Holy One!
						pronounce the call to worship.
					-
					-
						Found in three places, like the Speeder's footstep, come to present men's
						riches as oblations!
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Whose blaze most splendid, sovran in the forest, shines waxing on his way
						like the - Impeller.
					-
					-
						He knows himself, like as a guileless smelter, not to be stayed among the
						plants, Immortal.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Our friends extol him like a steed for vigour even Agni in the dwelling,
						jatave~as.
					-
					-
						Trce-fed, he fights with power as doth a champion, like Dawn's Sire to be
						praised with sacrifices.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Men wonder at his shining glows when, paring the woods with case, o'er the
						broad earth he goeth,
					-
					-
						And, like a rushing flood, loosed quickly, burneth, swift as a guilty
						thief, o'er desert places.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 12: Verse 6
				-
					-
						So mighty thou protectest us from slander, O Champion, Agni! with all fires
						enkindled.
					-
					-
						Bring opulence and drive away affliction. May brave sons gladden us through
						a hundred winters.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 13
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 1
				-
					-
						FROM thee, as branches from a tree, O Agni, from thee, Auspicious God!
						spring all our blessings-
					-
					-
						Wealth swiftly, strength in battle with our foemen, the rain besought of
						heaven, the flow of waters.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Thou art our Bhaga to send wealth thou dwellest, like circumambient air,
						with wondrous splendour.
					-
					-
						Friend art thou of the lofty Law, like Mitra, Controller, Agni! God! of
						many a blessing.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Agni! the hero slays with might his foeman; the singer bears away the
						Pani's booty-
					-
					-
						Even he whom thou, Sage, born in Law, incitest by wealth, accordant with
						the Child of Waters.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 4
				-
					-
						The man who, Son of Strength 1 with sacrifices, hymns, lauds, attracts thy
						fervour to the altar,
					-
					-
						Enjoys each precious thing, O God, O Agni, gains wealth of corn and is the
						lord of treasures.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Grant, Son of Strength, to men for their subsistence such things as bring
						high fame and hero children.
					-
					-
						For thou with might givest much food in cattle even to the wicked wolf when
						he is hungry.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 13: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Eloquent, Son of Strength, Most Mighty, Agni, vouchsafe us seed and
						offspring, full of vigour.
					-
					-
						May I by all my songs obtain abundance. May brave sons gladden us through a
						hundred winters.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 14
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WHOSO to Agni hath endeared his thought and service by his hymns,
					-
					-
						That mortal cats before the rest, and finds sufficiency of food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Agni, in truth, is passing wise, most skilled in ordering, a Seer.
					-
					-
						At sacrifices Manus' sons glorify Agni as their Priest.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 3
				-
					-
						The foeman's wealth in many a place, Agni, is emulous to help.
					-
					-
						Men fight the fiend, and seek by rites to overcome the riteless foe.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Agni bestows the hero chief, winner of waters, firm in fray.
					-
					-
						Soon as they look upon his might his enemies tremble in alarm.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 5
				-
					-
						For with his wisdom Agni, God, protects the mortal from reproach,
					-
					-
						Whose conquering wealth is never checked, is never checked in deeds of
						might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 14: Verse 6
				-
					-
						O Agni, God with Mitra's might call hither the favour of the Gods from
						earth and heaven.
					-
					-
						Bring weal from heaven that men may dwell securely. May we o'ercome the
						foe's malign oppressions, may we o'ercome them, through thy help o'ercome
						them.
					-
			-
				Mandala 6: Hymn 15
			-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WITH this my song I strive to reach this guest of yours, who wakes at early
						morn, the Lord of all the tribes.
					-
					-
						Each time he comes from heaven, the Pure One from of old: from ancient days
						the Child cats everlasting food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Whom, well-dis sed, the Blirgus stablished as a rriend, whom men must
						glorify, high-flaming in the wood.
					-
					-
						As such, most friendly, thou art every day extolled in lauds by Vitahavya,
						O thou wondrous God.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Be thou the foeless helper of the skilful man, subduer of the enemy near or
						far away.
					-
					-
						Bestow a wealthy home on men, O Son of Strength. Give Vitahavya riches
						spreading far and wide, give Bharadvaja wide-spread wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 6: Hymn 15: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Him, your refulgent guest, Agni who comes from heaven, the Herald of
						mankind, well-skilled in sacred rites,
