				-
					-
						Come unto us who bring the juice, come unto this our eulogy,
					-
					-
						Fair-visored! drink thou of the juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 5
				-
					-
						I pour it down within thee, so through all thy members let it spread:
					-
					-
						Take with. thy tongue the pleasant drink.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Sweet to thy body let it be, delicious be the savoury juice:
					-
					-
						Sweet be the Soma to thine heart.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Like women, let this Soma-draught, invested with its robe, approach,
					-
					-
						O active Indra, close to thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Indra, transported with the juice, vast in his bulk, strong in his neck
					-
					-
						And stout arms, smites the Vrtras down.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 9
				-
					-
						O Indra, go thou forward, thou who rulest over all by might:
					-
					-
						Thou Vrtra-slayer slay the fiends,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Long be thy grasping-hook wherewith thou givest ample wealth to him
					-
					-
						Who sheds the juice and worships thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Here, Indra, is thy Soma-draught, made pure upon the sacred grass:
					-
					-
						Run hither, come and drink thereof.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Famed for thy radiance, worshipped well this juice is shed for thy delight
					-
					-
						Thou art invoked, Akhandala!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 13
				-
					-
						To Kundapayya, grandson's son, grandson of Srngavrs! to thee,
					-
					-
						To him have I addressed my thought.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Strong pillar thou, Lord of the home armour of Soma-offerers:
					-
					-
						The drop of Soma breaketh all the strongholds down, and Indra is the Rsis'
						Friend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 17: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Holy Prdikusanu, winner of the spoil, one eminent o'er many men,
					-
					-
						Lead on the wild horse Indra with his vigorous grasp forward to drink the
						Soma juice.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 18
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Now let the mortal offer prayer to win the unexampled grace
					-
					-
						Of these Adityas and their aid to cherish life.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For not an enemy molests the paths which these Adityas tread:
					-
					-
						Infallible guards, they strengthen us in happiness.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Now soon may Bhaga, Savitar, Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman
					-
					-
						Give us the shelter widely spread which we implore.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 4
				-
					-
						With Gods come thou whose fostering care none checks, O Goddesss Aditi:
					-
					-
						Come, dear to many, with the Lords who guard us well.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 5
				-
					-
						For well these Sons of Aditi know to keep enmities aloof,
					-
					-
						Unrivalled, giving ample room, they save from woe.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Aditi guard our herd by day, Aditi, free from guile, by night,
					-
					-
						Aditi, ever strengthening, save us from grief!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 7
				-
					-
						And in the day our hymn is this: May Aditi come nigh to help,
					-
					-
						With loving-kindness bring us weal and chase our foes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 8
				-
					-
						And may the Asvins, the divine Pair of Physicians, send us health:
					-
					-
						May they remove iniquity and chase our foes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 9
				-
					-
						May Agni bless us with his fires, and Surya warm us pleasantly:
					-
					-
						May the pure Wind breathe sweet on us, and chase our foes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Drive ye disease and strife away, drive ye away malignity:
					-
					-
						Adityas, keep us ever far from sore distress.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Remove from us the arrow, keep famine, Adityas! far away:
					-
					-
						Keep enmities afar from us, Lords of all wealth!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Now, O Adityas, grant to us the shelter that lets man go free,
					-
					-
						Yea, even the sinner from his sin, ye Bounteous Gods 1
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Whatever mortal with the powe r of demons fain would injure us,
					-
					-
						May he, impetuous, suffer harm by his own deeds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 14
				-
					-
						May sin o'ertake our human foe, the man who speaketh evil thing,
					-
					-
						Him who would cause our misery, whose heart is false.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Gods, ye are with the simple ones, ye know each mortal in your hearts;
					-
					-
						Ye, Vasus, well discriminate the false and true.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Fain would we have the sheltering aid of mountains and of water-floods:
					-
					-
						Keep far from us iniquity, O Heaven and Earth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 17
				-
					-
						So with auspicious sheltering aid do ye, O Vasus, carry us
					-
					-
						Beyond all trouble and distress, borne in your ship.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Adityas, ye Most Mighty Ones, grant to our children and their seed
					-
					-
						Extended term of life that they may live long days.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Sacrifice, O Adityas, is your inward monitor: be kind,
					-
					-
						For in the bond of kindred we are bound to you.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 20
				-
					-
						The Maruts' high protecting aid, the Asvins, and the God who saves,
					-
					-
						Mitra and Varuna for weal we supplicate.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Grant us a home with triple guard, Aryaman, Mitra, Varuna!
					-
					-
						Unthreatened, Maruts! meet for praise, and filled with men.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 18: Verse 22
				-
					-
						And as we human beings, O Adityas, are akin to death,
					-
					-
						Graciously lengthen ye our lives that we may live.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 19
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 1
				-
					-
						SING praise to hiin, the Lord of Light. The Gods have made the God to be
						their messenger,
					-
					-
						And sent oblation to Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Agni, the Bounteous Giver, bright with varied flames, laud thou, O singer
						Sobhari-
					-
					-
						Him who controls this sacred food with Soma blent, who hath first claim to
						sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Thee have we chosen skilftillest in sacrifice, Immortal Priest among the
						Gods,
					-
					-
						Wise finisher of this holy rite:
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 4
				-
					-
						The Son of Strength, the blessed, brightly shining One, Agni whose light is
						excellent.
					-
					-
						May be by sacrifice win us in heaven the grace of Mitra, Varuna, and the
						Floods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 5
				-
					-
						The mortal who hath ministered to Agni with oblation, fuel, ritual lore,
					-
					-
						And reverence, skilled in sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Verily swift to run are his fleet-footed steeds, and most resplendent fame
						is his.
					-
					-
						No trouble caused by Gods or wrought by mortal man from any side o'ertaketh
						him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 7
				-
					-
						May we by thine own fires be well supplied with fire, O Son of Strength, O
						Lord of Might:
					-
					-
						Thou as our Friend hast worthy men.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Agni, who praises like a guest of friendly mind, is as a car that brings us
						gear.
					-
					-
						Also in thee is found perfect security thou art the Sovran Lord of wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 9
				-
					-
						That man, moreover, merits praise who brings, auspicious Agni, sacrificial
						gifts
					-
					-
						May he win riches by his thoughts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 10
				-
					-
						He for whose sacrifice thou standest up erect is prosperous and rules o'er
						men.
					-
					-
						He wins with coursers and with singers killed in song: with heroes he
						obtains the prize.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 11
				-
					-
						He in whose dwelling Agni is chief ornament, and, all-desired, loves his
						laud well,
					-
					-
						And zealously tends his offerings-
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 12
				-
					-
						His, or the lauding sage's word, his, Son of Strength! who Is most prompt
						with sacred gifts,
					-
					-
						Set thou beneath the Gods, Vasu, above mankind, the speech of the
						intelligent.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 13
				-
					-
						He who with sacrificial gifts or homage bringeth very skilful Agni nigh,
					-
					-
						Or him who flashes fast with song,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 14
				-
					-
						The mortal who with blazing fuel, as his laws command, adores the Perfect
						God,
					-
					-
						Blest with his thoughts in splendour shall exceed all men, as though he
						overpassed the floods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Give us the splendour, Agni, which may overcome each greedy fiend in our
						abode,
					-
					-
						The wrath of evil-hearted folk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 16
				-
					-
						That, wherewith Mitra, Varuna, and Aryaman, the Asvins, Bhaga give us
						light,
					-
					-
						That may we, by thy power finding best furtherance, worship, O Indra,
						helped by thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 17
				-
					-
						O Agni, most devout are they, the sages who have set thee Sage exceeding
						wise,
					-
					-
						O God, for men to look upon:
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Who have arranged thine altar Blessed God, at morn brought thine oblation,
						pressed the juice.
					-
					-
						They by their deeds of strength have won diem, mighty wealth, who have set
						all their hope in thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 19
				-
					-
						-May Agni worshipped bring us bliss, may the gift, Blessed One, and
						sacrifice bring bliss;
					-
					-
						Yea, may our praises bring us bliss.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Show forth the mind that brings success in war with fiends, wherewith thou
						conquerest in fight.
					-
					-
						Bring down the many firm hopes of our enemies, and let us vanquish with
						thine aid.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 21
				-
					-
						I praise with song the Friend of man, whom Gods sent down to be herald and
						messenger,
					-
					-
						Best worshipper, bearer of our gifts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Thou unto sharp-toothed Agni, Young and Radiant God, proclaimest with thy
						song the feast-
					-
					-
						Agni, who for our sweet strains moulds heroic strength when sacred oil is
						offered him,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 23
				-
					-
						While, served with sacrificial oil, now upward and now downward Agni moves
						his sword,
					-
					-
						As doth the Asura his robe.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 24
				-
					-
						The God, the Friend of man, who bears our gifts to heaven, the God with his
						sweet-smelling mouth,
					-
					-
						Distributes, skilled in sacrifice, his precious things, Invoking Priest,
						Immortal God.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Son of Strength, Agni, if thou wert the mortal, bright as Mitra, I
						worshipped with our gifts!
					-
					-
						And I were the Immortal God
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 26
				-
					-
						I would not give thee up, Vasu, to calumny, or misery, O Bounteous One.
					-
					-
						My worshipper should feel no hunger or distress, nor, Agni, should he live
						in sin.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 27
				-
					-
						Like a son cherished in his father's house, let our oblation rise unto the
						Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 28
				-
					-
						With thine immediate aid may I, excellent Agni, ever gain my wish
					-
					-
						A mortal with a God to help.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 29
				-
					-
						O Agni, by thy wisdom, by thy bounties, by thy leading may I gather wealth.
					-
					-
						Excellent Agni, thou art called my Providence: delight thou to be liberal.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 30
				-
					-
						Agni, he conquers by thine aid that brings him store of noble heroes and
						great strength,
					-
					-
						Whose bond of friendship is thy choice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 31
				-
					-
						Thy spark is black and crackling, kindled in due time, O Bounteous, it is
						taken up.
					-
					-
						Thou art the dear Friend of the mighty Mornings: thou shinest in
						glimmerings of the night.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 32
				-
					-
						We Sobharis have come to him, for succour, who is good to help with
						thousand powers,
					-
					-
						The Sovran, Trasadasyu's Friend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 33
				-
					-
						O Agni, thou on whom all other fires depend, as branches on the parent
						stem,
					-
					-
						I make the treasures of the folk, like songs, mine own, while I exalt thy
						sovran might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 34
				-
					-
						The mortal whom, Adityas, ye, Guilelew, lead to the farther bank
					-
					-
						Of all the princes, Bounteous Ones
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 35
				-
					-
						Whoe'er he be, Man-ruling Kings! the Regent of the race of men-
					-
					-
						May we, O Mitra, Varuna, and Aryaman, like him be furtherers of your law.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 36
				-
					-
						A gift of fifty female slaves hath Trasadasyu given me, Purukutsa's son,
					-
					-
						Most liberal, kind, lord of the brave.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 19: Verse 37
				-
					-
						And Syava too for me led forth a strong steed at Suvastu's ford:
					-
					-
						A herd of three times seventy kine, good lord of gifts, he gave to me.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 20
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 1
				-
					-
						LET none, Swift Travellers! check you: come hither, like-spirited, stay not
						far away,
					-
					-
						Ye benders even of what is firm.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Maruts, Rbhuksans, Rudras come ye with your cars strong-fellied and
						exceeding bright.
					-
					-
						Come, ye for whom we long, with food, to sacrifice, come ye with love to
						Sobbari.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 3
				-
					-
						For well we know the vigorous might of Rudra's Sons, the Martits, who are
						passing strong,
					-
					-
						Swift Visnu's band, who send the rain.,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Islands are bursting forth and misery is stayed: the heaven and earth are
						joined in one.
					-
					-
						Decked with bright rings, ye spread the broad expanses out, when ye, Self.
						luminous, stirred yourselves.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Even things immovable shake and reel, the mountains and the forest trees at
						your approach,
					-
					-
						And the earth trembles as ye come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 6
				-
					-
						To lend free course, O Maruts, to your furious rush, heaven high and higher
						still gives way,
					-
					-
						Where they, the Heroes mighty with their arms, display their gleaming
						omaments on their forms.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 7
				-
					-
						After their Godlike nature they, the bull. like Heroes, dazzling and
						impetuous, wear
					-
					-
						Great splendour as they show erect.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 8
				-
					-
						The pivot of the Sobharis' chariot within the golden box is balmed with
						milk.
					-
					-
						May they the Well-born, Mighty, kindred of the Cow, aid us to food and to
						delight.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Bring, ye who sprinkle balmy drops. oblations to your vigorous Marut
						company,
					-
					-
						To those whose leader is the Bull.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Come hither, O ye Mares, on your stronghorsed car, solid in look, with
						solid naves.
					-
					-
						Lightly like winged falcons, O ye Heroes, come, come to enjoy our
						ofrerings.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Their decoration is the same: their omaments of gold are bright upon their
						arms;
					-
					-
						Their lances glitter splendidly.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 12
				-
					-
						They toil not to defend their bodies from attack, strong Heroes with their
						mighty arms.
					-
					-
						Strong are your bows and strong the weapons in your cars, and glory sits on
						every face.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Whose name extendeth like a sea, alone, resplendent, so that all have joy
						in it,
					-
					-
						And life-power like ancestral might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Pay honour to these Maruts and sing praise to them, for of the wheel-spokes
						of the car
					-
					-
						Of these loud roarers none is last: this is their power, this moves them to
						give mighty gifts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Blest by your favouring help was he, O Maruts, at the earlier flushings of
						the morn,
					-
					-
						And even now shall he be blest.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 16
				-
					-
						The strong man to whose sacrifice, O Heroes, ye approach that ye may taste
						thereof,
					-
					-
						With glories and with war that winneth spoil shall gain great bliss, ye
						Shakers of the world.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Even as Rudra's Sons, the brood of the Creator Dyaus, the Asura, desire,
					-
					-
						O Youthful Ones, so shall it be:
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 18
				-
					-
						And these the bounteous, worthy of the Maruts who move onward pouring down
						the rain-
					-
					-
						Even for their sake, O Youthful Ones, with kindest heart take us to you to
						be your own.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 19
				-
					-
						O Sobhari, with newest song sing out unto the youthful purifying Bulls,
					-
					-
						Even as a plougher to his steers.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Who, like a celebrated boxer, overcome the challengers in every fight:
					-
					-
						They who, like shining bulls, are most illustrious-honour those Maruts with
						thy song.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Allied by common ancestry, ye Maruts, even the Cows, alike in energy,
					-
					-
						Lick, all by turns, each other's head.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Even mortal man, ye Dancers breast adorned with gold, attains to
						brotherhood with you.
					-
					-
						Mark ye and notice us, O Maruts; evermore your friendship is secured to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 23
				-
					-
						O Maruts, rich in noble gifts, bring us a portion of the Maruts' medicine,
					-
					-
						Ye Coursers who are Friends to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Haters of those who serve you not, bliss-bringers, bring us bliss with
						those auspicious aids
					-
					-
						Wherewith ye are victorious and guard Sindhu well, and succour Krvi in his
						need.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Maruts, who rest on fair trimmed grass, what balm soever Sindhu or Asikni
						hath,
					-
					-
						Or mountains or the seas contain.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 20: Verse 26
				-
					-
						Ye carry on your bodies, ye who see it all: so bless us graciously
						therewith.
					-
					-
						Cast, Maruts, to the ground our sick man's malady: replace the dislocated
						limb.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 21
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WE call on thee, O Matchless One! We seeking help, possessing nothing firm
						ourselves,
					-
					-
						Call on thee wonderful in fight
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 2
				-
					-
						On thee for aid in sacrifice. This youth of ours, the bold, the mighty,
						hath gonse forth.
					-
					-
						We therefore, we thy friends, Indra, havie chosen thee, free-giver, as our
						Guardian God.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Come hither, for the drops are here, O Lord of corn-lands. Lord of horses,
						Lord of kine:
					-
					-
						Drink thou the Soma, Soma's Lord!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 4
				-
					-
						For we the kinless singers have drawn hither thee, O Indra, who hast
						numerous kin.
					-
					-
						With all the forms thou hast, comic thou of bull-like strength, come near
						to drink the Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Sitting like birds beside thy meath., mingled with milk, that gladdeneth
						and exalteth thee,
					-
					-
						Indra, to thee we sing aloud.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 6
				-
					-
						We speak to thee with this our reverential prayer. Why art thou pondering
						yet awhile?
					-
					-
						Here are our wishes; thou art liberal, Lord of Bays: we and our hymns are
						present here.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 7
				-
					-
						For not in recent times alone, O Indra, Thunder-armed, have we obtained
						thine aid.
					-
					-
						Of old we knew thy plenteous wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Hero, we knew thy friendship and thy rich rewards: these, Thunderer, now we
						crave of thee.
					-
					-
						O Vasu, for all wealth that cometh of the kine, sharpen our powers,
						fair-visored God.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Him who of old hath brought to us this and that blessing, him I magnify for
						you,
					-
					-
						Even Indra, O my friends, for help
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Borne by Bay Steeds, the Lord of heroes, ruling men, for it is he who
						takes; delight.
					-
					-
						May Maghavan bestow on us his worshippers hundreds of cattle and of steeds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Hero, may we, with thee for Friend, withstand the man who pants against us
						in his wrath,
					-
					-
						In fight with people rich in kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 12
				-
					-
						May we be victors in the singer's battlesong, and meet the wicked, Much
						invoked!
					-
					-
						With heroes smite the foeman and show forth our strength. O Indra, further
						thou our thoughts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 13
				-
					-
						O Indra, from all ancient time rivalless ever and companionless art thou:
					-
					-
						Thou seekest comradeship in war.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Thou findest not the wealthy man to be thy friend: those scorn thee who are
						flown with wine.
					-
					-
						What time thou thunderest and gatherest, then thou, even as a Father, art
						invoked.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 15
				-
					-
						O Indra, let us not, like fools who waste their lives at home, with
						friendship such as thine
					-
					-
						Sit idly by the poured-out juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Giver of kine, may we not miss thy gracious gifts: let us not rob thee of
						thine own.
					-
					-
						Strip even the strong places of the foe, and bring: thy gifts can never be
						made vain.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Indra or blest Sarasvati alone bestows such wealth, treasure so great, or
						thou,
					-
					-
						O Citra, on the worshipper.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 21: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Citra is King, and only kinglings are the rest who dwell beside Sarasvati.
					-
					-
						He, like Parjanya with his rain, hath spread himself with thousand, yea,
						with myriad gifts.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 22
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 1
				-
					-
						HITHERWARD have I called to-day, for succour, that most wondrous car
					-
					-
						Which ye ascended, Asvins, ye whose paths are red, swift to give Car, for
						Surya's sake.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Car ever young, much longed-for, easily invoked, soon guided, first in
						deeds of might,
					-
					-
						Which waits and serves, O Sobhari, with benevolence, without a rival or a
						foe.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 3
				-
					-
						These Asvins with our homage, these Two Omnipresent Deities
					-
					-
						Hitherward will we bring for kind help, these who seek the dwelling of the
						worshipper.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 4
				-
					-
						One of your chariot wheels is moving swiftly round, one speeds for you its
						onward course.
					-
					-
						Like a milch-cow, O Lords of splendour, and with haste let your benevolence
						come to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 5
				-
					-
						That chariot of yours which hath a triple seat and reins of gold,
					-
					-
						The famous car that traverseth the heaven and earth, thereon Nasatyas,
						Asvins, come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Ye with your plough, when favouring Manu with your help, ploughed the first
						harvest in the sky.
					-
					-
						As such will we exalt you, Lords of splendour, now, O Asvins, with our
						prayer and praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Come to us, Lords of ample wealth, by paths of everlasting Law,
					-
					-
						Whereby to high dominion ye with mighty strength raised Trksi, Trasadasyu's
						son.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 8
				-
					-
						This Soma pressed with stones is yours, ye Heroes, Lords of plenteous
						wealth.
					-
					-
						Approach to drink the Soma, come, drink in the worshipper's abode.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 9
				-
					-
						O Asvins, mount the chariot, mount the golden seat, ye who are Lords of
						plenteous wealth,
					-
					-
						And bring to us abundant food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 10
				-
					-
						The aids wherewith ye helped Paktha and Adhrigt;, and Babhru severed from
						his friends,-
					-
					-
						With those, O Asvins, come hither with speed and soon, and heal whatever is
						diseased.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 11
				-
					-
						When we continually invoke the Asvins, the resistless, at this time of day,
					-
					-
						We lovers of the song, with songs.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Through these, ye Mighty Ones, come hither to my call which brings all
						blessings, wears all forms,-
					-
					-
						Tlirough which, All-present Heroes, lavishest of food ye strengthened Krvi,
						come through these.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 13
				-
					-
						I speak to both of these as such, these Asvins whom I reverence at this
						time of day:
					-
					-
						With homage we entreat them both.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Ye who are Lords of splendour, ye whose paths are red, at eve, at mom, at
						sacrifice,
					-
					-
						Give us not utterly as prey to mortal foe, ye Rudras, Lords of ample
						wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 15
				-
					-
						For bliss I call. the blissful car, at morn the inseparable Asvins with
						their car
					-
					-
						I call, like Sobhari our sire.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Rapid as thought, and strong, and speeding to thejoy, bringing.your
						swiftly-coming help,
					-
					-
						Be to us a protection even from far away Lords of great wealth, with many
						aids.'
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Come, Wonder-Workers, to our home, our home, O Asvins, rich in cattle,
						steeds, and gold,
					-
					-
						Chief drinkers of the Soma's juice
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 22: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Choice-worthy strength, heroic, firm and excellent, uninjured by the Raksas
						foe,
					-
					-
						At this your coming nigh, ye Lords of ample wealth and all good things, may
						we obtain.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 23
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WORSHIP thou Jatavedas, pray to him who willingly accepts,
					-
					-
						Whose smoke wanders at will, and none may grasp his flame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Thou, all men's friend, Visvamanas, exaltest Agni with thy song,
					-
					-
						The Giver, and his flames with which no cars contend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Whose resolute assault, to win vigour and food, deserves our praise,-
					-
					-
						Through whose discovering power the priest obtaineth wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Up springs the imperishable flame, the flame of the Refulgent One
					-
					-
						Most bright, with glowing jaws and glory in his train.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Skilled in fair sacrifice, extolled, arise in Godlike loveliness,
					-
					-
						Shining with lofty splendour, with effulgent light.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Called straight to our oblations, come, O Agni, through our eulogies,
					-
					-
						As thou hast been our envoy bearing up our gifts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 7
				-
					-
						I call your Agni, from of old Invoking Priest of living men:
					-
					-
						Him with this song I laud and magnify for you.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Whom, wondrous wise, they animate with solemn rites and his fair form,
					-
					-
						Kind as a friend to men who keep the holy Law.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Him, true to Law, who perfecteth the sacrifice,. Law-loving ones!
					-
					-
						Ye with your song have gratified in the place of prayer.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 10
				-
					-
						May all our sacrifices go to him the truest Angiras,
					-
					-
						Who is among mankind the most illustrious Priest.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Imperishable Agni, thine are all these high enkindled lights,
					-
					-
						Like horses and like stallions showing forth their strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 12
				-
					-
						So give us, Lord of Power and Might, riches combined with hero strength,
					-
					-
						And guard us with our sons and grand. sons in our frays.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Soon as the eager Lord of men is friendly unto Manti's race,
					-
					-
						Agni averteth from us all the demon host.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 14
				-
					-
						O Hero Agni, Lord of men, on hearing this new laud of mine,
					-
					-
						Burn down the Raksasas, enchanters, with thy flame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 15
				-
					-
						No mortal foe can e'er prevail by arts of magic over him
					-
					-
						Who serveth Agni well with sacrificial gifts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Vyasva the sage, who sought the Bull, hath won thee, finder of good things:
					-
					-
						As such may we enkindle thee for ample wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Usana Kavya stablished thee, O Agni, as Invoking Priest:
					-
					-
						Thee, Jatavedas, Sacrificing Priest for man.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 18
				-
					-
						All Deities of one accord appointed thee their messenger:
					-
					-
						Thou, God, through hearing, hadst first claim to sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Him may the mortal hero make his own immortal messenger.
					-
					-
						Far-spreading, Purifier, him whose path is black.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 20
				-
					-
						With lifted ladles let us call him splendid with his brilliant flame,
					-
					-
						Men's ancient Agni, wasting not, adorable.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 21
				-
					-
						The man who pays the worship due to him with sacrificial gifts
					-
					-
						Obtains both plenteous nourishment and hero fame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 22
				-
					-
						To Jatavedas Agni, chief in sacrifices, first of all
					-
					-
						With homage goes the ladle rich with sacred gifts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Even as Vyatya did, may we with these most high and liberal hymns
					-
					-
						Pay worship unto Agni of the splendid flame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Now sing, as Sthurayupa sang, with lands to him who spreadeth far,
					-
					-
						To Agni of the home, O Rsi, Vyasva's son.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 25
				-
					-
						As welcome guest of human kind, as offspring of the forest kings,
					-
					-
						The sages worship ancient Agni for his aid.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 26
				-
					-
						For men's oblations brought to him who is the mighty Lord of all,
					-
					-
						Sit, Agni, mid our homage, on the sacred grass.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 27
				-
					-
						Grant us abundant. treasures, grant the opulence which many crave,
					-
					-
						With store of heroes, progeny, and high renown.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 28
				-
					-
						Agni, Most Youthful of the Gods, send evermore the gift of wealth
					-
					-
						Unto Varosusaman and to all his folk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 29
				-
					-
						A mighty Conqueror art thou, O Agni, so disclose to us
					-
					-
						Food in our herds of kine and gain of ample wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 23: Verse 30
				-
					-
						Thou, Agni, art a glorious God: bring hither Mitra, Varuna,
					-
					-
						Imperial Sovrans, holy-minded, true to Law.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 24
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 1
				-
					-
						COMPANIONS, let us learn a prayer to Indra. whom the thunder arms,
					-
					-
						To glorify your bold and most heroic Friend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For thou by slaying Vrtra art the Vrtra-slayer, famed for might.
					-
					-
						Thou, Hero, in rich gifts surpassest wealthy chiefs.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 3
				-
					-
						As such, when glorified, bring us riches of very wondrous fame,
					-
					-
						Set in the highest rank, Wealth-giver, Lord of Bays!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Yea, Indra, thou disclosest that preeminent dear wealth of men:
					-
					-
						Boldly, O Bold One, glorified, bring it to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 5
				-
					-
						The workers of destruction stay neither thy right hand nor thy left:
					-
					-
						Nor hosts that press about thee, Lord of Bays, in fight.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 6
				-
					-
						O Thunder-armed, I come with songs to thee as to a stall with kine:
					-
					-
						Fulfil the wish and thought of him who sings thy praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Chief Vrtra-slayer, through the hymn of Visvamanas think of all,
					-
					-
						All that concerneth us, Excellent, Mighty Guide.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 8
				-
					-
						May we, O Vrtra-slayer, O Hero, find this thy newest boon, Longed-for, and
						excellent, thou who art much invoked!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 9
				-
					-
						O Indra, Dancer, Much-invoked! as thy great power is unsurpassed,
					-
					-
						So be thy bounty to the worshipper unchecked.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Most Mighty, most heroic One, for mighty bounty fill thee full.
					-
					-
						Though strong, strengthen thyself to win wealth, Maghavan!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 11
				-
					-
						O Thunderer, never have our prayers gone forth to any God but thee:
					-
					-
						So help us, Maghavan, with thine assistance now.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 12
				-
					-
						For, Dancer, verily I find none else for bounty, saving thee,
					-
					-
						For splendid wealth and power, thou Lover of the Song.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 13
				-
					-
						For Indra pour ye out the drops meath blent with Soma let him drink
					-
					-
						With bounty and with majesty will he further us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 14
				-
					-
						I spake to the Bay Coursers' Lord, to him who gives ability:
					-
					-
						Now hear the son of Asva as he praises thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Never was any Hero born before thee mightier than thou:
					-
					-
						None certairdy like thee in goodness and in wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 16
				-
					-
						O ministering priest, pour out of the sweet juice what gladdens most:
					-
					-
						So is the Hero praised who ever prospers us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Indra, whom Tawny Coursers bear, praise such as thine, preeminent,
					-
					-
						None by his power or by his goodness hath attained.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 18
				-
					-
						We, seeking glory, have invoked this Master of all power and might
					-
					-
						Who must be glorified by constant sacri fice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Come, sing we praise to Indra, friends, the Hero who deserves the laud,
					-
					-
						Him who with none to aid o'ercomes all tribes of men.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 20
				-
					-
						To him who wins the kine, who keeps no cattle back, Celestial God,
					-
					-
						Speak wondrous speech more sweet than butter and than meath.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Whose hero powers are measureless, whose bounty ne'er may be surpassed,
					-
					-
						Whose liberality, like light, is over all.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 22
				-
					-
						As Vyasva did, praise Indra, praise the Strong unfluctuating Guide,
					-
					-
						Who gives the foe's possessions to the worshipper.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Now, son of Vyasva, praise thou him who to the tenth time still is new,
					-
					-
						The very Wise, whom living men must glorify
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Thou knowest, Indra, Thunder-armed, how to avoid destructive powers,
					-
					-
						As one secure from pitfalls each returning day.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 25
				-
					-
						O Indra, bring that aid wherewith of old, Most Wondrous! thou didst slay
					-
					-
						His foes for active Kutsa: send it down to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 26
				-
					-
						So now we seek thee fresh in might, Most Wonderful in act! for gain:
					-
					-
						For thou art he who conquers all our foes for us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 27
				-
					-
						Who will set free from ruinous woe, or Arya on the Seven Streams:
					-
					-
						O valiant Hero, bend the Dasa's weapon down.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 28
				-
					-
						As to Varosusaman thou broughtest great riches, for their gain,
					-
					-
						To Vyasva's sons, Blest Lady, rich in ample wealth!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 29
				-
					-
						Let Narya's sacrificial meed reach Vyasva's Soma-bearing sons:
					-
					-
						In hundreds and in thousands be the great reward.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 24: Verse 30
				-
					-
						If one should ask thee, Where is he who sacrificed? Whither lookest thou?
					-
					-
						Like Vala he hath passed away and dwelleth now on Gomati.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 25
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 1
				-
					-
						I WORSHIP you who guard this All, Gods, holiest among the Gods,
					-
					-
						You, faithful to the Law, whose power is sanctified.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 2
				-
					-
						So, too, like charioteers are they, Mitra and sapient Varuna,
					-
					-
						Sons high-born from of old, whose holy laws stand fast.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 3
				-
					-
						These Twain, possessors of all wealth, most glorious, for supremest sway
					-
					-
						Aditi, Mighty Mother, true to Law, brought forth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Great Varuna and Mitra, Gods, Asuras and imperial Lords,
					-
					-
						True to Eternal Law proclaim the high decree.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 5
				-
					-
						The offspring of a lofty Power, Daksa's Two Sons exceeding strong,
					-
					-
						Who, Lords of flowing rain, dwell in the place of food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Ye who have gathered up your gifts, celestial and terrestrial food,
					-
					-
						Let your rain come to us fraught with the mist of heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 7
				-
					-
						The Twain, who from the lofty sky seem to look down on herds below,
					-
					-
						Holy, imperial Lords, are set to be revered.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 8
				-
					-
						They, true to Law, exceeding strong, have sat them down for savran rule:
					-
					-
						Princes whose laws stand fast, they have obtained their sway.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Pathfinders even better than the eye, with unobstructed sight,
					-
					-
						Even when they close their lids, observant, they perceive.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 10
				-
					-
						So may the Goddess Aditi, may the Nasatyas guard us well,
					-
					-
						The Martits guard us well,.endowed with mighty strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Do ye, O Bounteous Gods, protect our dwelling lace by day and night:
					-
					-
						With you for our defenders may we go unharmed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 12
				-
					-
						May we, unharmed, serve bountiful Visnu, the God who slayeth none:
					-
					-
						Self-moving Sindhu hear and be the first to mark.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 13
				-
					-
						This sure protection we elect, desirable and reaching far,
					-
					-
						Which Mitra, Varuna, and Aryaman afford.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 14
				-
					-
						And may the Sindhu of the floods, the Maruts, and the ASvin Pair,
					-
					-
						Boon Indra, and boon Visnu have one mind with us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Because these warring Heroes stay the enmity of every foe,
					-
					-
						As the fierce water-flood repels the furious ones.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Here this one God, the Lord of men, looks forth exceeding far and wide:
					-
					-
						And we, for your advantage, keep his holy laws.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 17
				-
					-
						We keep the old accustomed laws, the statutes of supremacy,
					-
					-
						The Iong-known laws of Mitra and of Varuna.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 18
				-
					-
						He who hath measured with his ray the boundaries of heaven and earth,
					-
					-
						And with his majesty hath filled the two worlds full,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Surya hath spread his light aloft up to the region of the sky,
					-
					-
						Like Agni all aflame when gifts are offered him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 20
				-
					-
						With him who sits afar the word is lord of food that comes from kine,
					-
					-
						Controller of the gift of unempoisoned food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 21
				-
					-
						So unto Surya, Heaven, and Earth at morning and at eve I speak.
					-
					-
						Bringing enjoyments ever rise thou up for us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 22
				-
					-
						From Uksanyayana a bay, from Harayana a white steed,
					-
					-
						And from Susaman we obtained a hamessed car.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 23
				-
					-
						These two shall bring me further gain of troops of tawny-coloured steeds,
					-
					-
						The carriers shall they be of active men of war.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 25: Verse 24
				-
					-
						And the two sages have I gained who hold the reins and bear the whip,
					-
					-
						And the two great strong coursers, with my newest song.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 26
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 1
				-
					-
						I CALL your chariot to receive united praise mid princely men,
					-
					-
						Strong Gods who pour down wealth, of never vanquished might!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Ye to Varosusaman come, Nasatyas, for this glorious rite.
					-
					-
						With your protecting aid. Strong Gods, who pour down wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 3
				-
					-
						So with oblations we invoke you, rich in ample wealth, to-day,
					-
					-
						When night hath passed, O ye who send us plenteous food.
					-
					-
						O Asvins, Heroes, let your car, famed, best to travel, come to us,
					-
					-
						And, for his glory, mark your zealous servant's lauds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Asvins, who send us precious gifts, even when offended, think of him:
					-
					-
						For ye, O Rudras, lead us safe beyond our foes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 5
				-
					-
						For, Wonder-Workers, with fleet steeds ye fly completely round this All,
					-
					-
						Stirring our thoughts, ye Lords of splendour, honey-hued.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 6
				-
					-
						With all-sustaining opulence, Asvins, come hitherward to us,
					-
					-
						Ye rich and noble Heroes, ne'er to be o'erthrown.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 7
				-
					-
						To welcome this mine offering, O ye Indra-like Nasatyas, come
					-
					-
						As Gods of best accord this day with other Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 8
				-
					-
						For we, like Vyasva, lifting up our voice like oxen, call on you:
					-
					-
						With all your loving kindness, Sages, come to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 9
				-
					-
						O Rsi, laud the Asvins well. Will they not listen to thy call?
					-
					-
						Will they not burn the Panis who are nearer them?
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 10
				-
					-
						O Heroes, listen to the son of Vyasva, and regard me here,
					-
					-
						Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman, of one accord.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Gods whom we yearn for, of your gifts, of what ye bring to us, bestow
					-
					-
						By princes' hands on me, ye Mighty, day by day.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Him whom your sacrifices clothe, even as a woman with her robe,
					-
					-
						The Asvins help to glory honouring him well.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Whoso regards your care of men as succour widest in its reach,
					-
					-
						About his dwelling go, ye Asvins, loving us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Come to us ye who pour down wealth, come to the home which men must guard:
					-
					-
						Like shafts, ye are made meet for sacrifice by song.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Most fetching of all calls, the laud, as envoy, Heroes, called to you
					-
					-
						Be it your own, O Asvin Pair.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Be ye in yonder sea of heaven, or joying in the home of food,
					-
					-
						Listen to me, Immortal Ones.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 17
				-
					-
						This river with his lucid flow attracts you, more than all the streams,-
					-
					-
						Even Sindhu with his path of gold.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 18
				-
					-
						O Asvins, with that glorious fame come hither, through our brilliant song,
					-
					-
						Come ye whose ways are marked with light.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Harness the steeds who draw the car, O Vasu, bring the well-fed pair.
					-
					-
						O Vayu, drink thou of our meath: come unto our drink-offerings.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Wonderful Vayu, Lord of Right, thou who art Tvastar's son-in-law,
					-
					-
						Thy saving succour we elect.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 21
				-
					-
						To Tvastar's son-in-law we pray for wealth whereof he hath control:
					-
					-
						For glory we seek vayu, men with juice effused.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 22
				-
					-
						From heaven, auspicious Vayu, come drive hither with thy noble steeds:
					-
					-
						Come on thy mighty car with wide-extending seat.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 23
				-
					-
						We call thee to the homes of men, thee wealthiest in noble food,
					-
					-
						And liberal as a press-stone with a horse's back.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 26: Verse 24
				-
					-
						So, glad and joyful in thine heart, do thou, God, Vayu, first of all
					-
					-
						Vouchsafe us water, strength, and thought.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 27
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 1
				-
					-
						CHEIF Priest is Agni at the laud, as stones and grass at sacrifice:
					-
					-
						With song I seek the Maruts, Brahmanaspati, Gods for help much to be
						desired.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 2
				-
					-
						I sing to cattle and to Earth, to trees, to Dawns, to Night, to plants.
					-
					-
						O all ye Vasus, ye possessors of all wealth, be ye the furtherers of our
						thoughts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Forth go, with Agni, to the Gods our sacrifice of ancient use,
					-
					-
						To the Adityas, Varuna whose Law stands fast, and the all-lightening Marut
						troop.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Lords of all wealth, may they be strengtheners of man, destroyers of his
						enemies.
					-
					-
						Lords of all wealth, do ye, with guards which none may harm, preserve our
						dwelling free from foes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Come to us with one mind to-day, come to us all with one accord,
					-
					-
						Maruts with holy song, and, Goddess Aditi, Mighty One, to our house and
						home.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Send us delightful things, ye Maruts, on your steeds: come ye, O Mitra, to
						our gifts.
					-
					-
						Let Indra, Varuna, and the Adityas sit, swift Heroes, on our sacred grass.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 7
				-
					-
						We who have trimmed the grass for you, and set the banquet in array,
					-
					-
						And pressed the Soma, call you, Varuina, like men, with sacrificial fires
						aflame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 8
				-
					-
						O Maruts, Visinu, Asvins, Pusan, haste away with minds turned hitherward to
						Me.
					-
					-
						Let the Strong Indra, famed as Vrtra's slayer, come first with the winners
						of the spoil.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Ye Guileless Gods, bestow on us a refuge strong on every side,
					-
					-
						A sure protection, Vasus, unassailable from near at hand or from afar.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Kinship have I with you, and close alliance O ye Gods, destroyers of our
						foes.
					-
					-
						Call us to our prosperity of former days, and soon to new klicity.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 11
				-
					-
						For now have I sent forth to you, that I may win a fair reward,
					-
					-
						Lords of all wealth, with homage, this my song of praise. like a milch-cow
						that faileth not.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Excellent Savitar hath mounted up on high for you, ye sure and careful
						Guides.
					-
					-
						Bipeds and quadrupeds, with several hopes and aims, and birds have settled
						to their tasks.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Singing their praise with God-like thought let us invoke each God for
						grace,
					-
					-
						Each God to bring you help, each God to strengthen you.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 14
				-
					-
						For of one spirit are the Gods with mortal man, co-sharers all of gracious
						gifts.
					-
					-
						May they increase our strength hereafter and to-day, providing case and
						ample room.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 15
				-
					-
						I laud you, O ye Guileless Gods, here where we meet to render praise.
					-
					-
						None, Varuna and Mitra, harins the mortal, man who honours and obeys your
						laws.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 16
				-
					-
						He makes his house endure, he gathers plenteous food who pays obedience to
						your will.
					-
					-
						Born in his sons anew he spreads as Law commands, and prospers every way
						unharmed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 17
				-
					-
						E'en without war he gathers wealth, and goes hisway on pleasant paths,
					-
					-
						Whom Mitra, Varuna and Aryaman protect, sharing the gift,of one accord.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 18
				-
					-
						E'en on the plain for him ye make a sloping path, an easy way where road is
						none:
					-
					-
						And far away from him the ineffectual shaft must vanish, shot at him in
						vain.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 19
				-
					-
						If ye appoint the rite to-day, kind Rulers, when the Sun ascends,
					-
					-
						Lords of all wealth, at sunset or at wakingtime, or be it at the noon of
						day,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Or, Asuras, when ye have sheltered the worshipper who goes to sacrifice, at
						eve
					-
					-
						may we, O Vasus, ye possessors of all wealth, come then into the midst of
						You.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 21
				-
					-
						If ye to-day at sunrise, or at noon, or in the gloom of eve,
					-
					-
						Lords of all riches, give fair treasure to the man, the wise man who hath
						sacrificed,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 27: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Then we, imperial Rulers, claim of you this boon, your wide protection, as
						a son.
					-
					-
						May we, Adityas, offering holy gifts, obtain that which shall bring us
						greater bliss.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 28
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 28: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THE Thirty Gods and Three besides, whose seat hath been the sacred grass,
					-
					-
						From time of old have found and gained.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 28: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Varuna, Mitra, Aryaman, Agnis, with Consorts, sending boons,
					-
					-
						To whom our Vasat! is addressed:
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 28: Verse 3
				-
					-
