					Mandala 8: Hymn 34: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Disclose to us O Hero, wealth in thousands both of kine and steeds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 34: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Bring riches hitherward to us in hundreds, thousands, myriads.
					-
					-
						Ye by command of yonder Dyaus, God bright by day! have gone to heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 34: Verse 16
				-
					-
						The thousand steeds, the mightiest troop, which we and Indra have received
					-
					-
						From Vasurocis as a gift,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 34: Verse 17
				-
					-
						The brown that match the wind in speed, and bright bay coursers fleet of
						foot,
					-
					-
						Like Suns, resplendent are they all.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 34: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Mid the Pargvata's rich gifts, swift steeds whose wheels run rapidly,
					-
					-
						I seemed to stand amid a wood.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 35
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WITH Agni and with Indra, Visnu. Varuna, with the Adityas, Rudras, Vasus,
						closely leagued;
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, O Asvins, drink the Soma
						juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 2
				-
					-
						With all the Holy Thoughts, all being Mighty Ones! in close alliance wil
						the Mountains, Heaven, and Earth;
					-
					-
						Accordant. of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, O Asvins, drink the Soma
						juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 3
				-
					-
						With all the Deities, three times eleven, here, in close alliance with the
						Maruts, Bhrgus, Floods;
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, O Asvins, drink the Soma
						juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Accept the sacrifice, attend to this my call: come nigh, O ye Twain Gods,
						to all libations here.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, O Asvins, bring us
						strengthening food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Accept our praise-song as a youth accepts a maid. Come nigh, O ye Twain
						Gods, to all libations here.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Sarya and with Dawn O Asvins, bring us
						strengthening food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Accept the songs we sing, accept the solemn rite. Conie nigh, O ye Twain
						Gods, to all libations here.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, O Asvins, bring us
						strengthening food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Ye fly as starlings fly unto the forest trees; like buffaloes ye seek the
						Soma we have shed.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, come thrice, O Asvins, to
						our home.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Ye fly like swans, like those who travel on their way; like buffaloes ye
						seek the Soma we have shed.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, come thrice, O Asvins, to
						our home.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Ye fly to our oblation like a pair of hawks; like buffaloes ye seek the
						Soma we have shed.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, come thrice, O Asvins, to
						our home.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Come hitherward and drink and satisfy yourselves, bestow upon us progeny
						and affluence.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, O Asvins, grant us
						vigorous strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Conquer your foes, protect us, praise your worshippers; bestow upon us
						progeny and affluence.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, O Asvins, grant us vigolms
						strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Slay enemies, animate men whom ye befriend; bestow upon us progeny and aff
						luence.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, O Asvins, grant us
						vigorous strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 13
				-
					-
						With Mitra, Varuna, Dharma, and the Maruts in your company approach unto
						your praiser's call.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, and with the Adityas,
						Asvins! come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 14
				-
					-
						With Visnu and the Angirases attending you, and with the Maruts come unto
						your praiser's call.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, and with the Adityas,
						Asvins! come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 15
				-
					-
						With Rbhus and With Vajas. O ye Mighty Ones, leagued with the Maruts come
						ye to your praiser's call.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, and with the Adityas,
						Asvins! come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Give spirit to our prayer and animate our thoughts; slay ye the Raksasas
						and drive away disease.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of One mind with Surya and with Dawn, -the presser's Soma,
						Asvins drink.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Strengthen the Ruling Power, strengthen the men of war; slay ye the
						Raksasas and drive away disease.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, the presser's Soma, Asvins
						drink.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Give strength unto the milch-kine, give the people strength, slay ye the
						Raksasas and drive away disease.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, the presser's Soma, Asvins
						drink.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 19
				-
					-
						As ye heard Atri's earliest eulogy, so hear Syavasva, Soma-presser, ye who
						reel in joy.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, drink juice, O Asvins,
						three days old.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Further like running streams Syavasva's eulogies who presses out the Soma,
						ye who reel in joy.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, drink juice, O Asvins,
						three days old.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Seize, as ye grasp the reins, Syavasva's solemn rites who presses out the
						Soma, ye who reel in joy.
					-
					-
						Accordant, of one mind with Surya and with Dawn, drink juice, O Asvins,
						three days old.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Drive down your chariot hitherward drink ye the Soma's savoury juice.
					-
					-
						Approach, ye Asvins, come to us: I call you, eager for your aid. Grant
						treasures to the worshipper.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 23
				-
					-
						When sacrifice which tells our reverence hath begun. Heroes! to drink the
						gushing juice,
					-
					-
						Approach, ye Asvins, come to us: I call you, eager for your aid. Grant
						treasures to the worshipper.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 35: Verse 24
				-
					-
						Sate you with consecrated drink, with juice effused, ye Deities.
					-
					-
						Approach, ye Asvins, come to us: I call you, eager for your aid. Grant
						treasures to the worshipper.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 36
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 36: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THOU helpest him whose grass is trimmed, who sheds the juice, O Satakratu,
						drink Soma to make thee glad.
					-
					-
						The share which they have fixed for thee, thou, Indra, Victor o'er all
						hosts and space, begirt with Maruts, Lord of Heroes, winner of the floods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 36: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Maghavan, help thy worshipper: let him help thee. O Satakratu, drink Soma
						to make thee glad.
					-
					-
						The share which they have fixed for thee, etc.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 36: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Thou aidest Gods with food, and that with might aidg thee,
					-
					-
						O Satakratu, drink Soma to make thee glad.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 36: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Creator of the heaven, creator of the earth, O Satakratu, drink Soma to
						make thee glad.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 36: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Father of cattle, father of all steeds art thou. O Satakratu, drink Soma to
						make thee glad.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 36: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Stone-hurler, glorify the Atris' hymn of praise. O Satakratu, drink Soma to
						make thee glad.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 36: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Hear thou Syavagva while he pours to thee, as erst thou heardest Atri when
						he wrought his holy rites.
					-
					-
						Indra, thou only gavest Trasadasyu aid in the fierce fight with heroes,
						strengthening his prayers.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 37
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 37: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THIS prayer, and those who shed the juice, in wars with Vrtra thou holpest,
						Indra, Lord of Strength, with all thy succours.
					-
					-
						O Vrtra-slayer, from libation poured at noon, drink of the Soma juice, thou
						blameless Thunderer.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 37: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Thou mighty Conqueror of hostile armaments, O Indra, Lord of Strength, with
						all thy saving help.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 37: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Sole Ruler, thou art Sovran of this world of life, O Indra, Lord of
						Strength, with all thy saving help.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 37: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Thou only sunderest these two consistent worlds, O Indra, Lord of Strength,
						with all thy saving help.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 37: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Thou art the Lord supreme o'er rest and energy, O Indra, Lord of Strength,
						with all thy saving help.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 37: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Thou helpest one to power, and one thou hast not helped, O Indra, Lord of
						Strength, with all thy saving aid.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 37: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Hear thou Syavasva while he sings to thee, as erst thou heardest Atri when
						he wrought his holy rites.
					-
					-
						Indra, thou only gavest Trasadasyu aid in the fierce fight with heroes,
						strengthening his powers.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 38
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 1
				-
					-
						YE Twain are Priests of sacrifice, wmners in war and holy works:
					-
					-
						Indra and Agni, mark this well.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Ye bounteous riders on the car, ye Vrtra-slayers unsubdued:
					-
					-
						Indra and Agni, mark this well.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 3
				-
					-
						The men with pressing-stones have pressed this meath of yours which gives
						delight:
					-
					-
						Indra, and Agni, mark this well.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Accept our sacrifice for weal, sharers of praise! the Soma shed:
					-
					-
						Indra and Agni, Heroes, come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Be pleased with these libations which attract you to our sacred gifts
					-
					-
						Indra and Agni, Heroes, come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Accept this eulogy of mine whose model is the Gayatri:
					-
					-
						Indra and Agni, Heroes, Come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Come with the early-faring Gods, ye who are Lords of genuine wealth:
					-
					-
						Indra-Agni, to the Soma-draught
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Hear ye the call of Atris, hear Syavasva as he sheds the juice:
					-
					-
						Indra-Agni to the Soma-draught
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Thus have I called you to our aid as sages called on you of old:
					-
					-
						Indra-Agni to the Soma draught!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 38: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Indra's and Agni's grace I claim, Sarasvati's associates
					-
					-
						To whom this psalm of praise is sung.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 39
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THE glorious Agni have I praised, and worshipped with. the sacred food.
					-
					-
						May Agni deck the Gods for us. Between both gathering-places he goes on his
						embassy, the Sage. May all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Agni, burn down the word within their bodies through our newest speech,
					-
					-
						All hatreds of the godless, all the wicked man's malignities. Away let the
						destroyers go. May all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Agni, I offer hymns to thee, like holy oil within thy moutlh.
					-
					-
						Acknowledge them. among the Gods, for thou art the rmost excellent, the
						worshipper's blissful messenger. Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Agni bestows all vital power even as each man supplicates.
					-
					-
						He brings the Vasus strengthening gifts, and grants deliglht, in rest and
						stir, for every calling on the Gods. Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Agni hath made himself renowned by wonderful victorious act.
					-
					-
						He is the Priest of all the tribes, chosen with sacrificial meeds. He urges
						Deities to receive. Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Agni knows all that springs from Gods, he knows the mystery of men.
					-
					-
						Giver of wealth is Agni, he uncloses both the doors to us when worshipped
						with our newest gift. Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Agni inhabiteth with Gods and men who offer sacrifice.
					-
					-
						He cherisheth with great delight much wisdom, as all things that be, God
						among Gods adorable. May all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Agni who liveth in all streams, Lord of the Sevenfold Race of men,
					-
					-
						Him dweller in three homes we seek, best slayer of the Dasytis for
						Mandhatar, first in sacrifice. Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Agni the Wise inhabiteth three gathering-places, triply formed.
					-
					-
						Decked as our envoy let the Sage bring hither and conciliate the Thrice
						Eleven Deities. Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 39: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Our Agni, thou art first among the Gods, and first mid living men.
					-
					-
						Thou only rulest over wealth. Round about thee, as natural dams,
						circumfluous the waters run. Let all the others die away.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 40
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 1
				-
					-
						INDRA and Agni, surely ye as Conquerors will give us wealth,
					-
					-
						Whereby in fight we may o'ercome that which is strong and firmly fixed, as
						Agni burns the woods with wind. Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 2
				-
					-
						We set no snares to tangle you; Indra we worship and adore, Hero of heroes
						mightiest.
					-
					-
						Once may he come unto us with his Steed, come unto us to win us strength,
						and to complete the sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 3
				-
					-
						For, famous Indra-Agni, ye are dwellers in the midst of frays.
					-
					-
						Sages in wisdom, ye are knit to him who seeketh you as friends. Heroes,
						bestow on him his wish.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Nabhaka-like, with sacred song Indra's and Agni's praise I sing,
					-
					-
						Theirs to whom all this world belongs, this heaven and this mighty earth
						which bear rich treasure in their lap.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 5
				-
					-
						To Indra and to Agni send your prayers, as was Nabhaka's wont,-
					-
					-
						Who oped with sideway opening the sea with its foundations seven-Indra all
						powerful in his might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Tear thou asunder, as of old, like tangles of a creeping plant,
					-
					-
						Demolish thou the Dasa's might. May we with Indra's help divide the
						treasure he hath gathered up.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 7
				-
					-
						What time with this same song these men call Indra-Agni sundry ways,
					-
					-
						May we with our own heroes quell those who provoke us to the fight, and
						conquer those who strive with us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 8
				-
					-
						The Two refulgent with their beams rise and come downward from the sky.
					-
					-
						By Indra's and by Agni's hest, flowing away, the rivers, run which they
						released from their restraint.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 9
				-
					-
						O Indra, many are thine aids, many thy ways of guiding us,
					-
					-
						Lord of the Bay Steeds, Hinva's Son. To a Good Hero come our prayers, which
						soon shall have accomplishment.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Inspire him with your holy hymns, the Hero bright and glorious,
					-
					-
						Him who with might demolisbeth even the brood of Susna, and winneth for us
						the heavenly streams.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Inspire him worshipped with fair rites, the glorious Hero truly brave.
					-
					-
						He brake in pieces Susna's brood who still expected not the stroke, and won
						for us the heavenly streams. Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 40: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Thus have we sung anew to Indra-Agni, as sang our sires, Angirases, and
						Mandhatar.
					-
					-
						Guard us with triple shelter and preserve us: may we be masters of a store
						of riches.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 41
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 1
				-
					-
						To make this Varuna come forth sing thou a song unto the band of Maruts
						wiser than thyself,-
					-
					-
						This Varuna who guardeth well the thoughts of men like herds of kine.
					-
					-
						Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Him altogether praise I with the song and hymns our fathers sang, and with
						Nabhaka's eulogies,-
					-
					-
						Him dwelling at the rivers' source, surrounded by his Sisters Seven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 3
				-
					-
						The nights he hath encompassed, and stablished the morns with magic art
						visible over all is he.
					-
					-
						His dear Ones, following his Law, have prospered the Three Dawns for him.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 4
				-
					-
						He, visible o'er all the earth, stablished the quarters of the sky:
					-
					-
						He measured out the eastern place, that is the fold of Varuna: like a
						strong herdsman is the God.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 5
				-
					-
						He who supports the worlds of life, he who well knows the hidden names
						mysterious of the morning beams,
					-
					-
						He cherishes much wisdom, Sage, as heaven brings forth each varied form.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 6
				-
					-
						In whom all wisdom centres, as the nave is set within the wheel.
					-
					-
						Haste ye to honour Trita, as kine haste to gather in the fold, even as they
						muster steeds to yoke.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 7
				-
					-
						He wraps these regions as a robe; he contemplates the tribes of Gods and
						all the works of mortal men.
					-
					-
						Before the home of Varuna all the Gods follow his decree.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 8
				-
					-
						He is an Ocean far-removed, yet through the heaven to him ascends the
						worship which these realms possess.
					-
					-
						With his bright foot he overthrew their magic, and went up to heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Ruler, whose bright far-seeing rays, pervading all three earths, have
						filled the three superior realms of heaven.
					-
					-
						Firm is the seat of Varuna: over the Seven he rules as King.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 41: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Who, after his decree, o'erspread the Dark Ones with a robe of light;
					-
					-
						Who measured out the ancient seat, who pillared both the worlds apart as
						the Unborn supported heaven. Let all the others die away.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 42
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 1
				-
					-
						LORD of all wealth, the Asura propped the heavens, and measured out the
						broad earth's wide expanses.
					-
					-
						He, King supreme, approached all living creatures. All these are Varuna's
						holy operations.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 2
				-
					-
						So humbly worship Varuna the Mighty revere the wise Guard of World
						Immortal.
					-
					-
						May he vouchsafe us triply-barred protection. O Earth and Heaven, within
						your lap preserve us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Sharpen this song of him who strives his utmost, sharpen, God Varuna, his
						strength and insight;
					-
					-
						May we ascend the ship that bears us safely, whereby we may pass over all
						misfortune.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Asvins, with songs the singer stones have made you hasten hitherward,
					-
					-
						Nasatyas, to the Soma-draught. Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 5
				-
					-
						As the sage Atri with his hymns, O Asvins, called you eagerly,
					-
					-
						Nasatyas, to the Soma-draught. Let all the others die away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 42: Verse 6
				-
					-
						So have I called you to our aid, even as the wise have called of old,
					-
					-
						Nasatyas, to the Soma-draught. Let all the others die away.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 43
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THESE songs of mine go forth as lauds of Agni, the disposing Sage,
					-
					-
						Whose worshipper is ne'er o'erthrawn.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Wise Agni Jatavedas, I beget a song of praise for thee.
					-
					-
						Who willingly receivest it.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Thy sharpened flames, O Agni, like the gleams of light that glitter
						through,
					-
					-
						Devour the forests with their teeth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Gold-coloured, bannered with the smoke, urged by the wind, aloft to heaven
					-
					-
						Rise, lightly borne, the flames of fire.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 5
				-
					-
						These lightly kindled fiery flames are all around made visible,
					-
					-
						Even as the glearaings of the Dawns.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 6
				-
					-
						As Jatavedas speeds along, the dust is black beneath his feet,
					-
					-
						When Agni spreads upon the earth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Making the plants his nourishment, Agni devours and wearies not,
					-
					-
						Seeking the tender shrubs again.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Bending him down with all his tongues, he flickers with his fiery glow
					-
					-
						Splendid is Agni in the woods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Agni, thine home is in the floods: into the plants thou forcest way,
					-
					-
						And as their Child art born anew.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Worshipped with offerings shines thy flame, O Agni, from the sacred oil,
					-
					-
						With kisses on the ladle's mouth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Let us serve Agni with our hymns, Disposer, fed on ox and cow,
					-
					-
						Who bears the Soma on his back.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Yea, thee, O Agni, do we seek with homage and with fuel, Priest
					-
					-
						Whose wisdom is most excellent.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 13
				-
					-
						O worshipped with oblations, pure Agni, we call on thee as erst,
					-
					-
						Did Bhrgu, Manus, Angiras.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 14
				-
					-
						For thou, O Agni, by the fire, Sage by the Sage, Good by the Good,
					-
					-
						Friend by the Friend, art lighted up.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 15
				-
					-
						So wealth in thousands, food with store of heroes give thou to the sage,
					-
					-
						O Agni, to the worshipper.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 16
				-
					-
						O Agni, Brother, made by strength, Lord of red steeds and brilliant sway,
					-
					-
						Take pleasure in this laud of mine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 17
				-
					-
						My praises, Agni, go to thee, as the cows seek the stall to meet,
					-
					-
						The lowing calf that longs for milk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Agni, best Angiras, to thee all people who have pleasant homes,
					-
					-
						Apart, have turned as to their wish.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 19
				-
					-
						The sages skilled in holy song and thin. kers with their thoughts have
						urged
					-
					-
						Agni to share the sacred feast.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 20
				-
					-
						So, Agni, unto thee the Priest, Invoker, strong in forays, pray
					-
					-
						'nose who spin out the sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 21
				-
					-
						In many a place, the same in look art thou, a Prince o'er all the tribes
					-
					-
						In battles we invoke thine aid.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Pray thou to Agni, pray to him who blazes served with sacred oil:
					-
					-
						Let him give ear to this our call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 23
				-
					-
						We call on thee as such, as one who hears, as Jatavedas, one,
					-
					-
						Agni! who beats away our foes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 24
				-
					-
						I pray to Agni, King of men, the Wonderful, the President
					-
					-
						Of holy Laws: may he give ear.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Him like a bridegroom, him who stirs all people, like a noble horse,
					-
					-
						Like a fleet steed, we instigate.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 26
				-
					-
						Slaying things deadly, burning up foes, Riksasas, on every side,
					-
					-
						Shine, Agni, with thy sharpened flame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 27
				-
					-
						Thou whom the people kindle even as Manus did, best Angiras!
					-
					-
						O Agni, mark thou this my speech.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 28
				-
					-
						O Agni, made by strength! be thou born in the heavens or born in floods,
					-
					-
						As such we call on thee with songs.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 29
				-
					-
						Yea, all the people, all the folk who have good dwellings, each apart,
					-
					-
						Send food for thee to eat thereof.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 30
				-
					-
						O Agni, so may we, devout, gazed at by men, throughout our days,
					-
					-
						Pass lightly over all distress.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 31
				-
					-
						We venerate with cheerful hearts the cheerful Agni, dear to all,
					-
					-
						Burning, with purifying flame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 32
				-
					-
						So thou, O Agni rich in light, beaming like Surya with thy rays
					-
					-
						Boldly demolishest the gloom,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 43: Verse 33
				-
					-
						We pray to thee for this thy gift, Victor the gift that faileth not,
					-
					-
						O Agni, choicest wealth from thee.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 44
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 1
				-
					-
						PAY service unto Agni with your fuel, rouse your Guest with oil:
					-
					-
						In him present your offerings.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Agni, do thou accept my laud, be magnified by this my song:
					-
					-
						Welcome my sweedy-spoken words.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Agni, envoy, I place in front; the oblation-bearer I address:
					-
					-
						Here let him seat the Deities.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Agni, the lofty flames of' thee enkindled have gone up on high,
					-
					-
						Thy bright flames, thou Refulgent One.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Beloved! let my ladles full of sacred oil come near to thee:
					-
					-
						Agni, accept our offerings.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 6
				-
					-
						I worship Agni-may he hear!-the cheerful, the Invoker, Priest,
					-
					-
						Of varied splendour, rich in light.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Ancient Invoker, meet for praise, beloved Agni, wise and strong,
					-
					-
						The visitant of solemn rites.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Agni, best Angiras, accept straightway these offerings, and guide
					-
					-
						The seasonable sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Excellent God, with brilliant flames, enkindled bring thou hitherward,
					-
					-
						Knowing the way, the Heavenly Host.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Him, Sage and Herald, void of guile, ensign of sacrifices, him
					-
					-
						Smoke-bannered, rich in light, we seek.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 11
				-
					-
						O Agni, be our Guardian thou, God, against those who injure us:
					-
					-
						Destroy our foes, thou Son of Strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Making his body beautiful, Agni the Sage hath waxen by
					-
					-
						The singer and his ancient hymn.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 13
				-
					-
						I invocate the Child of Strength, Agni with purifying flame,
					-
					-
						At this well-ordered sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 14
				-
					-
						So Agni, rich in many friends, with fiery splendour, seat thyself
					-
					-
						With Gods upon our sacred grass.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 15
				-
					-
						The mortal man who serves the God Agni within his own abode,
					-
					-
						For him he causes wealth to shine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 44: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Agni is head and height of heaven, the Master of the earth is he:
