						On all sides,. Soma, thou art our life-giver: aim of all eyes,
						light-finder, come within us.
					-
					-
						Indu, of one accord with thy protections both from behind and from before
						preserve us.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 49
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 1
				-
					-
						AGNI, come hither with thy fires; we choose thee as Invoking Priest.
					-
					-
						Let the extended ladle full of oil balm thee, best Priest, to sit on sacred
						grass.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For unto thee, O Angiras, O Son of Strength, move ladles in the sacrifice.
					-
					-
						To Agni, Child of Force, whose locks drop oil, we seek, foremost in
						sacrificial rites.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Agni, thou art Disposer, Sage, Herald, bright God! and worshipful,
					-
					-
						Best offercr, cheerful, to be praised in holy rites, pure Lord! by singers
						with their hymns.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Most Youthful and Eternal, bring the longing Gods to me, the guileless, for
						the feast.
					-
					-
						Come, Vasu, to the banquet that is well-prepared: rejoice thee, gracious,
						with our songs.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Famed art thou, Agni, far and wide, Preserver, righteous, and a Sage.
					-
					-
						The holy singers, O refulgent kindled God! arrangers, call on thee to come
						-
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Shine, Most Resplendent! blaze, send bliss unto the folk, and to thy
						worshipper
					-
					-
						Great art thou.
					-
					-
						So may my princes, with good fires, subduing foes, rest in the keeping of
						the Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 7
				-
					-
						O Agni, as thou burnest down to earth even high-grown underwood,
					-
					-
						So, bright as Mitra is, burn him who injures us, him who plots ill against
						thy friend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Give us not as a prey to mortal enemy, nor to the wicked friend of fiends.
					-
					-
						With conquering guards, auspicious, unassailable, protect us, O Most
						Youthful God.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Protect us, Agni, through the first, protect us through the second hymn,
					-
					-
						Protect us through three hymns, O Lord of Power and Might, through four
						hymns, Vasu, guard thou us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Preserve us from each fiend who brings the Gods no gift, preserve thou us
						in deeds of strength:
					-
					-
						For we possess in thee the nearest Friend of all, for service of the Gods
						and weal.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 11
				-
					-
						O Holy Agni, give us wealth renowned with men and strengthening life.
					-
					-
						Bestow on us, O Helper, that which many crave, more glorious still by
						righteousness;
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Wherewith we may o'ercome our rivals in the war, o'erpowering the foe's
						designs.
					-
					-
						So wax thou by our food, O Excellent in strength. Quicken our thoughts that
						find out wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Agni is even as a bull who whets and brandishes his horns.
					-
					-
						Well-sharpened are his jaws which may not be withstood: the Child of
						Strength hath powerful teeth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Not to be stayed, O Bull, O Agni, are thy teeth when thou art spreading far
						and wide.
					-
					-
						Make our ohlations duly offired up, O Priest, and give us store of precious
						things.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Thou liest in the wood: from both thy Mothers mortals kindle thee.
					-
					-
						Unweariedly thou bearest up the offerer's gifts, then shinest bright among
						the Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 16
				-
					-
						And so the seven priests, O Agni, worship thee, Free-giver, Everlasting
						One.
					-
					-
						Thou cIeavest through the rock with heat and fervent glow. Agni, rise up
						above the men.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 17
				-
					-
						For you let us whose grass is trimmed call Agni, Agni, restless God.
					-
					-
						Let us whose food is offered call to all the tribes Agni the Invoking
						Priest of men.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Agni, with noble psalm that tells his wish he dwells, thinking on thee who
						guardest him.
					-
					-
						Speedily bring us strength of many varied sorts to be most near to succour
						us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 19
				-
					-
						Agni, Praise-singer! Lord of men, God burner-up of Raksasas,
					-
					-
						Mighty art thou, the ever-present Household-Lord, Home-friend and Guardian
						from the sky.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 49: Verse 20
				-
					-
						Let no fiend come among us, O thou rich in light, no spell of those who
						deal in spells.
					-
					-
						To distant pastures drive faint hunger: far away, O Agni, chase the demons'
						friends.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 50
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 1
				-
					-
						BOTH boons,-may Indra, hitherward turned, listen to this prayer of ours,
					-
					-
						And mightiest Maghavan with thought inclined to us come near to drink the
						Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For him, strong, independent Ruler, Heaven and Earth have fashioned forth
						for power and might.
					-
					-
						Thou seatest thee as first among thy peers in place, for thy soul longs for
						Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Fill thyself full, O Lord of wealth, O Indra, with the juice we shed.
					-
					-
						We know thee, Lord of Bay Steeds victor in the fight, vanquishing e'en the
						invincible.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Changeless in truth, O Maghavan Indra, let it be as thou in wisdom willest
						it.
					-
					-
						May we, O fair of check, win booty with thine aid, O Thunderer, swiftly
						seeking it.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Indra, with all thy saving helps give us assistance, Lord of power.
					-
					-
						For after thee we follow even as glorious bliss, thee, Hero, finder-out of
						wealth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Increaser of our steeds and multiplying kine, a golden well, O God, art
						thou,
					-
					-
						For no one may impair the gifts laid up in thee. Bring me whatever thing I
						ask.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 7
				-
					-
						For thou,-come to the worshipper!-wilt find great wealth to make us rich.
					-
					-
						Fill thyself full, O Maghavan, for gain of kine, full, Indra, for the gain
						of steeds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Thou as thy gift bestowest many hundred herds, yea, many thousands dost
						thou give.
					-
					-
						With singers' hymns have we brought the Fort-render near, singing to Indra
						for his grace.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Whether the simple or the sage, Indra, have offered praise to thee,
					-
					-
						He Satakratu! by his love hath gladdened thee, ambitious! ever pressing on!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 10
				-
					-
						If he the Strong of arm, the breaker-down of forts, the great Destroyer,
						hear my call,
					-
					-
						We, seeking riches cry to Indra, Lord of wealth, to Satakratu with our
						lauds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 11
				-
					-
						We count not then as sinners, nor as niggardly or foolish men,
					-
					-
						When with the Soma juice which we have shed we make Indra, the Mighty One,
						our Friend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Him have we yoked in fight, the powerful Conqueror, debt-claimer, not to be
						deceived.
					-
					-
						Best charioteer, the Victor marks each fault, he knows the strong to whom
						he will come near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Indra, give us security from that whereof we are afraid.
					-
					-
						Help us, O Maghavan, let thy succour give us this: drive away foes and
						enemies.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 14
				-
					-
						For thou, O liberal Lord of bounty, strengthenest his ample home who
						worships thee.
					-
					-
						So Indra, Maghavan, thou Lover of the Song, we with pressed Soma call on
						thee,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Indra is Vrtra-slayer, guard, our best defender from the foe.
					-
					-
						May he preserve our last and middlemost, and keep watch from behind us and
						before.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Defend us from behind, below, above, in front, on all sides, Indra, shield
						us well.
					-
					-
						Keep far away from us the terror sent from heaven: keep impious weapons far
						away.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Protect us, Indra, each to-day, each morrow, and each following day.
					-
					-
						Our singers, through all days, shalt thou, Lord of the brave, keep safely
						both by day and night.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 50: Verse 18
				-
					-
						A crushing Warrior, passing rich is Maghavan, endowed with all heroic
						might.
					-
					-
						Thine arms, O Satakratu, are exceeding strong, arms which have grasped the
						thunderbolt.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 51
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 1
				-
					-
						OFFER ye up as praise to him that wherein Indra takes delight.
					-
					-
						The Soma-bringers magnify Indra's great energy with hymns. Good are the
						gifts that Indra gives.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Sole among chiefs, companionless, impetuous, and peerless, he
					-
					-
						Hath waxen great o'er many folk, yea., over all things born, in might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Lord of swift bounty, he will win e'en with a steed of worthless sort.
					-
					-
						This, Indra, must be told of thee who wilt perform heroic deeds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Come to us.hither: let us pay devotions that enhance thy might,
					-
					-
						For which, Most Potent! thou wouldst fain bless the man here who strives
						for fame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 5
				-
					-
						For thou, O Indra, makest yet more bold the spirit of the bold
					-
					-
						Who with strong Soma serveth thee, still ready with his reverent prayers.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Worthy of song, he looketh down as a man looketh into wells.
					-
					-
						Pleased with the Soma-bringer's skill he maketh him his mate and friend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 7
				-
					-
						In strength and wisdom all the Gods, Indra, have yielded unto thee.
					-
					-
						Be thou the Guard of all, O thou whom many praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Praised, Indra, is this might of thine, best for the service of the Gods,
					-
					-
						That thou with power dost slay Vrtra, O Lord of Strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 9
				-
					-
						He makes the races of mankind like synods of the Beauteous One.
					-
					-
						Indra knows this his manifest deed, and is renowned.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Thy might, O Indra, at its birth, thee also, and thy mental power,
					-
					-
						In thy care, Maghavan rich in kine! they have increased exceedingly.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 11
				-
					-
						O Vrtra-slayer, thou and I will both combine for winning spoil.
					-
					-
						Even malignity will consent, O Bolt-armed Hero, unto us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 51: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Let us extol this Indra as truthful and never as untrue.
					-
					-
						Dire is his death who pours no gifts great light hath he who offers them.
						Good are the gifts that Indra gives.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 52
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 1
				-
					-
						WITH powers of Mighty Ones hath he, Ancient, Beloved, been equipped,
					-
					-
						Through whom the Father Manu made prayers cfficacious with the Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Him, Maker of the sky, let stones wet with the Soma ne'er forsake,
					-
					-
						Nor hymns and prayer that must be said.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Indra who knew full well disclosed the kine to the Angirases.
					-
					-
						This his great deed must be extolled.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Indra, promoter of the song, the sage's Strengthener as of old,
					-
					-
						Shall come to bless and succour us at presentation of this laud.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Now after their desire's intent the pious singers with the cry
					-
					-
						Of Hail! have sung loud hymns to thee, Indra, to gain a stall of kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 6
				-
					-
						With Indra rest all deeds of might, deeds done and yet to be performed,
					-
					-
						Whom singers know devoid of guile.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 7
				-
					-
						When the Five Tribes with all their men to Indra have sent out their voice,
					-
					-
						And when the priest hath strewn much grass, this is the Friend's own
						dwellingpiace.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 8
				-
					-
						This praise is verily thine own: thou hast performed these manly deeds,
					-
					-
						And sped the wheel upon its way.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 9
				-
					-
						At the o'erflowing of this Steer, boldly he strode for life, and took
					-
					-
						Soma as cattle take their corn.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Receiving this and craving help, we, who with you are Daksa's sons,
					-
					-
						Would fain exalt the Maruts' Lord.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Yea, Hero, with the singers we sing.to the duly-coming Band.
					-
					-
						Allied with tbee may we prevail.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 52: Verse 12
				-
					-
						With us are raining Rudras, clouds accordant in call to battle, at the
						death of Vrtra,
					-
					-
						
					-
					-
						The strong assigned to him who sings and praises. May Gods with Indra at
						their head protect us.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 53
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 1
				-
					-
						MAY our hymns give thee great delight. Display thy bounty, Thunderer.
					-
					-
						Drive off the enemies of prayer.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Crush with thy foot the niggard churls who bring no gifts. Mighty art thou
					-
					-
						There is not one to equal thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Thou art the Lord of Soma pressed, Soma impressed is also thine.
					-
					-
						Thou art the Sovran of the folk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Come, go thou forth, dwelling in heaven and listening to the prayers of
						men:
					-
					-
						Thou fillest both the heavens and earth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Even that hill with rocky heights, with hundreds, thousands, held within.
					-
					-
						Thou for thy worshippers brakest through.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 6
				-
					-
						We call on thee both night and day to taste the flowing Soma juice:
					-
					-
						Do thou fulfil our heart's desire.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Where is that ever-youthful Steer, strong. necked and never yet bent down?
					-
					-
						What Brahman ministers to him?
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 8
				-
					-
						To whose libation doth the Steer, betake him with delight therein?
					-
					-
						Who takes delight in Indra now?
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Whom, Vrtra-slayer, have thy gift and hero powers accompanied?
					-
					-
						Who is thy dearest in the laud?
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 10
				-
					-
						For thee among mankind, among the Purus is this Soma shed.
					-
					-
						Hasten thou hither: drink thereof.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 11
				-
					-
						This, growing by Soma and by Saryanavan, dear to thee,
					-
					-
						In Arjikiya, cheers thee best.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 53: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Hasten thou hitherward, and drink this for munificence to-day,
					-
					-
						Delightful for thine eager draught.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 54
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THOUGH, Indra, thou art called by men from east and west, from north and
						soutb,
					-
					-
						Come hither quickly with fleet steeds
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 2
				-
					-
						If in the effluence of heaven, rich in its light, thou takest joy,
					-
					-
						Or in the sea in Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 3
				-
					-
						With songs I call thee, Great and Wide, even as a cow to profit us,
					-
					-
						Indra, to drink the Soma-draught.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Hither, O Indra, let thy Bays bear up and, bring upon thy car
					-
					-
						Thy glory, God! and majesty.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Thou, Indra, wouldst be sung and praised as great, strong, lordly in thy
						deeds
					-
					-
						Come hither, drink our Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 6
				-
					-
						We who have shed the Soma and prepared the feast are calling thee.
					-
					-
						To sit on this our sacred grass.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 7
				-
					-
						As, Indra, thou art evermore the common Lord of all alike,
					-
					-
						As such we invocate thee now.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 8
				-
					-
						The men with stones have milked for thee this nectar of the Soma juice:
					-
					-
						Indra, be pleased with it, and drink.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Neglect all pious men with skill in sacred song: come hitherward,
					-
					-
						With speed, and give us high renown.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Gods, may the mighty rest unharmed, the King who gives me spotted kine,
					-
					-
						Kine decked with golden ornaments.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 54: Verse 11
