				-
					-
						The noble, Suradeva's son, hath brought a calf, led by the car to three of
						us.
					-
					-
						As a chief brings a goat to milk.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 60
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 1
				-
					-
						O AGNI, with thy mighty wealth guard us from all malignity,
					-
					-
						Yea, from all hate of mortal man.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 2
				-
					-
						For over thee, O Friend from birih, the wrath of man hath no control:
					-
					-
						Nay, Guardian of the earth art thou.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 3
				-
					-
						As such, with all the Gods, O Son of Strength, auspicious in thy flame.
					-
					-
						Give us wealth bringing all things good.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Malignities stay not from wealth the mortal man whom, Agni, thou
					-
					-
						Protectest while he offers gifts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Sage Agni, be whom thou dost urge, in worship of the Gods, to wealth,
					-
					-
						With thine assistance winneth kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Riches with many heroes thou hast for the man who offers gifts:
					-
					-
						Lead thou us on to higher bliss.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Save us, O Jatavedas, nor abandon us to him who sins,
					-
					-
						Unto the evil-hearted man.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 8
				-
					-
						O Agni, let no godless man avert thy bounty as a God:
					-
					-
						Over all treasures thou art Lord.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 9
				-
					-
						So, Son of Strength, tbou aidest us to what is great and excellent.
					-
					-
						Those, Vasu! Friend! who sing thy praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Let our songs come anear to him beauteous and bright with piercing flame
					-
					-
						Our offerings, with our homage, to the
					-
					-
						Lord of wealth, to him whom many praise, for help:
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 11
				-
					-
						To Agni Jatavedas, to the Son of Strength, that he may give us precious
						gifts,
					-
					-
						Immortal, from of old Priest among mortal men, the most delightful in the
						house.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Agni, made yours by sacrifice, Agni, while holy rites advance;
					-
					-
						Agni, the first in songs, first with the warrior steed; Agril to win the
						land for us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 13
				-
					-
						May Agni who is Lord of wealth vouchsafe us food for friendship sake.
					-
					-
						Agni we ever seek for seed and progeny, the Vasu who protects our lives.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Solicit with your chants, for help, Agni the God with piercing flame,
					-
					-
						For riches famous Agni, Purumilha and ye men! Agni to light our dwelling
						well.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 60: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Agni we laud that he may keep our foes afar, Agni to give us health and
						strength.
					-
					-
						Let him as Guardian be invoked in all the tribes, the lighter-up of glowing
						brands.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 61
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 1
				-
					-
						PREPARE oblation: let him come; and let the minister serve again
					-
					-
						Who knows the ordering thereof,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Rejoicing in his friendship, let the priest be seated over man,
					-
					-
						Beside the shoot of active power.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Him, glowing bright beyond all thought, they seek among the race of man;
					-
					-
						With him for tougue they seize the food.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 4
				-
					-
						He hath inflamed the twofold plain: lifegiving, he hath climbed the wood,
					-
					-
						And with his tongue hath struck the rock.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Wandering here the radiant Calf finds none to fetter him, and seeks
					-
					-
						The Mother to declare his praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 6
				-
					-
						And now that great and mighty team, the team of horses that are his,
					-
					-
						And traces of his car, are seen.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 7
				-
					-
						The seven milk a single cow; the two set other five to work,
					-
					-
						On the stream's loud-resounding bank.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Entreated by Vivasvan's ten, Indra cast down the water-jar
					-
					-
						With threefold hammer from the sky.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Three times the newIy-kindled flame proceeds around the sacrifice:
					-
					-
						The priests anoint it with the meath.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 10
				-
					-
						With reverence they drain the fount that circles with its wheel above,
					-
					-
						Exhaustless, with the mouth below.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 11
				-
					-
						The pressing-stones are set at work: the meath is poured into the tank,
					-
					-
						At the out-shedding of the fount.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Ye cows, protect the fount: the two Mighty Ones bless the sacrifice.
					-
					-
						The handles twain are wrought of gold.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Pour on the juice the ornament which reaches both the heaven and earth
					-
					-
						Supply the liquid to the Bull.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 14
				-
					-
						These know their own abiding-place: like calves beside the mother cows
					-
					-
						They meet together with their kin.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Devouring in their greedy jaws, they make sustaining food in heaven,
					-
					-
						To Indra, Agni light and prayer.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 16
				-
					-
						The Pious One milked out rich food, sustenance dealt in portions seven,
					-
					-
						Together with the Sun's seven rays.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 17
				-
					-
						I took some Soma when the Sun rose up, O Mitra, Varuna.
					-
					-
						That is the sick man's medicine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 61: Verse 18
				-
					-
						From where oblations must be laid, which is the Well-beloved's home,
					-
					-
						He with his tongue hath compassed heaven.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 62
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 1
				-
					-
						ROUSE ye for him who keeps the Law, yoke your steeds, Aiyins, to your car
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Come, Asvins, with your car more swift than is the twinkling of an eye
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Asvins, ye overlaid with cold the fiery pit for Atri's sake:
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Where are ye? whither are ye gone? whither, like falcons, have ye flown?
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 5
				-
					-
						If ye at any time this day are listening to this my call,
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 6
				-
					-
						The Asvins, fust to hear our prayer, for closest kinship I approach:
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 7
				-
					-
						For Atri ye, O Asvins, made a dwellingplace to shield him well,
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Ye warded off the fervent heat for Atri when he sweetly spake:
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Erst Saptavadbri by his prayer obtained the trenchant edge of fire:
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Come hither, O ye Lords of wealth, and listen to this call of mine:
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 11
				-
					-
						What is this praise told forth of you as Elders in the ancient way?
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 12
				-
					-
						One common brotherhood is yours, Asvins your kindred is the same:
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 13
				-
					-
						This is your chariot, Asvins, which speeds through the regions, earth and
						heaven
					-
					-
						Let your protecting aid be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Approach ye hitherward to us with thousands both of steeds and kine:
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Pass us not by, remember us with thousands both of kine aud steeds:
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 16
				-
					-
						The purple-tinted Dawn hath risen, and true to Law hath made the light
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 17
				-
					-
						He looked upon the Asvins, as an axearmed man upon a tree:
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 62: Verse 18
				-
					-
						By the black band encompassed round, break it down, bold one, like a fort.
					-
					-
						Let your protecting help be near.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 63
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 1
				-
					-
						EXERTING all our strength with thoughts of power we glorify in speech
					-
					-
						Agni your dear familiar Friend, the darling Guest in every home.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Whom, served with sacrificial oil like Mitra, men presenting gifts
					-
					-
						Eulogize with their songs of praise
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Much-lauded Jatavedas, him who bears oblations up to heaven
					-
					-
						Prepared in service of the Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 4
				-
					-
						To noblest Agni, Friend of man, best Vrtra-slayer, are we come,
					-
					-
						Him in whose presence Rksa's son, mighty Srutarvan, waxes great;
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 5
				-
					-
						To deathless Jatavedas, meet for praise, adored, with sacred oil,
					-
					-
						Visible through the gloom o:f night
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Even Agni whom these priestly men worship with sacrificial gifts,
					-
					-
						With lifted ladles offering them.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 7
				-
					-
						O Agni, this our newest hymn hath been addressed from us to thee,
					-
					-
						O cheerful Guest, well-born, most wise, worker of wonders, ne'er deceived.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Agni, may it be dear to thee, most grateful, and exceeding sweet:
					-
					-
						Grow mightier, eulogized therewith.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Splendid with splendours may it be, and in the battle with the foe
					-
					-
						Add loftier glory to thy fame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Steed, cow, a lord of heroes, bright like Indra, who shall fill the car.
					-
					-
						Whose high renown ye celebrate, and people praise each glorious deed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Thou whom Gopavana made glad with song, O Agni Angiras,
					-
					-
						Hear this my call, thou Holy One.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 12
				-
					-
						Thou whom the priestly folk implore to aid the gathering of the spoil,
					-
					-
						Such be thou in the fight with foes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 13
				-
					-
						I, called to him who reels with joy, Srutarvan, Rksa's son, shall stroke
					-
					-
						The heads of four presented steeds, like the long wool of fleecy rams.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Four coursers with a splendid car, Savistha's horses, fleet of foot,
					-
					-
						Shall bring me to the sacred feast, as flying steeds brought Tugra's son.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 63: Verse 15
				-
					-
						The very truth do I declare to thee, Parusni, mighty flood.
					-
					-
						Waters! no man is there who gives more horses than Savistha gives.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 64
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 1
				-
					-
						YOKE, Agni, as a charioteer, thy steeds who best invite the Gods: As
						ancient Herald seat thyself.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 2
				-
					-
						And, God, as skilfullest of all, call for us bitherward the Gods:
					-
					-
						Give all our wishes sure effect.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 3
				-
					-
						For thou, Most Youthful, Son of Strength, thou to whom sacrifice is paid,
					-
					-
						Art holy, faithful to the Law.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 4
				-
					-
						This Agni, Lord of wealth and spoil hundredfold, thousandfold, is head
					-
					-
						And chief of riches and a Sage.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 5
				-
					-
						As craftsmen bend the felly, so bend at our general call: come nigh,
					-
					-
						Angiras, to the sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Now, O Virupa, rouse for him, Strong God who shines at early morn,
					-
					-
						Fair praise with voice that ceases not.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 7
				-
					-
						With missile of this Agni, his who looks afar, will we lay low
					-
					-
						The thief in combat for the kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Let not the Companies of Gods fail us, like Dawns that float away,
					-
					-
						Like cows who leave the niggardly.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Let not the sinful tyranny of any fiercely hating foe
					-
					-
						Smite us, as billows smite a ship.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 10
				-
					-
						O Agni, God, the people sing reverent praise to thee for strength:
					-
					-
						With terrors trouble thou the foe.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Wilt thou not, Agni, lend us aid in winning cattle, winning wealth?
					-
					-
						Maker of room, make room for us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 12
				-
					-
						In this great battle cast us not aside as one who bears a load:
					-
					-
						Snatch up the wealih and win it all.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 13
				-
					-
						O Agni, let this plague pursue and fright another and not us:
					-
					-
						Make our impetuous strength more strong.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 14
				-
					-
						The reverent or unwearied man whose holy labour he accepts,
					-
					-
						Him Agni favours with success.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Abandoning the foeman's host pass hither to this company:
					-
					-
						Assist the men with whom I stand.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 64: Verse 16
				-
					-
						As we have known thy gracious help, as of a Father, long ago,
					-
					-
						So now we pray to thee for bliss.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 65
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 1
				-
					-
						NOT to forsake me, I invoke this Indra girt by Maruts,
					-
					-
						Lord Of magic power who rules with might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 2
				-
					-
						This Indra with his Marut Friends clave into pieces Vrtra's bead
					-
					-
						With hundred-knotted thunderbolt.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Indra, with Marut Friends grown strong, hath rent asunder Vrtra, and
					-
					-
						Released the waters of the sea.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 4
				-
					-
						This is that Indra who, begirt by Maruts, won the light of heaven
					-
					-
						That he might drink the Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Mighty, impetuous, begirt by Maruts, him who loudly roars,
					-
					-
						Indra we invocate with songs.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Indra begirt by Maruts we invoke after the ancient plan,
					-
					-
						That he may drink the Soma juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 7
				-
					-
						O liberal Indra, Marut-girt, much-lauded Satakratu, drink
					-
					-
						The Soma at this sacrifice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 8
				-
					-
						To thee, O Indra, Marut-girt, these Soma juices, Thunderer!
					-
					-
						Are offered from the heart with lauds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Drink, Indra, with thy Marut Friends, pressed Soma at the morning rites,
					-
					-
						Whetting thy thunderbolt with strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Arising in thy might, thy jaws thou shookest, Indra, having quaffed
					-
					-
						The Soma which the mortar pressed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Indra, both worlds complained to thee when uttering thy fearful roar,
					-
					-
						What time thou smotest Dasyus dead.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 65: Verse 12
				-
					-
						From Indra have I measured out a song eight-footed with nine parts,
					-
					-
						Delicate, faithful. to the Law.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 66
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 66: Verse 1
				-
					-
						SCARCELY was Satakratu, born when of his Mother he inquired,
					-
					-
						Who are the mighty? Who are famed?
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 66: Verse 2
