						grass.
					-
					-
						So, waxen mighty, to our eulogy from heaven come ye as wild-bulls to the
						pool.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 76: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Come to us, O ye Asvins, now with steeds of many a varied hue,
					-
					-
						Ye Lords of splendour, wondrous, borne on paths of gold, drink Soma, ye who
						strengthen Law.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 76: Verse 6
				-
					-
						For we the priestly singers, fain tohymn your praise, invoke you for the
						gain of strength.
					-
					-
						So, wondrous, fair, and famed for great deeds come to us, through our hymn,
						Asvins, when ye hear.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 77
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 77: Verse 1
				-
					-
						As cows low to their calves in stalls, so with our songs we glorify
					-
					-
						This Indra, even your Wondrous God who checks attack, who joys in the
						delicious juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 77: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Celestial, bounteous Giver, girt about with might, rich, mountain-like, in
						precious things,
					-
					-
						Him swift we seek. for foodful booty rich in kine, brought hundredfold and
						thousandfold.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 77: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Indra, the strong and lofty hills are powerless to bar thy way.
					-
					-
						None stay that act of thine when thou wouldst fain give wealth to one like
						me who sings thy praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 77: Verse 4
				-
					-
						A Warrior thou by strength, wisdom, and wondrous deed, in might excellest
						all that is.
					-
					-
						Hither may this our hymn attract thee to our help, the hymn which Gotamas
						have made.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 77: Verse 5
				-
					-
						For in thy might thou stretchest out beyond the boundaries of heaven.
					-
					-
						The earthly region, Indra, comprehends thee not. After thy Godhead hast
						thou waxed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 77: Verse 6
				-
					-
						When, Maghavan, thou honourest the worshipper, no one is there to stay thy
						wealth.
					-
					-
						Most liberal Giver thou, do thou inspire our song of praise, that we may
						win the spoil.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 78
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 78: Verse 1
				-
					-
						To Indra sing the lofty hymn, Maruts that slays the Vrtras best.
					-
					-
						Whereby the Holy Ones created for the God the light divine that ever wakes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 78: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Indra who quells the curse blew curses far away, and then in splendour came
						to us.
					-
					-
						Indra, refulgent with thy Marut host! the Gods strove eagerly to win thy
						love.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 78: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Sing to your lofty Indra, sing, Maruts, a holy hymn of praise.
					-
					-
						Let Satakratu, Vrtra-slayer, kill the foe with hundred-knotted thunderbolt.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 78: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Aim and fetch boldly forth, O thou whose heart is bold: great glory will be
						thine thereby.
					-
					-
						In rapid torrent let the mother waters spread. Slay Vrtra, win the light of
						heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 78: Verse 5
				-
					-
						When thou, unequalled Maghavan, wast born to smite the Vrtras dead,
					-
					-
						Thou spreadest out the spacious earth and didst support and prop the
						heavens.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 78: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Theri was the sacrifice produced for thee, the laud, and song of joy,
					-
					-
						Thou in thy might surpassest all, all that now is and yet shall be.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 78: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Raw kine thou filledst with ripe milk. Thou madest Surya rise to heaven.,
					-
					-
						Heat him as milk is heated with pure Sama hymns, great joy to him who loves
						the song.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 79
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 79: Verse 1
				-
					-
						MAY Indra, who in every fight must be invoked, be near to us.
					-
					-
						May the most mighty Vrtra-slayer, meet for praise, come to libations and to
						hymns.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 79: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Thou art the best of all in sending bounteous gifts, true art thou, lordly
						in thine act.
					-
					-
						We claim alliance with the very Glorious One, yea, with the Mighty Son of
						Strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 79: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Prayers unsurpassed are offered up to thee the Lover of the Song.
					-
					-
						Indra, Lord of Bay Steeds, accept these fitting hymns, hymns which we have
						thought out for thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 79: Verse 4
				-
					-
						For thou, O Maghavan, art truthful, ne'er subdued and bringest many a Vrtra
						low.
					-
					-
						As such, O Mightiest Lord, Wielder of Thunder, send wealth hither to the
						worshipper.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 79: Verse 5
				-
					-
						O Indra, thou art far-renowned, impetuous, O Lord of Strength.
					-
					-
						Alone thou slayest with the guardian of mankind resistless never-conquered
						foes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 79: Verse 6
				-
					-
						As such we seek thee now, O Asura, thee most wise, craving thy bounty as
						our share.
					-
					-
						Thy sheltering defence is like a mighty cloak. So may thy glories reach to
						us.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 80
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 80: Verse 1
				-
					-
						DOWN to the stream a maiden came, and found the Soma by the way.
					-
					-
						Bearing it to her home she said, For Indra will I press thee out, for Sakra
						will I press thee out.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 80: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Thou roaming yonder, little man, beholding every house in turn,
					-
					-
						Drink thou this Soma pressed with teeth, accompanied with grain and curds,
						with cake of meal and song of praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 80: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Fain would we learn to know thee well, nor yet can we attain to thee.
					-
					-
						Still slowly and in gradual drops, O Indu, unto Indra flow.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 80: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Will he not help and work for us? Will he not make us wealthier?
					-
					-
						Shall we not, hostile to our lord, unite ourselves to Indra now?
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 80: Verse 5
				-
					-
						O Indra, cause to sprout again three places, these which I declare,-
					-
					-
						My father's head, his cultured field, and this the part below my waist.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 80: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Make all of these grow crops of hair, you cultivated field of ours,
					-
					-
						My body, and my father's head.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 80: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Cleansing Apala, Indra! thrice, thou gavest sunlike skin to her,
					-
					-
						Drawn, Satakratu! through the hole of car, of wagon, and of yoke.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 81
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 1
				-
					-
						INVITE ye Indra with a song to drink your draught of Soma juice,
					-
					-
						All-conquering Satakratu, most munificent of all who live.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Lauded by many, much-invoked, leader of song, renowned of old:
					-
					-
						His name is Indra, tell it forth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Indra the Dancer be to us the giver of abundant strength:
					-
					-
						May he, the mighty, bring it near.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Indra whose jaws are strong hath drunk of worshipping Sudaksa's draught,
					-
					-
						The Soma juice with barley mixt.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Call Indra loudly with your songs of praise to drink the Soma juice.
					-
					-
						For this is what augments his stiength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 6
				-
					-
						When he hath drqnk its gladdening drops, the God with vigour of a God
					-
					-
						Hath far surpassed all things that are.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Thou speedest down to succour us this ever-conquering God of yours,
					-
					-
						Him who is drawn to all our songs
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 8
				-
					-
						The Warrior not to he restrained, the Soma-drinker ne'er o'erthrown,
					-
					-
						The Chieftain of resistless might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 9
				-
					-
						O Indra, send us riches, thou Omniscient, worthy of our praise:
					-
					-
						Help us in the decisive fray.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Even thence, O 1ndra, come to us with food that gives a hundred powers,
					-
					-
						With food that gives a thousand powers.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 11
				-
					-
						We sought the wisdom of the wise. Sakra, Kine-giver, Thunder-armed!
					-
					-
						May we with steeds o'ercome in fight.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 12
				-
					-
						We make thee, Satakratu, find enjoyment in the songs we sing.
					-
					-
						Like cattle in the pasture lands.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 13
				-
					-
						For, Satakratu, Thunder-armed, all that we craved, as men are wont,
					-
					-
						All that we hoped, have we attained.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 14
				-
					-
						Those, Son of Strength, are come to thee who cherish wishes in their hearts
					-
					-
						O Indra, none excelleth thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 15
				-
					-
						So, Hero, guard us with thy care, with thy most liberal providence,
					-
					-
						Speedy, and terrible to foes.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 16
				-
					-
						O Satakratu Indra, now rejoice with that carouse of thine
					-
					-
						Which is most splendid of them all
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 17
				-
					-
						Even, Indra, that carouse which slays the Vrtras best, most widely famed,
					-
					-
						Best giver of thy power and might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 18
				-
					-
						For that which is thy gift we know, true Soma-drinker, Thunder-armed,
					-
					-
						Mighty One, amid all the folk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 19
				-
					-
						For Indra, Lover of Carouse, loud be our songs about the juice:
					-
					-
						Let poets sing the song of praise.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 20
				-
					-
						We summon Indra to the draught, irl whom all glories rest, in whom
					-
					-
						The seven communities rejoice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 21
				-
					-
						At the Trikadrukas the Gods span sacrifice that stirs the mind:
					-
					-
						Let our songs aid and prosper it.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 22
				-
					-
						Let the drops pass within thee as the rivers flow into the sea:
					-
					-
						O fndra, naught excelleth thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 23
				-
					-
						Thou, wakeful Hero, by thy might hast taken food of Soma juice,
					-
					-
						Which, Indra, is within thee now.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 24
				-
					-
						O Indra, Vrtra-slayer, let Soma be ready for thy maw,
					-
					-
						The drops be ready for thy forms.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 25
				-
					-
						Now Srutakaksa sings his song that cattle and the steed may come,
					-
					-
						That Indra's very self may come.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 26
				-
					-
						Here, Indra, thou art ready by our Soma juices shed for thee,
					-
					-
						Sakra, at hand that thou mayst give.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 27
				-
					-
						Even from far away our songs reach thee, O Caster of the Stone:
					-
					-
						May we come very close to thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 28
				-
					-
						For so thou art the hero's Friend, a Hero, too, art thou, and strong:
					-
					-
						So may thine heart be won to us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 29
				-
					-
						So hath the offering, wealthiest Lord, been paid by all the worshippers:
					-
					-
						So dwell thou, Indra, even with me.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 30
				-
					-
						Be not thou like a slothfid priest, O Lord of spoil and wealth: rejoice
					-
					-
						In the pressed Soma blent with milk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 31
				-
					-
						O Indra, let not ill designs surround us in the sunbeams' light:
					-
					-
						This may we gain with thee for Friend.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 32
				-
					-
						With thee to help us, Indra, let us answer all our enemies:
					-
					-
						For thou art ours and we are thine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 81: Verse 33
				-
					-
						Indra, the poets and thy friends, faithful to thee, shall loudly sing
					-
					-
						Thy praises as they follow thee.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 82
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 1
				-
					-
						SURYA, thou mountest up to meet the Hero famous for his wealth,
					-
					-
						Who hurls the bolt and works for man
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Him who with might of both his arms brake nine-and-ninety castles down,
					-
					-
						Slew Vrtra and smote Ahi dead.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 3
				-
					-
						This Indra is our gracious Friend. He sends us in a full broad stream
					-
					-
						Riches in horses, kine, and corn.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Whatever, Vrtra-slayer! thou, Surya, hast risen upon to-day,
					-
					-
						Tbat, Indra, all is in thy power.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 5
				-
					-
						When, Mighty One, Lord of the brave, thou thinkest thus, I shall not die,
					-
					-
						That thought of thine is true indeed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Thou, Indra, goest unto all Soma libations shed for thee,
					-
					-
						Both far away and near at hand.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 7
				-
					-
						We make this Indra very strong to strike the mighty Vrtra dead:
					-
					-
						A vigorous Hero shall he be.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Indra was made for giving, set, most mighty, o'er the joyous draught.
					-
					-
						Bright, meet for Soma, famed in song.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 9
				-
					-
						By song as 'twere, the powerful bolt which none may parry was prepared
					-
					-
						Lofty, invincible he grew.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Indra, Song-lover, lauded, make even in the wilds fair ways for us,
					-
					-
						Whenever, Maghavan, thou wilt.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 11
				-
					-
						Thou whose commandment and behest of sovran sway none disregards,
					-
					-
						Neither audacious man nor God.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 12
				-
					-
						And both these Goddesses, Earth, Heaven, Lord of the beauteous helm! revere
					-
					-
						Thy might which no one may resist.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 13
				-
					-
						Thou in the black cows and the red and in the cows with spotted skin
					-
					-
						This white milk hast deposited.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 14
				-
					-
						When in their terror all the Gods shrank from the Dragon's furious might,
					-
					-
						Fear of the monster fell on them.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 15
				-
					-
						Then he was my Defender, then, Invincible, whose foe is not,
					-
					-
						The Vrtra-slayer showed his might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 16
				-
					-
						Him your best Vrtra-slayer, him the famous Champion of mankind
					-
					-
						I urge to great munificence,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 17
				-
					-
						To come, Much-lauded! Many-named with this same thought that longs for
						milk,
					-
					-
						Whene'er the Soma juice is shed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 18
				-
					-
						Much-honoured by libations, may the Vrtra-slayer wake for us:
					-
					-
						May Sakra listen to our prayers.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 19
				-
					-
						O Hero, with that aid dost thou delight us, with what succour bring
					-
					-
						Riches to those who worship thee?
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 20
				-
					-
						With whose libation joys the Strong, the Hero with his team who quells
					-
					-
						The foe, to drink the Soma juice?
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 82: Verse 21
				-
					-
						Rejoicing in thy spirit bring thousandfold opulence to us:
					-
					-
						Enrich thy votary with gifts.
