					-
					-
						With whom thou silencest the enemy of man, with whon; thou goest round the
						sky.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 9
				-
					-
						O gracious Hero, may we learn anew to know thee as thou art:
					-
					-
						As in decisive fight thou holpest Etasa, or Vasa 'gainst Dasavraja,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 94: Verse 10
				-
					-
						As, Maghavan, to Kanva at the sacred feast, to Dirghanitha thine
						home-friend,
					-
					-
						As to Gosarya thou, Stone-darter, gavest wealth, give me a gold-bright
						stall of kine.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 95
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 1
				-
					-
						As with Manu Samvarani, Indra, thou drankest Soma juice,
					-
					-
						And, Maghavan, with Nipatithi, Medbyatithi, with Pustigu and Srustigu,-
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 2
				-
					-
						T'he son of Prsadvana was Praskaniva's host, who lay decrepit and forlorn.
					-
					-
						Aided by thee the Rsi Dasyave-vrka strove to obtain thousands of kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Call hither with thy newest song Indra who lacks not hymns of praise,
					-
					-
						Him who observes and knows, inspirer of the sage, him who seems eager to
						enjoy.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 4
				-
					-
						He unto whom they sang the seven-headed hymn, three-parted, in the loftiest
						place,
					-
					-
						He sent his thunder down on all these living things, and so displayed
						heroic might.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 5
				-
					-
						We invocate that Indra who bestoweth precious things on us.
					-
					-
						Now do we know his newest favour; may we gain a stable that is full of
						kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 6
				-
					-
						He whom thou aidest, gracious Lord, to give again, obtains great wealth to
						nourish him.
					-
					-
						We with our Soma ready, Lover of the Song! call, Indra Maghavan, on thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Ne'er art thou fruitless, Indra ne'er dost thou desert the worshipper
					-
					-
						But now, O Maghavan, thy bounty as a God is poured forth ever more and
						more.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 8
				-
					-
						He who hath. overtaken Krvi with his might, and silenced Susna with
						deathbolts,-
					-
					-
						When he supported yonder heaven and spread it out, then first the son of
						earth was born.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Good Lord of wealth is he to whom all Aryas, Dasas here belong.
					-
					-
						Directly unto thee, the pious Rusama Paviru, is that wealth brought nigh.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 95: Verse 10
				-
					-
						In zealous haste the singers have sung forth a song distilling oil and rich
						in sweets.
					-
					-
						Riches have spread among us and heroic strength, with us are flowing
						Soma-drops.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 96
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 1
				-
					-
						As, Sakra, thou with Manu called Vivasvan drankest Soma juice,
					-
					-
						As, Indra, thou didst love the hymn by Trita's side, so dost thou joy with
						Ayu now.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 2
				-
					-
						As thou with Matarisvan, Medhya, Prsadhra, hast cheered thee Indra, with
						pressed juice,
					-
					-
						Drunk Soma with Rjunas, Syumarasmi, by Dasonya's Dasasipra's side.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 3
				-
					-
						'Tis he who made the lauds his own and boldly drank the Soma juice,
					-
					-
						He to whom Visnu came striding his three wide steps, as Mitra's statutes
						ordered it.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 4
				-
					-
						In whose laud thou didst joy, Indra, at the great deed, O Satakratu, Mighty
						One!
					-
					-
						Seeking renown we call thee as the milkers call the cow who yields abundant
						milk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 5
				-
					-
						He is our Sire who gives to us, Great, Mighty, ruling as he wills.
					-
					-
						Unsought, may he the Strong, Rich, Lord of ample wealth, give us of horses
						and of kine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 6
				-
					-
						He to whom thou, Good Lord, givest that he may give increases wealth that
						nourishes.
					-
					-
						Eager for wealth we call on Indra, Lord of wealth, on Satakratu with our
						lauds.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Never art thou neglectful: thou guardest both races with thy care.
					-
					-
						The call on Indra, fourth Aditya! is thine own. Amrta is stablished in the
						heavens.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 8
				-
					-
						The offercr whom thou, Indra, Lover of the Song, liberal Maghavan,
						favourest,-
					-
					-
						As at the call of Kanva so, O gracious Lord, hear, thou our songs and
						eulogy.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Sung is the song of ancient time: to Indra have ye said the prayer.
					-
					-
						They have sung many a Brhati of sacrifice, poured forth the worshipper's
						many thoughts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 96: Verse 10
				-
					-
						Indra hath tossed together mighty stores of wealth, and both the worlds,
						yea, and the Sun.
					-
					-
						Pure, brightly-shining, mingled with the milk, the draughts of Soma have
						made Indra glad.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 97
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 97: Verse 1
				-
					-
						As highest of the Maghavans, preeminent among the Bulls,
					-
					-
						Best breaker-down of forts, kine-winner, Lord of wealth, we seek thee,
						Indra Maghavan.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 97: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Thou who subduedst Ayu, Kutsa, Atithigva, waxing daily in thy might,
					-
					-
						As such, rousing thy power, we invocate thee now, thee Satakratu, Lord of
						Bays.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 97: Verse 3
				-
					-
						The pressing-stones shall pour for us the essence of the meath of all,
					-
					-
						Drops that have been pressed out afar among the folk, and those that have
						been pressed near us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 97: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Repel all enmities and keep thern far away: let all win treasure for their
						own.
					-
					-
						Even among Sistas are the stalks that make thee glad, where thou with Soma
						satest thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 97: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Come, Indra, very near to us with aids of firmly-based resolve;
					-
					-
						Come, most auspicious, with thy most auspicious help, good Kinsman, with
						good kinsmen, come!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 97: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Bless thou with progeny the chief of men, the lord of heroes, victor in the
						fray.
					-
					-
						Aid with thy powers the men who sing thee lauds and keep their spirits ever
						pure and bright.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 97: Verse 7
				-
					-
						May we be such in battle as are surest to obtain thy grace:
					-
					-
						With holy offerings and invocations of the Gods, we mean, that we may win
						the spoil.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 97: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Thine, Lord of Bays, am I. Prayer longeth for the spoil. Still with thy
						help I seek the fight.
					-
					-
						So, at the raiders' head, I, craving steeds and kine, unite myself with
						thee alone.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 98
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 98: Verse 1
				-
					-
						INDRA, the poets with. their hymns extol this hero might of thine:
					-
					-
						They strengthened, loud in song, thy power that droppeth oil. With hymns
						the Pauras came to thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 98: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Through piety they came to Indra for his aid, they whose libations give
						theejoy.
					-
					-
						As thou with, Krsa and Samvarta hast rejoiced, so, Indra, be thou glad with
						us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 98: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Agreeing in your spirit, all ye Deities, come nigh to us.
					-
					-
						Vasus and Rudras shall come near to give us aid, and Maruts listen to our
						call.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 98: Verse 4
				-
					-
						May Pusan, Visnu, and Sarasvati befriend, and the Seven Streams, this call
						of mine:
					-
					-
						May Waters, Wind, the Mountains, and the Forest-Lord, and Earth give ear
						unto my cry.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 98: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Indra, with thine own bounteous gift, most liberal of the Mighty Ones,
					-
					-
						Be our boon benefactor, Vrtra-slayer, be our feast-companion for our weal.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 98: Verse 6
				-
					-
						Leader of heroes, Lord of battle, lead thou us to combat, thou Most Sapient
						One.
					-
					-
						High fame is theirs who win by invocations, feasts and entertainment of the
						Gods.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 98: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Our hopes rest on the Faithful One: in Indra is the people's life.
					-
					-
						O Maghavan, come nigh that thou mayst give us aid: make plenteous food
						stream forth for us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 98: Verse 8
				-
					-
						Thee would we worship, Indra, with our songs of praise: O Satakratu, be
						thou ours.
					-
					-
						Pour down upon Praskanva bounty vast and firm, exuberant, that shall never
						fail.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 99
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 99: Verse 1
				-
					-
						GREAT, verily, is Indra's might. I have beheld, and hither comes
					-
					-
						Thy bounty, Dasyave-vrka!
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 99: Verse 2
				-
					-
						A hundred oxen white of hue are shining like the stars in heaven,
					-
					-
						So tall, they seem to prop the sky.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 99: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Bamboos a hundred, a hundred dogs, a hundred skins of beasts well-tanned,
					-
					-
						A hundred tufts of Balbaja, four hundred red-hued mares are mine.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 99: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Blest by the Gods, Kinvayanas! be ye who spread through life on life:
					-
					-
						Like horses have ye stridden forth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 99: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Then men extolled the team of seven not yet full-grown, its fame is great.
					-
					-
						The dark mares rushed along the paths, so that no eye could follow them.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 100
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 100: Verse 1
				-
					-
						THY bounty, Dasyave-vrka, exhaustless hath displayed itself:
					-
					-
						Its fulness is as broad as heaven.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 100: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Ten thousand Dasyave-vrka, the son of Putakrata, hath
					-
					-
						From his own wealth bestowed on me.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 100: Verse 3
				-
					-
						A hundred asses hath he given, a hundred head of fleecy sheep,
					-
					-
						A hundred slaves, and wreaths besides.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 100: Verse 4
				-
					-
						There also was a mare led forth, picked out for Putakrata's sake,
					-
					-
						Not of the horses of the herd.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 100: Verse 5
				-
					-
						Observant Agni hath appeared, oblation-bearer with his car.
					-
					-
						Agni with his resplendent flame hath shone on high as shines the Sun, hath
						shone like Surya in theheavens.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 101
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 101: Verse 1
				-
					-
						ENDOWED, O Gods, with your primeval wisdom, come quickly with your chariot,
						O ye Holy.
					-
					-
						Come with your mighty powers, O ye Nasatyas; come hither, drink ye this the
						third libation.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 101: Verse 2
				-
					-
						The truthful Deities, the Three-and-Thirty, saw you approach before the
						Ever-Truthful.
					-
					-
						Accepting this our worship and libation, O Asvins bright with fire, drink
						ye the Soma.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 101: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Asvins, that work of yours deserves our wonder,-the Bull of heaven and
						earth and air's mid region;
					-
					-
						Yea, and your thousand promises in battle, -to all of these come near and
						drink beside us.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 101: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Here is your portion laid for you, ye Holy: come to these songs of ours, O
						ye Nasatyas.
					-
					-
						Drink among us the Soma full of sweetness, and with your powers assist the
						man who worships.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 102
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 102: Verse 1
				-
					-
						HE whom the priests in sundry ways arranging the sacrifice, of one accord,
						bring hither,
					-
					-
						Who was appointed as a learned Brahman, -what is the sacrificer's knowledge
						of him?
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 102: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Kindled in many a spot, still One is Agni; Silrya is One though high o'er
						all he shineth.
					-
					-
						Illumining this All, still One is usas. That which is One hath into All
						developed.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 102: Verse 3
				-
					-
						The chariot bright and radiant, treasure-laden, three-wheeled, with easy
						seat, and lightly rolling,
					-
					-
						Which She of Wondrous Wealth was born to harness,-this car of yours I call.
						Drink what remaineth.
					-
			-
				Mandala 8: Hymn 103
			-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 103: Verse 1
				-
					-
						IN offerings poured to you, O Indra-Varuna, these shares of yours stream
						forth to glorify your state.
					-
					-
						Ye haste to the libations at each sacrifice when ye assist the worshipper
						who sheds the juice.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 103: Verse 2
				-
					-
						The waters and the plants, O Indra-Varuna, had efficacious vigour, and
						attained to might:
					-
					-
						Ye who have gone beyond the path of middle air,-no godless man is worthy to
						be called your foe.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 103: Verse 3
				-
					-
						True is your Krsa's word, Indra and Varuna: The seven holy voices pour a
						wave of meath.
					-
					-
						For their sake, Lords of splendour! aid the pious man who, unbewildered,
						keeps you ever in his thoughts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 103: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Dropping oil, sweet with Soma, pouring forth their stream, are the Seven
						Sisters in the seat of sacrifice.
					-
					-
						These, dropping oil, are yours, O Indra-Varuna: with these enrich with
						gifts and help the worshipper.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 103: Verse 5
				-
					-
						To our great happiness have we ascribed to these Two Bright Ones
						truthfulness, great strength, and majesty.
					-
					-
						O Lords of splendour, aid us through the Three-times-Seven, as we pour holy
						oil, O Indra-Varuna.
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 103: Verse 6
				-
					-
						What ye in time of old Indra and Varuna, gave Rsis revelation, thought, and
						power of song,
					-
					-
						And places which the wise made, weaving sacrifice,-these through my
						spirit's fervid glow have I beheld.,
					-
				-
					Mandala 8: Hymn 103: Verse 7
				-
					-
						O Indra-Varuna, grant to the worshippers cheerfulness void of pride, and
						wealth to nourish them.
					-
		-
			Mandala 9
		-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 1
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 1: Verse 1
				-
					-
						In sweetest and most gladdening stream
					-
					-
						flow pure, O Soma, on thy way,
					-
					-
						Pressed out for Indra, for his drink.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 1: Verse 2
				-
					-
						Fiend-queller, Friend of all men, he hath with the wood attained unto
					-
					-
						His place, his iron-fashioned home.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 1: Verse 3
				-
					-
						Be thou best Vrtra-slayer, best granter of bliss, most liberal:
					-
					-
						Promote our wealthy princes' gifts.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 1: Verse 4
				-
					-
						Flow onward with thy juice unto the banquet of the Mighty Gods:
					-
					-
						Flow bither for our strength and fame.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 1: Verse 5
				-
					-
						O Indu, we draw nigh to thee, with this one object day by day:
					-
					-
						To thee alone our prayers are said
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 1: Verse 6
				-
					-
						By means of this eternal fleece may Surya's Daughter purify
					-
					-
						Thy Soma that is foaming forth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 1: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Ten sister maids of slender form seize him within the press and hold
					-
					-
						Him firmly on the final day.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 1: Verse 8
				-
					-
						The virgins send him forth: they blow the the skin musician-like and fuse
					-
					-
						The triple foe-repelling meath.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 1: Verse 9
				-
					-
						Inviolable milch-kine round about him blend for Indra's drink,
					-
					-
						The fresh young Soma with their milk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 1: Verse 10
				-
					-
						In the wild raptures of this draught, Indra slays all the Vrtras: he,
					-
					-
						The Hero, pours his wealth on us.
					-
			-
				Mandala 9: Hymn 2
			-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 2: Verse 1
				-
					-
						Soma, flow on, inviting Gods, speed to the purifying cloth:
					-
					-
						Pass into Indra, as a Bull.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 2: Verse 2
				-
					-
						As mighty food speed hitherward, Indu, as a most splendid Steer:
					-
					-
						Sit in thy place as one with strength.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 2: Verse 3
				-
					-
						The well-loved meath was made to flow, the stream of the creative juice
					-
					-
						ne Sage drew waters to himself.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 2: Verse 4
				-
					-
						The mighty waters, yea, the floods accompany thee Mighty One,
					-
					-
						When thou wilt clothe thee with the milk.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 2: Verse 5
				-
					-
						The lake is brightened in the floods. Soma, our Friend, heaven's prop and
						stay,
					-
					-
						Falls on the purifying cloth.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 2: Verse 6
				-
					-
						The tawny Bull hath bellowed, fair as mighty Mitra to behold:
					-
					-
						He shines together with the Sun.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 2: Verse 7
				-
					-
						Songs, Indu, active in their might are beautified for thee, wherewith
					-
					-
						Thou deckest thee for our delight.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 2: Verse 8
				-
					-
						To thee who givest ample room we pray, to win the joyous draught:
					-
					-
						Great are the praises due to thee.
					-
				-
					Mandala 9: Hymn 2: Verse 9
				-
					-
